<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0747 04-09 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs separate on Dorrance moved as a0752.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>John Dorrance</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John T. Dorrance, Jr., chairman of the
executive committee of Campbell Soup Co.'s board of directors and
former chairman of the board, died Sunday of an apparent heart
attack. He was 70.
   Dorrance joined Campbell in 1946 after serving in the Army
during World War II. He spent 16 years working in different
departments of the company, including a stint as a floor foreman in
the Camden plant.
   He was elected to Campbell's board of directors in 1947 and was
elected chairman of the board in 1962. He retired in 1984 and was
elected chairman of the board's executive committee.
   Dorrance, who lived in Gladwyne, Pa., is survived by his wife,
Diana, and three children.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Harold Saidt</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold N. ``Bus'' Saidt, a
longtime sports writer and columnist for The Times of Trenton, died
Saturday of an apparent heart attack. He was 68.
   Saidt graduated from Rider College in 1940 with a bachelor's
degree in accounting, and worked for 25 years as a senior municipal
accountant for the city.
   From 1947 to 1969 he was sports director of radio stadion WBUD
in Trenton, where he had a 15-minute sports show. He gave local and
national scores and commentary.
   In 1964, Saidt started writing for The Trentonian, where he
remained until 1967 when he moved to The Times as sports columnist.
   In 1974, 1984 and 1986, Saidt was named New Jersey Sports Writer
of the Year by the National Sportswriters and Sportscasters
Association.
   Saidt is survived by his wife, Helen Martin Saidt, a sister, and
two stepsons.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Betty Farrally</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Betty Farrally, co-founder of
Canada's oldest dance company, died Sunday in Kelowna at age 73
after a long bout with with brain cancer.
   She and her former teacher and lifetime companion, Gweneth
Lloyd, founded the Royal Winnipeg Ballet 50 years ago.
   The two women emigrated to Canada from England shortly before
World War II, started a dance studio and developed the company from
a performance club for their best students.
   Lloyd was artistic director and chief choreographer, while
Farrally was principal dancer and ballet mistress.
   Farrally became artistic director of the company in the early
1950s, then left in 1954 to join Lloyd in establishing a teaching
business in Kelowna, about 170 miles northeast of Vancouver.
</TEXT>
