<DOCNO> AP890410-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 0051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion-CrowdSize     04-10 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Crowd Size,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organizers Dispute Police Estimate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of the abortion rights march on the
nation's Capitol fumed at a police estimate that put their crowd of
supporters at only 300,000.
   ``We aren't going to let them deny us our numbers,'' said
Eleanor Smeal, president of the Fund for the Feminist Majority and
one of the march organizers who claim more than 600,000 people
turned out for Sunday's rally.
   Both estimates showed the demonstration was larger than the
approximately 250,000 people organizers had predicted would turn
out, but still supporters felt cheated by the police estimate.
   ``This was no ordinary march. We took over the city,'' Smeal
said during the rally that closed down the streets around the
Capitol and the Mall and flooded the West side of the Capitol with
activists.
   She suggested that Bush administration politics were at play,
noting that the U.S. Park Police, one of three law enforcement
authorities involved in making the estimate, ``report to the White
House.''
   ``They always low-ball our numbers,'' she added.
   Smeal said march organizers, which included the National
Organization for Women and Planned Parenthood, consulted with
architectural and landscape engineers in coming up with their
figure of 600,000.
   The 300,000 estimate was made jointly by the U.S. Park Police,
which has jurisdiction over federal property; the U.S. Capitol
Police, whose force covers the Capitol grounds; and the District of
Columbia Metropolitan Police, who cover city properties.
   ``The three police agencies are very good at estimating crowds
because we do it so often,'' said Dan Nichols, a spokesman for the
Capitol Police.
   He and Michael Braxton, a spokesman for the Park Police,
dismissed suggestions that their count was politically motivated.
   ``All we do is give an accurate count,'' Braxton said,
explaining that in this march as in most large rallies officers
view the crowd from helicopters and then estimate the size based on
grid maps, which divide the area into sections.
   ``It doesn't make any difference to us how many turn out,''
Nichols said. ``We don't have anything to gain or lose.''
   He added that rally organizers invariably dispute police crowd
estimates, but he said that because Sunday's march was so large
``it leaves more room for a gap.''
</TEXT>
