<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion-Generations     04-10 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Generations,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Generations of Family Take Part in Abortion Rights March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mothers, daughters and even granddaughters
took their places in the massive march on the nation's Capitol as
generations joined the show of solidarity for a woman's right to
choose an abortion.
   Norma Melbourne, who took her daughter Dylan to the women's
rights march in New York City back in August 1970, joined both her
daughter and her 2-year-old granddaughter, Honore Ford, at Sunday's
demonstration that attracted more than 300,000 from the Washington
Monument to the steps of the Capitol. Organizers estimated the
turnout at closer to 600,000.
   ``We're here so she'll never have to come again,'' Dylan
Melbourne of Gaithersburg, Md., said of the fair-haired toddler
seated quietly in her stroller.
   ``We have taken it for granted that they had choices,'' said
Norma Melbourne.
   She recalled stories of ``little places in Pennsylvania and
Mexico'' where women had to go to obtain abortions before the
Supreme Court decision in Roe vs. Wade in 1973.
   Patricia Rocket, 61, of Lewes, Del., also has heard the stories
of back-alley abortions and brought her 81-year-old mother, Evelyn
Pope, to protest any possible change in the law.
   ``It scares me to death to think of going back to before Roe vs.
Wade,'' Rocket said.
   Nearby, Ella Byrnes, also 81, of Muncie, Ind., raised a homemade
sign which said ``Indiana Republicans for Choice,'' and in smaller
letters claimed that former President Reagan was pro-choice.
   ``My mother was in a class ahead of Reagan's at Eureka
College,'' said Barbara Maves, who said that Reagan, as president
of the student council, was a big supporter of individual rights.
   ``The Republican philosophy is basically individual rights,''
said Nancy Grundmann, of Kokomo, Ind., who left her home at 4 a.m.
Saturday to make the march. ``I wanted the rest of the United
States to know many Republicans are pro-choice.''
</TEXT>
