<FIRST>r w PM-AbortionRally-Notebook     04-10 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Rally-Notebook,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Jane Roe' of Landmark Abortion Decision Sheds Anonymity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She looked like just one of the hundreds of
thousands of other demonstrators at the Capitol, wearing a blue
sweatshirt with the words ``Roe v. Wade'' and a drawing of the
Supreme Court.
   By name, Norma McCorvey is just as anonymous.
   But she is also Jane Roe _ as in Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 Supreme
Court case that resulted in the landmark decision legalizing
abortion. And she's still speaking out, despite a recent shotgun
blast to her Texas home.
   ``Our law's in jeopardy,'' she told a handful of reporters at
Sunday's abortion rights rally, organized to focus attention on a
major challenge to the Roe vs. Wade ruling that is being considered
by the Supreme Court.
   For most of the afternoon, McCorvey simply sat at the foot of
the Capitol with a few friends, barely noticed by the hundreds of
Hollywood stars, rally volunteers and politicians who filled the
stage.
   For her, the attention she did get was almost too much.
   ``She's shaking,'' said Gloria Allred, a women's rights attorney
from Los Angeles who sat by McCorvey's side. ``She's not used to
all of this.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   For Beth Shafran, a 31-year-old law student from San Francisco,
women's abortion rights were more important than her bar exam.
   ``I blew my bar exam money to do this,'' she said after Sunday's
rally, for which she flew across the country to attend.
   ``It was so important, especially with the Supreme Court hearing
the Webster case so soon,'' she said, referring to a Missouri case
before the court that could lead the justices to restrict abortion
rights.
   After being part of the demonstration with several hundred
thousand other women's rights activists, she said it was worth the
sacrifice.
   ``I'll wait another six months'' to take the exam, she said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Actress Cybill Shepherd said she was embarrassed to admit that
Sunday's abortion rights march was the first big demonstration
she's participated in.
   But when it came her turn to address the sea of people assembled
on the Capitol lawn and the adjacent Mall, she seemed a pro.
   ``I wanted my children, but no one has the right to force me to
have an unwanted child,'' she boomed to the crowd.
   Still, she bore the polish of Hollywood, wearing a long white
coat over a white blouse and purple sweatshirt _ the colors of the
march in honor of the suffragettes _ and carrying a Japanese-style
parasol.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I don't think this is just a women's issue,'' said Leonard
Nimoy, remembered as the Mr. Spock of ``Star Trek'' fame.
   Sporting an ``Honorary Sister'' pin on his white sweatshirt,
Nimoy said he grew up when abortions were illegal and remembers the
stories of women having the procedures performed ``on kitchen
tables.''
   ``Nobody likes the idea of an abortion,'' said Nimoy, one of
dozens of celebrities who traveled to Washington for the rally.
``But if it has to happen, there should be freedom of choice.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Actress Valerie Harper was the last of the Hollywood contingent
to address the rally. Wearing a white dress and light sweater, she
was shivering against late afternoon cold as she walked from the
stage. But when asked to stay a few minutes longer to answer some
questions about the march, she didn't hesitate.
   ``It's an outlandish success. It's extraordinary,'' she said.
``It sends a clear message there is a very widespread, deeply held
conviction out there.''
</TEXT>
