<DOCNO> AP890410-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 0117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EPANominee     04-10 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EPA Nominee,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top EPA Nominee Fought Agency Two Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Environmental Protection Agency tried
to crack down on U.S. government polluters two years ago, a Justice
Department official was accused of sabotaging the effort and making
EPA ``the enforcement eunuch'' of the government.
   House members and EPA officials directed their criticism at F.
Henry Habicht II, who now has been recommended by EPA Administrator
William K. Reilly as the agency's No. 2 official.
   Habicht is working as an EPA consultant while he waits for
President Bush's nomination as deputy administrator, said EPA
spokesman David Cohen, who described Reilly's choice as ``one of
the brightest and toughest environmental enforcers in town.''
   Habicht, 35, admittedly was a key architect in developing the
Justice Department policy that forced EPA to negotiate with U.S.
government polluters, instead of handing them orders to clean up
their hazardous waste.
   Internal EPA memos in 1986-87 called the policy ``unlawful''
because it was more lenient toward government than private
polluters, and warned the double standard could ``severely damage''
EPA's credibility.
   EPA officials said in interviews last week the policy has
allowed the defense and energy departments to stonewall
negotiations involving their facilities, thereby delaying
agreements at some of the nation's worst pollution sites.
   An EPA source, speaking only on condition he not be named, said
the ``practical effect'' of Habicht's policy ``is it takes longer
than it should to correct violations'' at federal facilities.
   ``We spend too much time negotiating because there's no order
that would culminate the negotiating process,'' the source said.
   ``The idea behind orders is that people are not going to screw
around if they know EPA has delegated authority from the president
to make the decision on what needs to be done.''
   Habicht resigned as the chief of the Justice Department's land
and natural resources division in 1987, shortly after his testimony
before Congress on the negotiation policy. He has worked since for
an environmental consulting firm that was headed by former EPA
Administrator William D. Ruckelshaus.
   Cohen said Reilly chose Habicht because he's ``one of the most
capable environmental managers. Anyone who knows Hank Habicht knows
he is first-rate.''
   Defending Habicht's actions two years ago, Cohen said there were
``constitutional problems'' with EPA's administrative orders to
other agencies, and Habicht ``has not ruled out administrative
orders as a possible tool.''
   ``It was a strictly legal consideration, and I don't think it
reflects, as some would lead you to believe, in any way negatively
on Hank Habicht's determination to get on with the job of federal
facilities cleanup _ and also with making sure that federal
facilities are treated as much as possible as polluters are treated
in the private sector.''
   Other EPA officials also described Habicht as a committed
environmentalist, despite his rough treatment in April 1987 when he
appeared before the House Energy and Commerce investigations
subcommittee.
   Panel Chairman John D. Dingell, D-Mich., predicted the
negotiation policy would make EPA ``the enforcement eunuch of the
federal agencies, and with regard to federal facilities, its
failures and the penalties that will be suffered by the public will
be noteworthy.''
   Other committee members called the policy ``a prescription for
non-enforcement of the country's environmental laws'' and said it
created a ``double standard between federal agency polluters and
private industry.''
   Sen. Quentin N. Burdick, chairman of the Senate Environment and
Public Works Committee, said the panel is checking into the
controversy, since it would conduct Habicht's confirmation hearing.
   ``The committee will definitely look into this matter and his
other work at the Justice Department, if he is nominated,''
Burdick, D-N.D., said. ``I am concerned about the theory which
limit's EPA's ability to ensure that federal agencies comply with
federal environmental laws.''
   A spokesman for Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., a committee member,
said the controversy is ``extremely disturbing.'' But the
spokesman, Craig Varoga, said Reid has an ``open mind'' on the
nomination, and has ``the greatest enthusiasm for providing Mr.
Reilly with all the proper support he needs.''
</TEXT>
