<FIRST>r w PM-US-Soviet     04-10 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scowcroft Wary of Gorbachev's Motives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should pursue a cautious
strategy toward the Soviet Union, tempering new initiatives with
skepticism about President Mikhail Gorbachev's intentions,
President Bush's national security adviser says.
   Brent Scowcroft maintained on Sunday that the Western strategy
of projecting ``strength and determination'' in dealings with the
Kremlin has been successful. He cited Gorbachev's withdrawal from
Afghanistan and indications the Soviet economic system is in
trouble.
   At the same time, both Scowcroft and Secretary of State James A.
Baker III acknowledged in national television interviews that Bush
administration officials remain immersed in a substantial
interagency review of East-West relations.
   Scowcroft labeled as ``premature'' published reports saying Bush
already had been advised by a policy task force to pursue a
basically status-quo policy toward the Soviets.
   ``We have initial results from the study by the bureaucratic
interagency process,'' he said on NBC-TV's ``Meet The Press.'' But
Scowcroft said ``it's probably not surprising that the future looks
a lot like the present, in a sort of straight-line projection. But
we're not there yet.''
   Baker, interviewed on ABC's ``This Week With David Brinkley,''
brushed aside complaints by Gorbachev that the go-slow U.S. policy
stance has jeopardized momentum for agreement on a treaty to slash
the superpowers' strategic nuclear stockpiles.
   ``We are conducting a policy review,'' Baker said. ``We have
told the Soviets _ as long ago as a month _ that we anticipated
that these reviews would be completed about the end of April.''
   He also said he ``would be prepared to discuss some of these
issues'' during his scheduled meeting in Moscow in early May with
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   ``So they've known what our time frame and timetable was for
quite some time,'' Baker said, ``so it's sort of interesting to see
this statement only coming out now.''
   Scowcroft, a retired Air Force general, was asked to comment on
reports that Bush had been advised to steer a cautious course
toward the Soviets and to be wary of Gorbachev's promises of reform
in Russia.
   ``A major power like the United States ought not to make sharp,
dramatic changes in policy,'' he said. ``We've had a fairly
consistent policy now, through Democratic and Republican
administrations, for 40 years. ... A lot of things are happening
and it's important now, perhaps for the first administration in a
long time, to look out ahead, to look toward the end of the
century, and say, `Where do we want to be?'
   ``There's no question that we have every reason to look back on
the past 40 years and say we've been successful,'' Scowcroft added.
   An administration official, discussing the internal policy
review on grounds of anonymity, said the initial policy report
advised Bush to pursue no major new initiatives.
   Bush asked his advisers to ``take another look another time at
the whole situation'' after receiving recommendations on relations
with the Soviet Union, Eastern Europe, and East-West relations, the
official said. Three such reports are part of a major foreign
policy review Bush initiated as he took office in January.
   In relations with the Soviet Union, ``I don't see anything
new,'' the official said, adding that there apparently was ``not
much to change right now.'' The reports were given to Bush during
meetings of the National Security Council over the past 10 days, he
said.
   Scowcroft said he feels that Gorbachev is ``dynamic, modern ...
dedicated to change'' in the Soviet Union. ``But what is in doubt
is what the character of that change and what his motivation for
change is. And there is a major question.''
   The national security adviser said ``the evidence so far is
mixed'' on Gorbachev's true intentions. ``So I think it's too early
to assess how much he's really dedicated to substantive change,''
he said.
</TEXT>
