<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0430,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Authorities Arrest Top Drug Kingpin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with U.S. comment; Picks up
4th pvs: `The government...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested one of the world's most
wanted cocaine dealers, a Mexican who has also been accused of
links to the killing of a U.S. drug agent, the federal attorney
general's office said Sunday.
   Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo, called the godfather of Mexican
drug trafficking, was arrested late Saturday in Guadalajara in the
western state of Jalisco, the prosecutor's office said in a
statement.
   Numerous high-powered weapons were also seized by members of the
Federal Judicial Police, the statement said. It said Felix
Gallardo, 43, put up no resistance. He is thought to run one of the
largest cocaine trafficking operations in the world.
   A U.S. official welcomed news of the arrest. ``We're delighted
to hear that. This is most interesting,'' said William Graves, a
U.S. embassy spokesman, on Sunday night.
   The government news agency Notimex reported that Felix Gallardo
and four others also arrested have been flown to Mexico City, 300
miles east of Guadalajara.
   In another development, authorities said the entire police force
of the city of Culiacan, in the northwestern state of Sinaloa, was
arrested in a massive sweep Saturday night.
   All 70 to 80 police officers were set free Sunday with the
exception of Police Chief Robespier Lisarraja and State Police
Chief Arturo Moreno, who remained in military custody at a local
army base, said Jorge Gonzalez, spokesman for the federal attorney
generals' office in Culiacan.
   Gonzalez could not say why the entire police force was arrested
or on what charges the chiefs were being held. Culiacan is Felix
Gallardo's hometown and has long had a reputation for official
corruption.
   Agents of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration long had
suspected Felix Gallardo of involvement in the 1985 slaying of
fellow agent Enrique Camarena Salazar, but were unable to locate
him.
   U.S. officials investigating Camarena killing said Felix
Gallardo was able to build up an immense drug operation with
protection from high Mexican officials, including a state governor.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who took office on Dec. 1,
has pledged to crack down on drug dealers, and the arrest
underlines Salinas' vow to ``fight this social cancer,'' the
attorney general's office said.
   Called the godfather of Mexican drug trafficking, Felix Gallardo
had such good connections that U.S. drug agents said Mexican agents
were afraid to find him, according to the recently published book
``Desperados'' by Elaine Shannon.
   Felix Gallardo was at one time a member of the Sinaloa state
police and bodyguard for former Gov. Leopoldo Sanchez Celis until
1980. The DEA believes he introduced cocaine smuggling to Mexican
marijuana rings in the mid-1970s, Shannon said.
   At one time in the mid-1980s the DEA believed Felix Gallardo was
responsible for the smuggling of 1{ to 2 tons of cocaine monthly
from South America into the United States, according to Shannon's
book.
   The United States has been pressuring Mexico to stem the flow of
drugs across the border. Mexico has countered that the U.S. demand
for drugs fuels the Mexican narcotics trade.
   Some U.S. congressmen, including Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., have
accused Mexico of widespread official corruption and maintain that
certification should be denied.
</TEXT>
