<FIRST>r a PM-MuleActivist     04-10 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mule Activist,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Arrested Trying to Stop Mule Act at Fair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUSTIS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An animal rights activist ran up a 30-foot
ramp in an attempt to stop a diving mule act but was arrested and
the show went on.
   ``There comes a time in every person's life when they have to
take a risk for what they believe in,'' said 58-year-old Noelle
Valentine. ``I believe in the rights of animals very deeply.''
   Valentine charged up the ramp as the performance was scheduled
to start Friday. She shouted anti-cruelty slogans and some
spectators jeered.
   ``Jump!'' some of them yelled.
   A police officer and the Lake County Fair's operator accompanied
Valentine back to the ground, and she was charged with trespassing
and resisting arrest without violence.
   Earlier Friday, county animal control officer Frankie Thorp
watched a 15-year-old mule named Kit dive into the pool of water
and determined the act was not cruel.
   The Leesburg and Lake County humane societies, however, insisted
the act was cruel.
   ``It's not a natural act,'' said Dan Davis, a Lake County Humane
Society investigator. ``That's got to do damage to the poor animal.
If I do a belly flop at 30 feet, it's gonna hurt. If I do it more
than once, it's going to really hurt internally.''
</TEXT>
