<DOCNO> AP890410-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 0914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-USBases     04-10 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-US Bases,0365</SECOND>
<BYLINE>New Greek-U.S. Talks Open on Bases ^By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and U.S. negotiators opened a new
round of talks today on U.S. military bases in Greece, but a
diplomat predicted no quick progress.
   The Greeks seek assurances from U.S. officials that they will
try to solve outstanding differences with neighboring Turkey, a
NATO ally of both countries. Greece also wants to close Hellinikon
Airbase next to Athens International Airport.
   U.S. negotiators say they want to keep the Greek-Turkish issues
outside the current talks. They also say Hellinikon is an integral
part of U.S. operations in Greece. It is used by aircraft to shadow
movements of the Soviet Mediterranean fleet.
   The old pact provided that United States pay Greece indirectly
for the bases with about $500 million in annual military
assistance. The Greeks want the aid increased to $800 million.
   The new talks beginning today at the Foreign Ministry are the
16th round. They are not expected to last longer than three days
and will mainly deal with a preamble to a new agreement.
   Western diplomatic sources believe no agreement will be reached
before scheduled June 18 general elections ``in order to avoid it
becoming a pre-electoral issue,'' one diplomat said on condition of
anonymity.
   ``New ground will have to be broken with the next government,''
said the diplomat.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou, who leads the Panhellenic Socialist
Movement, has said repeatedly any new agreement will be put to a
public referendum for a final decision.
   After the 14th round of talks in Athens two months ago, Greek
government spokesman Sotiris Costopoulos said there were
``differences of opinion between the two sides but no deadlock.''
   Four major U.S. installations are in question: Hellinikon; a
navy communications station in Nea Makri, 20 miles southeast of the
Greek capital; an air force communications installation on the
Aegean island of Crete; and a support base for the 6th fleet, also
on Crete.
   The previous five-year agreement expired last December. That
accord gave the United States 17 months from the expiration date to
either dismantle its bases or sign a new contract.
</TEXT>
