<FIRST>u i PM-Greece-Bomb     04-10 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Bomb,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Outside Home of Supreme Court Judge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Samouil Samouil is cq in 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today outside the home of
a Supreme Court judge, and a leftist terrorist group said it
mounted the attack to pressure judges to reject a U.S. request to
extradite a Palestinian bombing suspect.
   Police said the pre-dawn blast caused no injuries. They said it
did extensive damage at the apartment of Judge Samouil Samouil in
suburban Neo Psychicho and at nearby apartments. It exploded at the
front door of the judge's fifth-floor apartment, the police said.
   There was no immediate word on whether the judge was home at the
time.
   The Greek terrorist group, May 1, claimed responsibility in a
proclamation published in the leftist newspaper Eleftherotypia. The
statement contained threats against Supreme Court members involved
in a decision on extraditing a Palestinan to the United States on
terrorism charges.
   The Supreme Court is scheduled to announce Tuesday whether it
will allow the extradition of Mohammed Rashid, also known as
Mohammed Hamdan.
   ``Our action is a warning and is directed to all members of the
judiciary, irrespective of their position, who are involved in the
Hamdan (Rashid) case, that their protection does not rely on the
police but ... on their decision,'' the May 1 statement said.
   Rashid, whose legal expenses are being paid by the Palestine
Liberation Organization, was arrested at Athens airport last year
following a tip by the U.S. Embassy.
   He is wanted in the United States on charges of placing a bomb
aboard a Pan Am airliner in 1982. One person died in the explosion
over Hawaii.
   The Marxist-oriented May 1 group previously has claimed
responsibility for shooting and wounding Giorgos Raftopoulos, the
president of the General Confederation of Greek Laborers, in 1987
and assassinating Supreme Court Judge Anastasios Vernardos earlier
this year.
   Judicial sources declined to say if Samouil is involved in
Rashid's case. Not all judges of the 48-member Supreme Court are
reviewing the case.
</TEXT>
