<FIRST>u i PM-PLO-Israel     04-10 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PLO-Israel,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Reject Elections In Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO today rejected Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's proposal to hold elections in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, saying it was a warmed
over version of the Camp David Accords.
   In its first reaction to Shamir's plan, the Palestine Liberation
Organization said any elections in the territories Israel occupied
in the 1967 Middle East war should be held after Israeli withdrawal
and under international supervision.
   The PLO news agency Wafa quoted an unidentified PLO spokesman as
saying Shamir's plan is ``nothing but a reactivation of the
self-autonomy scheme of the Camp David Accord which the PLO and our
entire Palestinian people already have rejected.''
   Shamir unveiled his election ideas in Washington last week as a
way of breaking a deadlock in Middle East peace efforts.
   His plan calls for having Palestinians choose representatives
for negotiations about an interim settlement in the disputed lands.
   The agency called the idea ``nothing but a maneuver aimed at
undermining efforts undertaken by several world powers to achieve a
just settlement in the Middle East.''
   The U.S.-brokered Camp David Accords between Egypt and Israel
called for limited autonomy for Palestinians in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip. The 1978 accords led to peace with Egypt but were
rejected by the PLO.
   ``The only just solution is an Israeli withdrawal from
Palestinian and Arab territory,'' the spokesman said. ``The West
Bank and Gaza Strip should be placed under United Nations
supervision for a transition period, during which Palestinians
could exercise their right to self-determination, including the
holding of free elections.''
   The statement reiterated frequent PLO calls for an international
peace conference on the Middle East involving all parties
concerned, ``including the Palestinian state'' proclaimed by the
PLO National Council on Nov. 15.
   It is the first time the PLO has mentioned the Palestinian state
as the representative of Palestinians at the proposed international
peace conference. All previous references mentioned the PLO.
   In Jerusalem, an Israeli newspaper reported today that Shamir
indicated he might consider allowing Palestinians from outside the
occupied territories to participate in the proposed elections.
   Interviewed by the Maariv daily in Chicago, Shamir was asked
whether Palestinians outside the territories and in annexed east
Jerusalem could vote in his proposed elections. He replied the
question would be ``a subject for discussion.''
</TEXT>
