<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     04-10 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Bomb U.S. Communications Equipment; 12 Killed In Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels bombed a U.S.
military communications center in northern Benguet province,
destroying an antenna and damaging three electric pylons, officials
said.
   Military officials said there were no injuries from Sunday's
explosion at the station on Mount Cabuyao, 140 miles north of
Manila.
   ``The communication site remains operational,'' said a statement
from the U.S.-run Clark Air Base, 50 miles north of Manila. Maj.
Wayne Crist, a spokesman at the base, said estimates of the damage
were unavailable.
   The complex houses a U.S. Air Force microwave relay station,
which assists communication inside the country, and a U.S. Navy
remote tracking station, Crist said.
   A Philippine Constabulary report said the saboteurs planted 18
explosive devices under an antenna and several electric towers in
the compound but only five went off, destroying the antenna and
three electric pylons.
   ``It is suspected that this is the work of communist terrorists
in the area,'' armed forces chief of staff Gen. Renato de Villa
told a news conference. ``It has been known that the (rebels) are
targeting U.S. installations and personnel.''
   Communist insurgents have waged a 20-year-old rebellion. They
have threatened to attack U.S. facilities unless the United States
stopped supporting President Corazon Aquino's counterinsurgency
campaign.
   Communist guerrillas killed three Americans and a Filipino in
attacks outside Clark in October 1987.
</TEXT>
