<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AbortionRally-Missouri 1stLd-Writethru aa</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Rally-Missouri, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ashcroft Defends Missouri Anti-Abortion Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, As Ashcroft, to delete reference to abortion
as akin to murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLE FELDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri Gov. John Ashcroft says an unborn
baby should not have to die because of ``the inconvenience or
desperate circumstances'' of a pregnant woman, so he's asking the
Supreme Court to restrict abortions.
   As Ashcroft made his comments, hundreds of thousands of
pro-choice activists marched on the Capitol on Sunday seeking to
avert a reversal of the Supreme Court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision
legalizing abortion.
   The court will hear arguments April 26 on a Missouri statute
that bans abortions and abortion counseling in public facilities
and requires doctors to try to save fetuses aborted after a certain
age of gestation.
   ``Abortion is a topic that relates to death because we lose
about a million-six hundred to million-seven hundred thousand
unborn babies that are killed in the process,'' Ashcroft said on
CBS' ``Face the Nation.''
   He acknowledged that as a result of the law, women who had
abortions might still find themselves with unwanted premature
babies facing physical problems, such as neonatal lung disorders.
   Asked who pays for the care of the child, Ashcroft said, ``I
think that depends.''
   Pressed on whether any state money had been budgeted for the
care of children who survive abortions, he responded, ``The state
is, as a matter of policy, eager to save the lives of as many of
these children as we can, and we're willing to help. Not only in
making sure that the medical needs are met, but making sure that
there are families that take these children.''
   The Republican governor said his state passed the restrictive
abortion statute because ``we hope that any time we can save the
life of a child in Missouri, that we would seek to save the life of
that child. ...
   ``And if the right of an abortion, as it's currently construed,
is to rid the mother of the _ whether it be inconvenience or
desperate circumstances she feels she's in because she's pregnant _
if that doesn't mean the baby has to die, we don't see any reason
for that baby to die.''
   Ashcroft defended the provision of the Missouri statute banning
abortion in public facilities and denied that it discriminated
against poor women.
   ``Many of the poorer people in our state are treated in private
hospitals,'' he said. ``As a matter of fact, the trend is away from
public hospitals, so difficult to administer, and frequently, work
on patients that would ordinarily be in a public hospital are
referred on a contract basis to private hospitals now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
