<DOCNO> AP890410-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1019EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bork-Warren     04-10 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bork-Warren,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bork: Warren Court Responsible for Demonstrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion Rally, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Supreme Court nominee Robert Bork
says the Earl Warren court is responsible for the continuing
political demonstrations that surround the high court's decisions.
   At a conference commemorating the 20-year anniversary of
Warren's retirement as chief justice, Bork, a former federal
appeals court judge whose nomination to the Supreme Court was
rejected in 1987, said the ``activism'' of the Warren court
``damaged perceptions of the legal system.''
   ``People have vigils around the court, they march up and down
Constitution Avenue. And what that means is that they perceive the
court as essentially a political institution. I think that's
dangerous.''
   He spoke Sunday as hundreds of thousands of abortion-rights
advocates marched in the nation's capital calling for continuation
of legal abortion, which the court is to re-examine April 26.
   Bork did not discuss the abortion issue but referred to the
Warren court's declaration of a constitutional right of privacy,
which because the basis of the Warren Burger court's 1973 ruling
legalizing abortions, as one of the court's ``excesses.''
   Bork's rejection of a constitutional right of privacy was a
central issue in the Senate's rejection of his nomination to the
high court by President Reagan. Bork has since resigned as an
appeals judge and is a speaker on conservative issues and a scholar
at the American Enterprise Institute.
   He took part in a panel discussion, part of a weekend of events
commemorating Warren, an Eisenhower appointee who served on the
Supreme Court from 1953 to 1969 and died in 1974.
   At a dinner Saturday night, Justice William Brennan said Warren,
with whom he served 13 years, will be remembered for ``his concern
with fairness for the disadvantaged, the downtrodden, the poor, the
friendless,'' and for his leadership at a time of ``the greatest
diversity of deeply troublesome questions in our court's history.''
   But Bork, speaking to reporters after his panel appearance, said
the nation would be better off if the Warren court had never
existed.
   ``If I had a court of Byron Whites, judges in that range, I
think the country would be better off because there wouldn't have
been so many excesses,'' he said. White, appointed by President
John F. Kennedy, served in the later years of the Warren court but
dissented from some of its liberal rulings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
