<FIRST>r a PM-Drive-byShootings     04-10 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drive-by Shootings,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighborhood Rallies Against Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A neighborhood rally sounded a call for
unity to battle the crack cocaine epidemic after weekend shootings
left two dead and 10 injured.
   ``It's time for us to get together,'' said the Rev. Cecil
Williams, who led several hundred chanting people through the
city's Ocean View neighborhood on a march before the Sunday rally.
   The march and rally, during which participants carried signs
that read ``No Hope in Dope'' and ``Jobs Not Drugs,'' followed a
weekend of violent outbreaks in the Bayview-Hunters Point district,
less than two miles away.
   Williams, pastor of the inner-city Glide Memorial United
Methodist Church, called the gathering a first step in the fight
against crack, the smokable form of cocaine that is destroying
families and communities across the nation.
   Organizers called for increased job training and education
programs to give youngsters an alternative to drugs.
   The rally was planned several weeks ago, but a drive-by ambush
and another shooting probably prompted more people to participate,
Williams said.
   ``People are being killed, being openly killed,'' he said.
   Two people were killed and nine injured in an automatic weapons
ambush early Saturday that police said may have been a case of
mistaken identity. In a separate incident Saturday night, two men
were abducted by four others carrying an Uzi machine gun and a
.45-caliber handgun. One of them was shot and wounded.
   The rally participants' inference that the shootings were
drug-related was bolstered by a report in The San Francisco
Examiner on Sunday. It quoted an unidentified young man who said
the attack early Saturday was directed by a crack dealer who
followed what he thought were some gang members as they left an
outdoor party in a nearby park.
   The source said most of the victims had no gang connections and
the crack dealer's main target escaped injury.
   ``Everybody's scared now. It was never like this,'' said JoAnne
Miller, a school board member and a neighbor and acquaintance of
one of those who died.
   Residents on Saturday spray-painted the words ``Why, Why, Why?''
in an intersection near the shootings.
</TEXT>
