<FIRST>r a PM-SuicideFilm     04-10 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Suicide Film,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Filmmaker Accuses State Of Censorship In Effort To Ban Movie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The producer of an educational film on
teen-age suicide accused the state of censorship for ordering him
to surrender all prints of the movie so it can be destroyed.
Officials say the movie, produced at state expense, could actually
encourage suicide.
   Department of Mental Health officials said that Jerry Naylor's
film, ``Give Yourself a Chance for Life,'' contains a graphic
suicide scene that could provoke troubled teen-agers to take their
own lives.
   Naylor, hired by the state to produce the film for $237,000, has
refused to give up the movie, contending it should be shown in
every California high school because it can save lives.
   ``It's censorship, direct censorship,'' Naylor said Friday. ``If
I sincerely believed this film was `a lethal weapon,' as they call
it, or that it would cause one person to kill himself, I'd never
want it shown. I'm not giving up.''
   Dr. Michael O'Connor, director of the Department of Mental
Health, says he too is not giving up.
   ``My mind will never change on that film,'' O'Connor said.
``This is a matter of medical ethics, not artistic content. Medical
and clinical people I've shown the film to unanimously told me they
thought the film was dangerous, that people might get the wrong
idea when they see it.''
</TEXT>
