<FIRST>r i PM-HospitalKillings     04-10 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Killings,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Nurses Under Arrest Admit To 49 Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four nurses have confessed to killing 49
patients with lethal injections in a Vienna hospital since 1983,
police said today.
   The fourth nurse was arrested Sunday, after three other women
had been arrested Friday and acknowledged killing 44 patients at
Lainz hospital, Police Chief Guenter Boegl said.
   He told reporters that the nurse arrested Sunday acknowledged
killing five patients.
   Boegl said the nurses gave the patients, who reportedly ranged
in age from 75 to 80, overdoses of insulin or a sleeping medication
or forced infusions of water into their lungs.
   The nurses, identified by police as Maria Gruber, 25, Irene
Leidolf, 27, Waltraud Wagner, 30, and Stephanie Mayer, 50, are in
custody, but no formal charges had been filed by this afternoon.
   Police said each nurse knew the others were killing patients.
Investigators said in a few cases two nurses would act together to
administer a lethal injection.
   Initial reports said the killings in Lainz hospital occurred in
the past year, but Boegl said the slayings apparently began in 1983.
   He said no new arrests were planned.
   Boegl said Sunday the nurses gave as their main motive ``active
euthanasia,'' inducing painless death in people suffering from a
painful, terminal disease.
   Another police investigator said the nurses also killed patients
whom they considered a nuisance.
   Interior Minister Franz Loeschnak said in a radio interview it
would be ``difficult for those who work (at the hospital) to
re-establish trust with the patients.''
</TEXT>
