<HEAD>Biaggi Begins Serving Bribery Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede GRAPEVINE, Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Biaggi entering prison, add
further background. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `He was...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former congressman Mario Biaggi entered
a federal prison early today to start serving his 2{-year sentence
for accepting a bribe.
   Biaggi, 71, reported to the U.S. Correctional Facility, a
minimum security prison that has about 850 inmates, about 1 a.m.,
said Warden Ron Burkhart.
   He immediately began the check-in process, was given
institutional clothing and assigned a place to live, Burkhart said.
After a physical examination and several days of orientation,
Biaggi will be assigned a job at the facility.
   ``Everybody does something that is reflective of his abilities
or restrictions,'' Burkhart said.
   Biaggi arrived at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport late
Sunday on a flight from Newark, N.J.
   He parlayed a record as the most highly decorated police officer
in New York City history into a successful political career,
winning election to the House of Representatives 10 times.
   But in September 1987, he was convicted of federal bribery
charges in for accepting a Florida spa vacation from former New
York City Democratic boss Meade Esposito.
   He was later convicted in the Wedtech scandal and sentenced to
eight years.
   At the New Jersey airport, Biaggi said he had served his
constituents well and would return ``to pick up where we left off.''
   Flanked by family members, he told reporters he went to church
earlier in the day. He also said he visited his wife, Marie Wassil
Biaggi, who is hospitalized with Hodgkin's disease.
   ``I have loving grandchildren and loving children,'' he said.
``They'll be here when I get back.''
   The former congressman maintained he accepted the Florida
vacation as a friend of Esposito.
   ``I find myself going to a federal facility today because a
friend of some 35 years was generous to me,'' said Biaggi.
   About 30 friends gathered at a posh New York City restaurant
Saturday for a combination farewell party for him and birthday
party for the daughter of a long-time friend.
   ``They gave me a great honor,'' said Biaggi. ``I believe I
served them well. I tried with all of my might. I'm leaving, but
I'll be back and we'll pick it up where we left off.''
</TEXT>
