<FIRST>u i PM-Haiti 1stLd-Writethru a0438 04-10 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Haiti, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Government Works to Restore Authority after Crushing Coup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with government in control today,
increases casualty estimate by one civilian; pickup 9th graf pvs `Avril's
seven-month-old....' SUBS two grafs for grafs 15-end to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril's military
government worked today to restore its authority after crushing a
revolt by army units in two days of fierce fighting.
   The government appeared to be firmly in control after the
rebellion, which followed a failed military coup eight days ago.
Shops, offices and schools were open and traffic was back to normal
in Port-au-Prince, this Caribbean nation's capital of 1 million
people.
   Government communiques released late Sunday lifted news
censorship and eased an overnight curfew.
   Only sporadic shooting was heard in Port-au-Prince overnight,
and one body was found in a street early today.
   The government released no information about the number of
casualties during the weeklong revolt or the fate of rebels
captured during the final assault Saturday by Avril's Presidential
Guard on the mutineers' stronghold.
   However, Roman Catholic Radio Soleil said today that 30 soldiers
_ 25 rebels and five loyalists _ and four civilians were killed
Friday and Saturday in fighting with cannons, mortars, grenades,
rifles and machine guns. A Haitian doctor speaking on condition of
anonymity said at least 15 soldiers of the Presidential Guard were
wounded but he had no report on injured rebels.
   A military communique issued at 5:15 p.m. Saturday said loyal
troops had seized the Dessalines Barracks compound adjoining the
National Palace and most of the rebels were captured but a few fled.
   It blamed the revolt, which began April 2 with a failed coup
attempt, on people it said were opposed to the government's ``vast
campaign against drug trafficking, contraband and corruption.''
   Four ranking officers were accused of plotting the coup and
three were deported last week to the United States. The fourth,
Col. Guy Francois, commander of the Dessalines Barracks, received
asylum in the Vatican Embassy, according to Radio Soleil.
   Avril's seven-month-old government has been under pressure from
the United States to act against narcotics trafficking and those
military officers reportedly profiting from it.
   Washington has made action against the trafficking a condition
for restoring $70 million in aid that was suspended in November
1987 after bands of thugs killed 34 people and brought the
cancellation of elections.
   The balloting would have been Haiti's first free elections in 30
years. It was scheduled after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to
France in February 1986 during violent demonstrations.
   Avril was installed as president in September after a coup led
by non-commissioned officers and established the island's fourth
government since 1968. He has promised democratic elections.
   Two of the army's strongest military units, the Dessalines
Barracks with 750 troopers and the Leopards Battalion on the
outskirts of the capital with 400 soldiers, rebelled after Avril
deported three alleged leaders of the attempted April 2 coup: Lt.
Col. Himmler Rebu, commander of the Leopards; Presidential Guards
commander Col. Philippe Biamby and Col. Leonce Qualo of army
headquarters.
   But the Presidential Guards, which has 1,100 soldiers and is the
largest unit in Haiti's 7,000-man army, remained loyal.
   Soldiers of the Leopards Battalion revolted after the failed
coup, demanding the release of their commander. There have been
conflicting reports about the death toll in fighting earlier in the
week with at least six Leopards killed.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Susan Clyde said Sunday the United
States had donated $25,000 to the Haitian Red Cross for medical
assistance.
</TEXT>
