<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Army     04-10 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Army,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colonel Steps Down Because of West Bank Actions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron
has forced a colonel to resign after investigations of attacks on
Palestinians by soldiers under his command, a military source said
today.
   The Maariv daily said it was the harshest action taken in more
than a decade against an officer of such a high rank serving in the
occupied territories.
   The military source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Col. Yuhuda Meir decided to step down and leave the army after
Shomron told him he must either quit or stand trial.
   Meir, who was military governor of Nablus in the occupied West
Bank at the start of the 16-month Palestinian uprising, was
investigated in connection with two incidents.
   One of these was a widely reported case in Kfar Salem near
Nablus last year where troops under Meir's command used a bulldozer
to bury four Palestinians under piles of sand, the newspaper said.
The victims survived.
   Another inquiry involved the beatings of two Palestinian
teen-agers in Nablus, one of them with a stone. The attack was
filmed by American television cameras. Those youths also survived.
   Meir was removed from his Nablus post following these incidents
and reassigned elsewhere, the military source said. He was later
investigated on suspicion of ``inappropriate behavior'' for these
actions, prompting Shomron's action, the source added.
   Maariv said the last high-ranking officer to step down over
actions in the territories was a brigadier general removed by
then-Defense Minister Ezer Weizman after tear gas was fired at a
school in the West Bank town of Beit Jallah in May 1978.
</TEXT>
