<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Williams     04-10 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Williams,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalist, Civic Leader Ernie Williams Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ernest E. Williams, former editor of the
Fort Wayne News-Sentinel and the man who encouraged Vice President
Dan Quayle to enter politics, has died. He was 72.
   Williams, a key figure in local and state Republican politics,
died Sunday of complications following cardiac bypass surgery.
   ``It was Ernie's idea first that I run for Congress in 1976,''
Quayle told the Fort Wayne Journal-Gazette. ``Ernie Williams was a
courageous, honest, independent, hard-driving professional.
   ``He was also a warm and considerate human being who always
thought of other people. He was a close friend and he will be
missed,'' Quayle said.
   Williams, a native of Logansport, Ind., graduated from Indiana
University in 1939. He joined the News-Sentinel as a reporter in
1945 and was named editor in 1966. He retired in October 1982.
   Richard Inskeep, publisher of the Journal-Gazette, said, ``Ernie
was highly regarded in his long-time newspaper career, both as a
reporter and as an editor. This community will miss him.''
   Williams was named coordinator of the journalism program at
Indiana-Purdue at Fort Wayne in 1981. He was inducted into the
Indiana Journalism Hall of Fame at DePauw University in 1988.
   Surviving are his wife, Hildreth E. Williams; two daughters;
three sons; two sisters; a brother; and four grandchildren.
   Funeral services were set for Wednesday.
</TEXT>
