<HEAD>79 Killed in Northern Uganda Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clashes involving rebels, civilians and
soldiers in northern Uganda last week left at least 79 people dead
_ including some who were hacked to death with machetes, a
newspaper reported Monday.
   The clashes occured April 4 in a trading town north of the
administrative town of Gulu, 175 miles north of the capital,
Kampala, according to the government newspaper New Vision.
   A group of unidentified rebels, some armed with rifles, first
hacked to death 20 civilians in a village on the outskirts of the
trading town of Lagor, about 35 miles north of Gulu, the newspaper
said, quoting an army officer.
   The rebels then went to an army barracks in nearby Lagor, where
a battle killed 50 rebels and nine soldiers.
   There are at least 10 groups in Uganda fighting President Yoweri
Museveni's 38-month-old government.
