<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WomeninMedia     04-10 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Women in Media,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women Rare in News Executive Suites, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women hold only 6 percent of top jobs in the
news media and 25 percent of mid-management jobs, according to a
study released today at a conference here on ``Women, Men and
Media.''
   The study, financed primarily by the conference's sponsor, the
Gannett Foundation, also reported that women in the media earn 64
cents for every dollar earned by a man.
   ``Not only are women ignored at jobs in the media, they are
slighted in coverage as well,'' the study said.
   The researchers said they studied photos, bylines and story
sources in 10 newspapers in March and found that 27 percent of the
bylines on the front page were female, 24 percent of the photos
included women, usually with their families; and 11 percent of the
people quoted were female.
   Using this standard, the researchers ranked the newspapers
``from best to worst'' as follows:
   USA Today first; Houston Chronicle and Atlanta Constitution tied
for second; followed in order by the Seattle Times, Washington
Post, Los Angeles Times, Miami Herald, St. Louis Post-Dispatch,
Chicago Tribune and New York Times.
   A study of nightly network newscasts found that from 1975 to
1989 the percentage of female news correspondents increased from
9.9 percent to 15.8 percent, the report said. It said the
percentages of stories filed by women in February were 22.2 percent
on CBS, 14.4 percent on NBC and 10.5 percent on ABC.
   The percentages of stories that focused on women were 13.7
percent on ABC, 10.2 percent on CBS and 8.9 percent on NBC, the
survey found.
   The study of hiring and promotion was conducted by Jean Gaddy
Wilson of the University of Missouri and television and newspaper
coverage was studied by Kathy Bonk, co-director of a communications
consortium, and Junior Bridge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0462 04-10 0939</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0462,0959</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Edge Of Oil Breaking Up; Fishing Port Prepares For The Worst</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with rough weather continuing
to break up and stall the spill; tanker reinforced to prevent further leaks;
other detail. Picks up 11th graf pvs, ``The tanker...'. SUBS 18th graf,
`Air Force...', to delete now-redundant first reference to Meidt, add Coast
Guard bringing in more cutters. SUBS last graf to update cleanup total
to 18,000 sted 17,000 barrels.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rough weather continued to break up the
leading edge of the giant, gloppy Exxon Valdez oil spill, the Coast
Guard said today. But the nation's richest fishing port prepared
for the worst by stringing logs across bays.
   On Sunday, U.S. military jets flew skimmers, booms and beach
landing craft into Alaska, and commanders issued a Pacific-wide
call for more equipment to fight the nation's worst oil spill.
   In Kodiak, 300 miles southwest of the spill site, fishermen
covered logs with fish net and spread them across vital fishing
areas Sunday. But officials reported today that the slick seems to
have stalled on its on a southwesterly course for the island, with
high winds making the water so choppy that the blob of oil doesn't
move.
   ``It's not pushing it (oil) to the Kenai Peninsula, and that's
good,'' said Coast Guard spokesman Rick Meidt, referring to the
land mass to the west of the spill and northeast of Kodiak. ``The
weather is breaking up the slick, and that's good.'' In the past
three days, Meidt said, the slick apparently hasn't moved any
further.
   Small craft advisories and a gale warning were posted at Kodiak,
which saw rain, seas to 15 feet and winds from the northeast to 35
knots early today, the National Weather Service said. Winds
decreased toward Valdez, which reported a northeast wind at 10
knots.
   Oil was still at least 60 miles from Kodiak, where officials
even used television to display boom-making techniques.
   Herring boats and Coast Guard cutters were dispatched to speed
the breakup of the spill, whose $166 million catch last year was
the nation's most lucrative. At Seward, on the edge of a
still-threatened national park, a skimmer stood ready to protect
inner bays and fish hatcheries.
   In other developments:
   _U.S. gasoline prices jumped more than a dime a gallon in the
wake of the tanker spill, according to the Lundberg Survey. Prices,
however, were showing signs of easing, said analyst Trilby Lundberg.
   _Exxon said it was beginning to reimburse Cordova fishermen for
losses from the cancellation of the $12 million herring season, and
had paid $250,000 to cover expenses for fishing boats attacking the
spill on their own.
   _The state said the tanker, anchored in a remote cove for
repairs, continues to leak oil, which escapes containment booms
because currents keep shifting the barrier around, snagging it on
the tanker's bow. Today, the Coast Guard said salvage workers have
reinforced punctured areas of the tanker itself to prevent further
fractures.
   The tanker could be seen sitting dead calm with a half-dozen
smaller boats around it. Steam drifted from its stack, a radar arm
rotating and a helicopter on its deck. Long streamers of congealed
oil the color of chocolate milk drifted off for miles.
   _Cleanup crews planned to resume shoreline work on an
experimental basis, testing different pressurized washing systems.
   _Plans to allow a small trawler to harvest shrimp in Prince
William Sound were canceled.
   A 40-foot gray whale was found dead in an oil area Sunday, but
an autopsy revealed that it died long before the oil spill
occurred, said Alaska Department of Fish and Game spokeswoman
Sheila Nickerson.
   Biologists planned to investigate a report of a dead seal south
of Latouche Island to determine what may have killed it, said Karen
Gleason, a spokeswoman for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
   Wildlife experts say spring is a time when many animals are
found dead in Prince William Sound.
   On Friday, President Bush said he would send troops to help the
cleanup, and put the federal government virtually in control of the
effort. Exxon will continue to pay for materials and manpower.
   Air Force Lt. Gen. Thomas McInerney, chief of the Alaskan Air
Command, asked ``bases around the Pacific to find out what was
available and what the ETA (estimated time of arrival) would be for
Valdez,'' Meidt said. Today, the Coast Guard said it was brining in
six more cutters from the West Coast.
   Experts dispatched by the Pentagon began assessing the cleanup,
and more were expected today. With the help of the military,
cleanup gear was pouring into Valdez.
   ``C5-A after C5-A is bringing in equipment'' including 10 Navy
skimmers, 200,000 feet of 7-foot-deep containment boom and even
beach landing craft to move people to the oily shoreline, Meidt
said. The C5-A is the nation's largest cargo plane.
   The Navy also was sending barges outfitted as hotels so that
when coastline cleanup gets under way, workers will be housed
nearby.
   Officials said 119 dead sea otters have been counted and two
boats are waiting to unload additional dead animals. Hundreds of
dead birds have been counted, including some rare yellow-billed
loons and two eagles.
   Wildlife experts say the toll is really in the thousands because
most dead animals sink in water or remain on shore.
   About 18,000 barrels of the 240,000 spilled have been recovered
as of today, officials said. The cleanup is removing 1,000 to 1,500
barrels a day. In addition, some of the oil has evaporated in the
last 2{ weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
