<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ComputerSecurity     04-10 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Security,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Questions NSA Role in Improving Computer Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public interest group said Monday that the
National Security Agency, the nation's biggest intelligence agency,
could exert excessive control over a program to strengthen the
security of computer systems throughout the federal government.
   The group, Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility,
urged key members of Congress to focus ``particularly close
scrutiny'' on the NSA's role in helping to implement legislation
aimed at safeguarding sensitive but unclassified information in
federal computers.
   ``There is a constant risk that federal agencies, under the
guise of enhancing computer security, may find their programs _ to
the extent that they rely upon computer systems _ increasingly
under the supervision of the largest and most secretive
intelligence organization in the country,'' it said.
   In a letter sent to Capitol Hill, the group said that ``the
clandestine nature of the NSA, its classified budget, the
difficulty in overseeing its activities, and its aggressive use of
advanced technologies for eavesdropping and encryption and
decryption of communications, raise serious concerns about its
role'' in implementing the Computer Security Act.
   Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility, based in Palo
Alto, Calif., describes itself as an organization of computer
scientists and other professionals concerned about the impact of
computer technology on society.
   The letter, signed by Marc Rotenberg, head of the group's
Washington office, was sent to Reps. Dan Glickman, D-Kan.; Doug
Walgren, D-Pa., and Tim Valentine, D-N.C.
   Glickman, a member of the House Intelligence Committee, was one
of the authors of the Computer Security Act. Walgren and Valentine
are chairmen of House Science subcommittees overseeing
computer-related issues.
   Commenting on the letter, Glickman said:
   ``I think there is some legitimate concern about the role of NSA
in computer security issues. ... We need to make certain that they
don't assert power over civilian (computer) records in this
country.''
   Cynthia Beck, a spokeswoman at the NSA's public affairs office,
declined to comment on the letter.
   The NSA, headquartered at Fort Meade, Md., about halfway between
Washington and Baltimore, has a work force topping 60,000 employees
_ more than all other U.S. spy agencies combined _ and a budget
said to be upwards of $10 billion a year.
   Its main missions are eavesdropping on communications around the
world, encrypting U.S. communications and cracking foreign codes,
as well as protecting the security of U.S. military computers and
communications systems.
   Last month, the NSA reached an agreement with the National
Institute of Standards and Technology, a research arm of the
Commerce Department based in suburban Gaithersburg, Md.
   The memorandum of understanding was aimed at facilitating a
program under which the two agencies have started jointly reviewing
thousands of computer security plans submitted by offices
throughout the government.
   In its letter, the computer professionals group noted that
institute lacks the resources to fully implement the computer
security legislation and thus must rely on the NSA for assistance.
   ``This may be a marriage of convenience, but it is not a
marriage between equals,'' it said. ``NSA's resources for this
particular project are, by best estimates, at least 10 times
greater in manpower and budget than those'' of the institute.
   The letter contended that ``Congress must monitor the actions of
the NSA particularly closely. Under the Computer Security Act, the
NSA will have access to information about computer systems
throughout the entire federal government.''
   ``This is an extraordinary amount of information and literally
provides a blueprint for the management of all federal computer
systems,'' it said.
</TEXT>
