<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Lead-Schools     04-10 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lead-Schools,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Issues Guidelines on Testing Water Fountains for Lead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency today
issued guidelines to school officials on how to test for lead in
water fountains, saying more than a million fountains still being
used in schools have lead components.
   A law enacted last year required the EPA to issued the
guidelines as well as develop a list of what brand and models of
school water coolers have lead components. The law directed a
timetable for eliminating those coolers or correcting the problem.
   Lead is a toxic metal that is harmful to health even at low
levels of exposure. It can cause damage to the brain and nervous
system and lead to learning disabilities, hearing impairment, and
interference in the formation of red blood cells, according to the
EPA.
   Mike Cook, director of the EPA office that deals with drinking
water contamination, said lead in school drinking fountains is only
one of many sources from which children may be exposed to lead.
   A greater source of lead in drinking water often is the pipe
systems that carry the water.
   Nevertheless, the EPA said three manufacturers of drinking
fountain coolers in schools have estimated that more than 1 million
coolers in use contain some lead components. Two other
manufacturers did not respond and another said it made no coolers
with lead components, said Cook.
   The EPA issued more than 100 model numbers of fountain coolers
that have been found to contain lead components. The agency also
made public six models of coolers still in use that have tanks that
are lined with lead. Cook said he had no estimate how many coolers
were manufactured with lead-lined tanks.
   Young children are of particular risk from lead even with only
short-term exposure. According to the EPA, lead in drinking water
typically accounts for about 20 percent of the total lead exposure
in young children.
   Cook said the EPA considers a lead level of 20 parts per billion
in water to pose health risks. While the agency gave no levels for
all the coolers cited in today's announcement, it said that in some
coolers that had lead-lined tanks the levels were more than several
hundred parts per billion.
   ``We've found very high levels of lead in these (lead-lined)
tanks,'' Cook told reporters.
   He said the coolers found to have lead components are only a
``small fraction'' of the total number of coolers used by schools,
although the EPA has no solid figures on how many coolers are
actually in use nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MIASearch     04-10 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MIA Search,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Search for MIA Remains Set This Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three teams of American experts will travel to
Hanoi later this week for 2{ weeks of investigative work searching
for U.S. servicemen missing from the Vietnam War, the Pentagon said
Monday.
   In addition, the Vietnamese government has informed the United
States it intends ``to repatriate 21 remains, which may be those of
Americans, on April 27,'' the Pentagon said in a statement.
   The investigative teams will arrive in Hanoi on Wednesday for
what will be the fifth such joint mission working with Vietnamese
officials in the field.
   The three teams _ two comprised of investigators and one
consisting of forensic scientists _ have been told they can remain
in the country until April 30, making this the longest such mission
ever, the Pentagon added.
   Previous U.S.-Vietnamese field missions were limited to 10 days
each.
   The teams concentrate their efforts primarily on investigating
geographic areas near the last known position of so-called
``discrepancy'' cases. A discrepancy case is one in which the U.S.
government has reason to believe an American serviceman survived an
airplane crash or hostile fire.
   The joint teams also attempt to investigate live-sighting
reports and other claims about the fate of missing servicemen.
   The Pentagon said the three teams participating in this month's
work would consist of a total of 10 individuals. A separate team of
Americans will fly to Hanoi on April 27 to take possession of the
remains that Vietnam has said it will turn over then.
   According to the Pentagon, there are still 2,370 American
servicemen missing from the Vietnam War, including 1,736 in either
North or South Vietnam. In addition, 545 are listed as missing in
Laos, 83 in Cambodia and six in China.
   The Pentagon said most of the investigative work planned this
month would be concentrated in what used to be South Vietnam, in
and around the area of Danang.
</TEXT>
