<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BeetleYeast     04-10 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beetle Yeast,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beetle Bellies May Hold Key to Safer Food Supplies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Agriculture Department scientists said
today that a natural yeast found in the stomach of a beetle can
neutralize deadly farm chemicals and natural toxins that sometimes
are found in the nation's food supply.
   Entomologists Patrick F. Dowd and Samuel K. Shen of the
department's Agricultural Research Service said that if the
preliminary tests are borne out in further experiments, the yeast
could be used to remove potentially harmful toxins from livestock
feed and to clean up the environment.
   ``Although we're not yet sure of its full range of detoxifying
ability, the implication we see here is for the environmental
cleanup situations, like toxic waste dumps,'' Shen said.
   If the yeast can be developed properly, it could be
mass-produced to detoxify a wide variety of plant and chemical
toxins in the environment, he said in a report issued here by the
USDA agency.
   Shen spoke Monday at a meeting of the American Chemical Society
in Dallas, Texas. He and Dowd, along with geneticist Nancy J.
Alexander, are working on the project at the agency's northern
regional research center in Peoria, Ill.
   The yeast is found naturally in the stomach of the cigarette
beetle, a pest of stored tobacco, spices and other products. The
yeast provides the insect with vitamins and nutrients, and it
neutralizes certain toxins. This enables the insect to feed on a
wider range of plant materials.
   In laboratory tests, the researchers found that the yeast's
enzymes acted on a variety of compounds, including the insecticides
parathion and carbaryl; phytic acid, which can make some seed meals
unfit as livestock feed; and a ``precursor of aflatoxin,'' a fungal
toxin suspected of being carcinogenic.
   The scientists plan to text the yeast against aflatoxin itself.
Some of last year's drought-damaged corn crop has had high levels
of aflatoxin, a naturally occuring carcinogen.
   A number of microorganisms are already used to a limited extent
to clean water systems and soil, Shen said. But unlike those, the
yeast could be used for multiple cleanup tasks.
   Dowd, Shen's colleague, said that one of the limitations of the
yeast is that it is a slow-growing microorganism.
   ``To successfully produce this thing, we need to find a
faster-growing strain or a way to genetically transfer its
detoxifying ability to a faster-growing yeast,'' Dowd said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SocialSecurity     04-10 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commissioner Defends Agency's Plan to Use 800 Number</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social Security Commissioner Dorcas R. Hardy
on Monday defended the agency's plan to use a nationwide 800
telephone number to do most of its business with the public and
said people will be able to get through with one call 95 percent of
the time by next fall.
   She testified before the Senate Special Committee on Aging,
whose members received complaints from constituents during January
and February when the new system was flooded with calls.
   The General Accounting Office, an arm of Congress, said the
``busy rate'' jumped to 43 percent in January and was 35 percent in
February, due largely to material mailed to 36 million beneficaries
promoting use of the 800 number.
   However, the GAO said that high busy rate compared with a 17
percent ``busy'' average over the preceeding three months and a 9
percent rate _ lowest ever _ in March.
   Hardy told the panel the agency is working on the assumption
that there is a 15 percent chance a caller will get a busy signal
on the first call now and that the goal is to reduce that to 5
percent by Oct. 1 when the system is fully installed.
   It covers about 60 percent of the nation now and, when fully
installed, will feature the ability for calls to be channeled from
more busy phone centers to less busy phone centers.
   The number is the main current listing for Social Security in
areas of the nation where it is in service.
   Hardy told the committee that, with 120 million American adults
directly affected by Social Security, there will always be isolated
examples of callers encountering troubles.
   She noted that the agency has handled 22 million calls since it
started putting the 800 number system in place six months ago in
what Hardy said was the public's increasing preference to do
business by telephone when possible.
   Live operators are available from 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. Monday
through Friday to answer questions and provide basic services such
as mailing forms. Recorded messages are available nights and
weekends to provide basic information, process some actions and
take messages for callback the next business day.
   Hardy said operators schedule appointments at the nearest Social
Security office for callers who need face-to-face service.
   ``The American people want to deal with us by telephone,'' said
Hardy. ``This program was not done to cut costs, but to provide
better service.''
   The nationwide telephone system is part of the so-called Project
2000 long-range Social Security management strategy developed by
Hardy and praised recently by the House Ways and Means subcommittee
that has primary oversight responsibility over the Social Security
Administration.
   The House and Senate aging committees have no direct
jurisdiction over Social Security but typically serve as a conduit
for beneficaries upset with what they believe to be inadequate
service from the program.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITORS: The number is 1-800-234-5772.
</TEXT>
