<FIRST>r a AM-CrashLanding     04-10 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash Landing,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Crashes Plane In Palm Grove</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot who crash-landed in a grove of palm
trees next to a fast-food restaurant said Monday he expected to die
but hoped he would not take anyone with him.
   ``I got quite a jolt, but everything is looking up,'' Warren
Basler, 62, said in a hospital interview. He was being treated for
a bruised hip, a bump on the head and a swollen hand, but suffered
no broken bones.
   Basler, who owns a small cargo airline in Oshkosh, Wis., slammed
his Beechcraft B-18 into the trees Saturday when both engines
failed shortly after takeoff from Tampa International Airport.
   ``I didn't think I would get out of this alive, but I didn't
want to take a lot of people with me,'' he said.
   The plane just missed a Burger King and landed adjacent to a
busy thoroughfare.
   No one else was injured, but the $400,000, uninsured plane was
destroyed.
</TEXT>
