<FIRST>r a AM-QuayleSnub     04-10 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle Snub,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle's Republican Fund-raiser Offers Liberal Economist Little Temptation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When lifelong Democrat John Kenneth Galbraith
received an embossed invitation from Vice President Dan Quayle to
join the GOP's ``exclusive'' Senatorial Inner Circle, the economist
hastened to accept.
   ``But thus far we've not received his check for $1,000, so his
acceptance sounds a little hollow,'' Quayle spokesman David
Beckwith said Monday.
   Politicians on both sides of the fence have been chuckling over
Galbraith's wry response to the mixup that spawned his invitation
to join the group, whose annual dues go toward getting Republican
candidates elected to the Senate.
   About one-third of the Inner Circle's 6,000 members were in
Washington on Monday for various briefings and a cocktail party at
the vice president's residence.
   ``I don't think Mr. Galbraith will be there,'' said Wendy
DeMocker, a spokeswoman for the Republican Party offshoot.
   ``But we don't really consider his invitation a mistake in that
a number of very prominent Republicans were once Democrats,'' she
added. ``Look at Ronald Reagan.''
   Galbraith, who supported Gov. Michael S. Dukakis' 1988
presidential bid, was an unlikely target for a Republican
fund-raising group's direct mail form letter.
   But once the pitch was made, the Democrat latched onto it,
responding not a little sardonically to the invitation that arrived
on vice presidential stationery.
   ``It was very nice, indeed, of Sen. John Chafee to nominate me
for membership,'' Galbraith wrote in a letter, part of an exchange
reprinted in The Boston Globe. ``There are one or two things that
do trouble me....''
   Galbraith went on to give Quayle a lecture on the ethics of
offering dues-payers access to privileged ``closed door'' briefings.
   ``You are either offering information for money-making purposes
that is not available to the public at large or you are guilty of a
certain fraud in giving the impression that there will be such
advantage,'' he wrote.
   He also issued the 41-year-old vice president a tongue lashing
for what some consider a grammatical faux pas.
   ``In your letter you say that Marilyn (Quayle) and I `would like
to personally invite you to the vice president's residence.''' the
letter reads. ``I will counsel you as a leader in a great
English-speaking country against so ungracious a use of the split
infinitive.''
   Chafee, who Quayle said had sponsored Galbraith's nomination,
said he had met the Harvard University professor on occasion and
found him a pleasant man. But the Rhode Island Republican still
couldn't explain how the liberal's name was picked up by the
Republican fund raisers.
   ``As soon as I saw that Arnold Schwarzenegger and Mario Andretti
were on the list (of Inner Circle members), Galbraith's name just
leapt to mind,'' Chafee said tongue-in-cheek.
   Beckwith said the GOP had suffered similar computer hijinks in
the past, but that it was all to the greater good.
   ``When you deal with mailing lists you have to accept a few
inappropriate recipients,'' he said. ``It's happened before with a
few other non-logical people, but none quite so prominent as John
Kenneth Galbraith. ''
</TEXT>
