<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1500EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-10 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A platoon of plodding pachyderms strolled
through midtown to Central Park on Monday, to the bewilderment of
office workers and the delight of hundreds of children.
   ``New York's a jungle,'' said S.L. Grimes, 38, shaking his head
as he watched the 18 adult elephants and a youngster maneuver
through Columbus Circle.
   The parade and brief show on the park's Great Lawn was a
publicity stunt by the Ringling Bros. and Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus,
which is in town through April 23.
   Keeping them in line, tails-to-trunks, was whip-wielding Gunther
Gebel-Williams, the animal trainer who is calling this his final
tour.
   Two street cleaners followed the parade, brushing and spraying
away evidence of the elephants' passing.
   Predictably, some motorists were not amused, laying on their
horns as crosstown traffic came to a stop. Others just laughed.
   ``The elephants behave better than the people in the St.
Patrick's Day Parade,'' said a motorcycle officer serving as escort.
   In the park, the elephants chowed down on vegetables and a loaf
of bread offered by Mayor Edward I. Koch, who introduced
Gebel-Williams and spoke about his own bid for a fourth term.
   ``What he does in the ring, I do in the primary,'' Koch told the
uncomprehending schoolchildren. ``He's going to teach me the tricks
of the trade. The first is: Never trust them. Never turn your back
on them.''
   Tiffany Fregara, 9, said the show taught her that ``Elephants
aren't just smelling animals. They're intelligent.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fraternity pledges roused sleepers from
their beds and a pizza parlor closed early to provide some of the
2,145 swimmers who took a lap in a pool to set a one-day relay
record.
   The 19-hour marathon at Hamilton College last weekend apparently
broke the previous mark in the Guinness Book of World Records, set
in April 1986 by 2,135 swimmers, each of whom swam one lap at the
Syracuse YMCA.
   By 12:30 a.m. Sunday, organizers were still more than 100
swimmers shy of the mark, said Jeff VanBuren, a junior at the
college who also participated in the Syracuse event.
   ``We sent all pledges on campus to wake people up and go to
parties to round up more people,'' Van Buren said.
   A pizza shop closed early so its eight workers could each swim a
lap around 1:30 a.m., he said.
   The college in central New York has about 1,700 students, and
Clinton has another 2,100 residents.
   The feat at Hamilton to be verified by Guiness Book officials
before it would replace the previous record.
</TEXT>
