<FIRST>r a AM-Biaggi     04-10 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Biaggi,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biaggi Begins Serving Bribery Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former congressman Mario Biaggi, who
served 10 terms in the House of Representatives, entered a federal
prison Monday to begin serving a 2{-year term for accepting an
illegal gift.
   Biaggi, 71, maintained he broke no law by accepting a Florida
vacation from former New York City Democratic boss Meade Esposito.
   ``I find myself going to a federal facility today because a
friend of some 35 years was generous to me,'' Biaggi said Sunday
before boarding a plane at Newark, N.J.
   The former hero policeman arrived late Sunday at Dallas-Fort
Worth International Airport and reported to the U.S. Correctional
Facility, a minimum security prison housing 855 inmates, about 1
a.m., said Warden Ron Burkhart.
   Biaggi received institutional clothing and was assigned a place
to live at the prison, a former hospital. He was to receive several
days of orientation, a physical examination and be assigned a job,
Burkhart said.
   ``Everybody does something that is reflective of his abilities
or restrictions,'' Burkhart said. ``We're like a town within a
town.''
   At Newark, Biaggi said he had served his constituents well and
would return ``to pick up where we left off.''
   Biaggi, who parlayed a record as the most highly decorated
police officer in New York City history into a successful political
career, was convicted in September 1987.
   He also was later convicted in the Wedtech defense contractor
scandal and received an eight-year sentence, to be served after the
term he began Monday.
   Before flying to Texas, Biaggi spent the weekend fielding calls
from well-wishers and attended a farewell party Saturday. He also
spent time with his wife, Marie, who is hospitalized with Hodgkin's
disease.
</TEXT>
