<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-10 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Intensify Attack on Jalalabad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas who besieged
Jalalabad five weeks ago have attacked with new fury, launching
18,000 rockets and shells at the city in 24 hours, the government
said Monday.
   ``This big offensive was launched from afar on the city, backed
by Pakistani artillery,'' a Foreign Ministry statement said.
   Throughout the siege, the Marxist government has sought to
portray the battle as being fought 15 to 30 miles from Jalalabad
without close combat. Its latest statement appears to contradict
that by saying ``the enemy tried to retake positions they had lost
during the battl, without success.''
   As described officially, the guerrilla bombardment would be one
of the heaviest in the fight for Jalalabad, the first major
guerrilla offensive launched after completion of the Soviet
military withdrawal Feb. 15.
   Government reports on the fighting in the past three weeks
indicated the daily total of shells and rockets fired at Jalalabad,
the capital of Nagarhar province 75 miles east of Kabul, had not
exceeded 12,000.
   No confirmation of battle reports is possible because foreign
journalists are not allowed into the area, which is about 45 miles
from the Pakistan border.
   The Foreign Ministry statement, given to Western reporters by
telephone, said soldiers killed 112 enemy fighters in the 24 hours
ending at sundown Monday, including an ``Arab adviser,'' and 70
were wounded. It reported 11 civilians and three government
soldiers killed and 40 shops destroyed.
   It is not known how many people remain in Jalalabad, which
government statistics say had a population of 64,600 two years ago.
Thousands have fled since the siege began March 6.
   As usual, the government said the guerrillas were assisted by
``Pakistani militiamen and Wahhabis tied to Saudi Arabia.'' Both
nations deny direct involvement in the war.
   The Wahhabi sect of Islam is predominant in Saudi Arabia but a
small minority in Afghanistann, where 80 percent of the population
follow the mainstream Sunni branch.
   Wahhabis are a subgroup in the Sunni sect and President Najib
has sought to portray them as heretics.
   Saudi Arabia, the United States, Pakistan and China are the
major supporters of the guerrillas, who began fighting after a
communist coup in April 1978. Soviet military forces entered the
war in December 1979.
</TEXT>
