<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-HospitalKillings     04-10 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Killings,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Nurses Admit Killing 49 Patients, Hospital Ward Closed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four nurses who confessed to 49 ``mercy
killings'' of elderly patients plugged the noses of some victims
and forced water into their lungs, police said Monday.
   Police said they doubted the nurses' claim that they killed the
patients to relieve their suffering because of the way the victims
died.
   The first slayings took place in 1983 in a ward of Lainz
hospital, but most of them occurred in the last two years, police
said.
   The ward _ dubbed ``The Death Pavilion'' _ was closed Monday,
and police were checking hospital records.
   Police Chief Guenter Boegl said the nurses gave the patients,
who reportedly ranged in age from 75 to 80, forced water into the
lungs of some victims or gave overdoses of insulin or tranquilizers
to others.
   Police sources said in at least 23 cases the nurses would plug
victims' noses and force water down their throats to induce death
by forcing fluid in the lungs.
   The nurses, identified as Maria Gruber, 25; Irene Leidolf, 27;
Waltraud Wagner, 30; and Stephanie Mayer, 50; are in custody, but
no formal charges had been filed by late Monday.
   Three of the nurses were arrested Friday and the fourth Sunday.
   Police said each nurse knew the others were killing patients.
Investigators said in a few cases two nurses would act together.
   Ms. Wagner acknowledged killing 22 patients with water, police
said. A police spokesman said Ms. Mayer, who was arrested Sunday,
confessed to killing five patients, one of them with water.
   All are in investigative custody after being arrested on
suspicion of murder and attempted murder, but no formal charges
have so far been filed, pending completion of the investigation.
   The police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed reports that an arrest warrant had been issued for a
fifth nurse who is on vacation, but some reports said she may be
innocent and have been implicated in revenge by one of those
arrested.
   The fifth nurse reportedly told doctors a year ago about a
suspicious death at the hospital, but an investigation was
inconclusive.
   One police investigator said the nurses also admitted to killing
patients they considered a nuisance.
   There were fears that the number of victims might still rise.
Under investigators' review are hospital records from 1982 to 1988,
when 3,126 people died in the hospital.
   Officials rejected charges that doctors had failed to supervise
the nurses properly.
   Fritz Gschneit, who was appointed hospital director on Monday,
said it was ``thanks to the alertness of the doctors'' that the
slayings could be discovered.
   Erhard Busek, a city counselor of the Austrian People's Party,
said the city council should hold a special meeting to discuss the
entire health system and called for a committee to probe the
hospital scandal.
</TEXT>
