<DOCNO> AP890410-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Relief     04-10 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Relief,0402</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Ethiopia Says No to U.N. Plan to Aid Southern Sudanese ^By DIDRIKKE
SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia says it won't permit planned
relief shipments into southern Sudan, cutting off a key part of an
effort to avert starvation, a U.N. official said Monday.
   ``It came as a bit of a shock,'' said Vincent O'Reilly, one of
the coordinators of Operation Lifeline Sudan. It aims to provide
170,000 tons of food and supplies to 2.5 million southern Sudanese
displaced by civil war and facing starvation.
   The effort aims to prevent a repetition of the tragedy in 1988
when an estimated 250,000 to 500,000 people died. It hopes to move
the supplies before mid-May, when seasonal rains are expected to
render roads and airstrips unusable.
   The United Nations had hoped to obtain and move 20,000 metric
tons of food into southern Sudan from Ethiopia, one of Operation
Lifeline's eight routes.
   However, Ethiopian President Mengistu Haile Mariam over the
weekend sent a telex to UNICEF chief James Grant in New York saying
he could not accomodate the request, said Carlton James, a UNICEF
spokesman in Nairobi. Grant said April 3 he had received assurances
from Ethiopian officials.
   It was not immediately clear why Ethiopia is blocking passage.
   ``The Ethiopia operation has been canned,'' O'Reilly said.
   U.N. officials now hope to move the emergency supplies through
one of the operation's other corridors, possibly the route from
Kenya that already is slated to handle 25,000 tons of food and
supplies by road and air.
   However, O'Reilly said aircraft still have not been donated and
the Kenyan operation could fail without them.
   ``We are completely dependent on an integrated support system,''
said O'Reilly. ``It will succeed or fail based on whether we get a
combination of air and road transport.'' Also, only $80 million of
the $132 million needed for the operation has been pledged, he said.
   Operation Lifeline began April 1 after the Sudanese government
and rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army agreed to allow the
emergency aid to move unhampered to rebel-controlled and
government-held towns in southern Sudan.
   Some relief officials estimate as many as 2 million people may
have died since Sudan's war broke out in 1983, mostly civilians
driven from their homes who either died seeking shelter or starved
to death in refugee camps and besieged towns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
