<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--US-Korea     04-10 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--US-Korea,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three North Koreans Attend Conference Under New Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three North Koreans are attending an academic
conference in the United States under a new U.S. policy designed to
reduce tensions on the Korean peninsula, an official said Monday.
   The three arrived late last week for a conference at the
University of Hawaii and will probably visit other academic centers
in the United States as well, said the State Department official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The decision to let North Koreans visit the United States was
part of a policy shift adopted last October at the request of South
Korea.
   The U.S. ally hoped that a gesture from Washington would
encourage more openness by the North Korean government toward its
southern neighbor and arch-rival, although contacts so far between
the sides have not yielded significant progress.
   The United States does not have diplomatic ties with North
Korea, listing it among a handful of countries that support
terrorism.
   Nonetheless, the new U.S. policy lifted a ban on contacts with
North Korean officials outside the United States, and three
meetings have been held so far between American and North Korean
diplomats in Beijing. The last meeting was Feb. 28, said the
official.
   He said the meetings amounted to an exchange of views and could
not be termed negotiations, although further meetings are expected.
</TEXT>
