<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1652EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--Drugs-Ships     04-10 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Drugs-Ships,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard to Ease Seizure Rules in Drug Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard is making permanent its
decision not to seize vessels when only small qualtities of drugs
are found on board.
   The agency announced Monday a rulemaking that would subject the
owners of commercial fishing vessels to a summons in cases when
personal-use quantities of illegal drugs are found on their ships.
   The issuing of summonses in such cases was instituted on an
interim basis Feb. 16 and the rulemaking would make that permanent,
the Coast Giard said.
   Before that, vessels had been subject to immediate seizure when
any quantity of drugs was found.
   The new regulation covers commercial fishing, fish processing
and fish tender vessels.
   Separate laws extend similar protection to ferry boats, cruise
ships and other commercial vessels in cases in which a passenger
brings small qualtities of drugs on board. However, these vessels
remain subject to seizure if there is evidence that the master or
operator of the vessel was aware of the violation.
</TEXT>
