<FIRST>r a AM-CostlyKits     04-10 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costly Kits,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Captain Shocked at Cost of Repair Kits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has paid Lockheed Corp. more
than $26 million for 47 repair kits for its C-5 cargo planes and
may buy 100 more despite warnings that the kits are overpriced, a
newspaper reported.
   Items in the kits include a business card-sized metal plate
priced at $114 and a splicer costing $362, the Dayton Daily News
said Sunday, citing an Air Force cost analyst's report.
   The kits are designed to fix the aircraft's landing gear main
frames, outer wings, and wheel wells, and part of its lower
fuselage in the event of a major crash, the newspaper said.
   According to internal Air Force memos and reports obtained by
the newspaper, Air Force officials have questioned the cost of and
the need for the kits, as well as the decision to buy them from
Lockheed.
   Capt. Kathy Johnson, a cost-price analyst, visited a Lockheed
plant in Marietta, Ga., last June and later recommended reviewing
the kits' 6,000 types of parts.
   Ms. Johnson cited apparent overpricing and warned it could lead
to negative publicity for the Air Force, the Daily News said.
   Eric M. Thorson, an assistant Air Force secretary, echoed her
fears in a memo one month later after learning that a limited
review of the orders found 39 percent of the parts to be
overpriced, the newspaper said.
   Col. Allan V. Cummings, a spokesman for the Air Force Logistics
Command at Wright Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton, said the
figures cited were only Lockheed's proposed prices.
   ``The Air Force should not be chastised for paying prices that
we've not finally agreed upon,'' he said.
   Lt. Gen. Claudius E. Watts III, the comptroller of the Air
Force, noted in a memo that money and kits were changing hands
while neither contractor nor buyer could say what the kits
contained or what they ultimately would cost, the Daily News said.
</TEXT>
