<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     04-10 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turmoil in Iran Seen as Barring Progress in Talks With Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political turmoil in Iran is likely to prevent
significant progress in a new round of peace talks with Iraq
expected to be held soon, an exiled Iranian said Monday.
   Shahram Chubin, an exiled Iranian historian, said that with two
of his senior aides losing their posts in the past few weeks,
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran would probably stick to
a hard-line course rather than expose himself to criticism at home.
   ``And of course, Iraq would have little incentive to offer too
much if it is not getting an response,'' said Chubin, who worked at
the London Institute for Strategic Studies before taking a teaching
post at Geneva's prestigious Graduate Institute of International
Affairs.
   Iranian Foreign Ministry officials and U.N. officials met last
week to lay groundwork for a new round of talks between Velayati
and his Iraqi counterpart, Tariq Aziz. They have agreed to hold the
talks in the near future at an undisclosed site near U.N.
headquarters in New York, but no date has been set. The talks have
been deadlocked since November over Iran's insistence that Iraqi
troops withdraw from Iranian territory, while Iraq insists that the
first step should be the clearing of war debris from the Shatt
al-Arab waterway on the border.
   Before a U.N.-brokered U.N. agreement last August, at least 1
million people were killed or wounded in the eight-year Persian
Gulf War. Some estimates of the dead alone surpass 1 million, and
the economic cost totals hundreds of billions of dollars.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Chubin noted that
ousted Deputy Foreign Minister Javad Mohammad Larijani and Jaffar
Mahallati, Iran's U.N. ambassador, were both associates of
Velayati. He also said there is some uncertainty whether Velayati
himself will last.
   Chubin said pragmatists in the Foreign Ministry are now
struggling to push their views while radicals like Interior
Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashami ``are making as much capital as
possible.''
   The historian predicted that Khomeini will avoid a definitive
stand, ``sometimes taking one side and sometimes the other.''
   ``Khomeini is too clever to entrust the future of the Islamic
Republic to one faction,'' he said.
   Also in Geneva, the International Committee of the Red Cross
said 66 Iraqi prisoners of war were repatriated on Monday after
their unilateral release by Iran.
   The Geneva-based humanitarian agency said the prisoners were all
wounded, sick or elderly. Four other prisoners refused to be
repatriated and remained in Iran, it said.
   Iran had said it would free the prisoners to mark the 10th
anniversary of the founding of the Islamic Republic.
   More than 100,000 war prisoners are still held by Iran and Iraq,
according to Red Cross estimates. Only 2,295 have been released
since the cease-fire.
</TEXT>
