<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Mayors     04-10 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Mayors,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors Conference Focuses on Ethnic Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Teddy Kollek told foreign mayors Monday
at a conference on ethnic conflict in cities that Jerusalem's Jews,
Moslems, and Christians ``will never integrate.''
   However, he also played down the impact on Jerusalem of the
16-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied lands, saying:
``There are tensions, but they are less than you see on your TV.''
   During the uprising, 422 Palestinians and 18 Israelis have been
killed, including two Arabs and a Jew in Jerusalem. Israel seized
Arab east Jerusalem when it captured the occupied territories from
Arab neighbors in the 1967 Middle East war, and it later made the
city its capital.
   In the conference, Kollek described the problems of governing
Jerusalem for about 30 mayors from 16 countries, including the
United States.
   ``We'll always have Jews, Moslems and Christians in this city,''
Kollek said. ``But unlike in other cities, here they will never
integrate. It is not their purpose.''
   Kollek said city officials must also deal with sometimes
clashing Christian denominations.
   ``There are 40 different Christian denominations in Jerusalem.
Sometimes these groups are very competitive amongst themselves over
the holy places, rights, the times they are allowed to pray in
various churches,'' Kollek said.
   Speaking after Kollek's address, Mayor William Boner of
Nashville, Tenn., elicited laughter when he said: ``Mayor Kollek,
after hearing you, I don't think I have any ethnic conflicts in
Nashville.''
   In Nashville, Boner said, blacks make up about 22 percent of the
city's population of about 500,000.
   ``As a group, blacks in Nashville are poor, they're less healthy
.... They are more prone to crime and drug abuse,'' Boner said.
``Such disparity has produced resentment, despair and crucial
issues for we mayors.''
   Mayor Joanne Benjamin of Los Gatos, Calif., said one of the main
challenges facing her city of 28,000 people was providing education
for the children of Hispanic and Vietnamese immigrants. She said
many speak little or no English.
</TEXT>
