<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Whistle-blowers     04-10 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Whistle-blowers,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Whistle-Blower Bill Into Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislaton Monday
expanding job protection to federal whistle-blowers, a revamped
version of a measure vetoed late last year by then-President Reagan.
   ``The true whistle-blower is a public servant of the highest
order,'' Bush said at the signing ceremony in the Old Executive
Office Building attended by the measure's congressional sponsors.
   The legislation will provide increased protection from firing
and demotion for federal employees who disclose misdeeds and
mismanagement in the agenices where they work.
   Bush called the bill ``a significant improvement'' over the one
Reagan vetoed.
   The new measure does not contain a provison, opposed by Reagan,
that would have permitted the Office of Special Counsel to go to
court on behalf of whistle-blowers. Reagan protested that this
would have resulted in federal agencies battling each other in
court.
   Under the new act, employees fighting for their jobs would face
less stringent standards of proof that their firing or demotion
resulted from whistle-blowing.
   The Office of the Special Counsel, established eight years ago
to investigate civil service abuses, will become an independent
agency under the new law. The office now is an arm of the Merit
Systems Protection Board and has been criticized in Congress on
grounds that it has done little to assist whistle-blowers.
   Whistle-blowers now will be able to take their cases directly to
the board if the special counsel does not act within 120 days.
   Joining Bush in the signing ceremony were the legislation's
co-authors, Sens. Carl Levin, D-Mich., and Rep. Frank Horton,
R-N.Y., and other sponsors.
   ``We used to think of a whistle-blower as some guy in a funny
hat running around on a field with a black-and-white shirt on,
always throwing down the flag,'' Bush said.
   ``But that might well be an apt comparison to the business at
hand because whistle blowing is, after all, the one who cries foul
to waste, fraud and abuse.''
   ``I share the determination of Congress that we do everything
possible to ensure that these dedicated men and women should not be
fired or rebuked or suffer financially for their honesty and good
judgment,'' he added.
   However, in a separate statement, Bush also voiced confidence in
agency heads.
   ``Although whistle-blowers clearly can and do contribute to
better government, these managers respond regularly to a variety of
problems, including those disclosed by whistle-blowers, without
special statutory provisons and procedures,'' the statement said.
   Bush earlier in the day praised volunteers of another sort,
signing a proclamation at a Rose Garden ceremony making this
National Volunteer Week.
   ``You're winning because you refuse to believe that it can't be
done,'' he told an invited audience of individuals and
representatives of various volunteer organizations.
   ``I always like to remember that there is no exercise better for
the human heart than reaching down and lifting someone else up,''
Bush said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Reaction     04-10 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Reaction,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Reacts to Spill With Tears and Offers of Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nation's pain and outrage are being felt
in the governor's office, where staffers have answered thousands of
calls from Americans touched by scenes of oil-choked animals on
blackened beaches.
   Gov. Steve Cowper's staff have answered as many as 1,200 phone
calls a day since the Exxon Valdez ruptured on a reef south of
Valdez on March 24, dumping 10.1 million gallons of oil into Prince
William Sound.
   The switchboard really lights up each day after the network TV
news broadcasts on the East Coast, when it's still early afternoon
in Juneau. The most emotional calls come in response to televised
scenes of dead or suffering animals.
   ``People call here crying,'' said Laury Roberts Scandling,
Cowper's director of constituent relations. ``Their first reaction
is outrage and anger.''
   Some offer sympathy or opinion, ask how to help, offer money.
Others try to sell products to help in the cleanup.
   The unusually hectic pace the oil spill has imposed on Cowper's
office has taken its toll on Cowper and his staff of 20.
   ``A lot of us are tired,'' Scandling said late last week. ``Our
families don't see us. People are tense and sometimes we all have
to stop.''
   Cowper came down with the flu late last week and had to work
from the governor's mansion for two days.
   ``All of us have colds,'' Scandling said. ``It really knocked
Cowper down.''
   Cowper's wife, Michael, has come in daily to answer calls with
the seven staffers who share the duty. Andy Spear, a former state
environmental official, was hired to set up a call-screening
procedure and field technical inquiries.
   In addition to calls, Cowper's office each day has received
about 50 spill-related letters, several telegrams, product samples
and countless messages on the office telecopier.
   ``The fax goes 24 hours a day,'' Spear said.
   One manufacturer mailed a bottle of crude oil and an absorbent
to demonstrate the absorbent's effectiveness. ``It smelled up my
office,'' Scandling said.
   Spear, who used to head the state's oil-pollution control
program, refers the samples to officials on the spill scene. Some
of the products have been used, he said, citing a cork material
that had been adopted as an absorbent.
   Although Spear said some suggestions border on the ``wacko,''
even those are not immediately dismissed.
   A California woman who suggested pouring Dawn dishwashing liquid
on the oil slick to break it up was not far off the mark. That
brand has long been used to clean oil off sea mammals and birds,
Spear noted.
   ``You never know,'' he said. ``I hate to discourage anyone who
may have a good idea.''
   Most of the letters, however, are lean on ideas and thick on
emotions.
   ``Probably nine out of 10 letters begin with, `I'm sad, I'm very
angry, I'm outraged,' '' Scandling said.
   A Florida man wrote a terse letter to say had destroyed his
Exxon credit card. A Coloradan said he had canceled his 11-week
summer vacation in Alaska although he knew it would not take him
near Prince William Sound.
   ``Long I've heard about no taxes in Alaska _ the oil people pay
for everything,'' he wrote. ``Well, you sold your soul and now are
paying the price.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AbortionLobbying     04-10 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Lobbying,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Activists Take Their Case To Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion-Politics Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of abortion rights activists, buoyed
by the record turnout for their march on the Capitol, lobbied
members of Congress on Monday as stalwarts of the women's movement
predicted that their effort will leave a lasting impression on the
Supreme Court.
   That view, however, was not shared by at least one member of the
Bush administration _ Vice President Dan Quayle.
   The march was ``nothing unusual in this town,'' he said. ``I
don't believe the Supreme Court should be, nor do we expect it to
be, swayed by a demonstration. That is not the way the system is
supposed to work. They are there to render a legal opinion.''
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said, ``Everyone
has the right to march and present their views. It appears that it
was a very successful march over the weekend in terms of the number
of people they wanted to get here. They presented their views very
effectively and that's good.''
   Advocates who took part Sunday in the largest abortion rights
rally got their first taste of lobbying as they traveled from House
offices to Senate buildings, delivering information packages
containing a 30-minute ``Abortion for Survival'' video and pressing
their cases.
   In most instances, lawmakers were absent and activists met with
congressional staff. But the circumstances did little to dampen
their enthusiasm.
   ``We'd like very much for him to see it,'' Jeanette D. Newsom,
of Sylva, N.C., told a staff member for Republican Sen. Jesse Helms
as her husband Gene presented the packet.
   The couple _ he's a farmer, she's a librarian _ from the tiny
town of 1,700 near Asheville have written Helms in support of the
Equal Rights Amendment, nuclear freeze and environmental issues.
They traveled from Sylva to march in the demonstration and lobby in
person.
   ``After lobbying on the state level, we naively assumed we could
do it here in Washington, D.C.,'' said Gene Newsom before the
couple headed to the offices of North Carolina's other senator,
Democrat Terry Sanford.
   Hundreds of thousands of activists, including mothers with small
children, Hollywood stars and college students, converged on the
Capitol to show their support for the 1973 Supreme Court decision
that legalized abortion.
   Law enforcement officials estimated the crowd at 300,000 but
Eleanor Smeal, president of the Fund for the Feminist Majority, put
the total at 600,000.
   The turnout far exceeded the 90,000 people who gathered for a
March 1986 abortion rights rally in Washington and the numbers
organizers had predicted. Leaders said the response will have an
impact on the Supreme Court.
   ``Nobody in public office isn't affected by a huge outpouring,''
said Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women.
   Questioned about lobbying members of Congress rather than
focusing on the court, Yard noted that lawmakers are in contact
with the nine justices.
   ``Do you think the leadership in this body doesn't talk to the
Supreme Court? Sure they do,'' Yard said. ``Do you think members of
the Bush administration don't talk to the Supreme Court? Sure they
do.''
   Francoise Jacobsohn, president of the New York City chapter of
NOW, said the congressional lobbying was ``a logical progression of
what we did yesterday. We have a political army.''
   ``We cannot stand for erosion. We have been complacent,'' said
Jacobsohn, who said in the past the attitude has been, ``we already
fought this fight, why do we have to fight it again.''
   Activists plan to gather again on April 26 when the court will
hear arguments in a Missouri case that pro-choice and anti-abortion
forces agree could significantly alter the ruling that gave women
the right to an abortion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
