<FIRST>r a AM-DerailmentLawsuit     04-10 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Derailment Lawsuit,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittsburgh Sues Conrail Over Derailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city has sued Conrail and Monsanto Co. to
recover the costs of cleaning up a train derailment and chemical
spill that forced the evacuation of more than 10,000 residents two
years ago.
   In the lawsuit filed Friday in federal court, the city said it
spent about $225,000 for police and fire protection, evacuation of
the Bloomfield neighborhood and cleanup of the spill.
   City solicitor Dan Pellegrini said Monday the city had failed to
negotiate a settlement with Conrail and Monsanto and was suing
because the statute of limitations was running out.
   Adjacent Allegheny County, which Pellegrini said had incurred
about $25,000 in expenses, also has sued.
   A Conrail freight train derailed along a curve and knocked a
second train, carrying phosphorous oxychloride, off parallel tracks
in the April 11, 1987, accident.
   The chemical is a gasoline additive produced by Monsanto that
can react chemically with moisture in the lungs to produce
hydrochloric acid.
   Bloomfield was evacuated twice, on April 11 and April 12, and 70
people were hospitalized for treatment of skin, eye and lung
irritation.
   The lawsuit charges the defendants were negligent in failing to
maintain and label their equipment, in using an unsafe tank car and
transporting the chemical through heavily populated areas.
   Monsanto attorney Randy Struk said a March 1988 study had
determined that burning phonograph records from one of the freight
cars caused the only major risk in the accident. The records
released hydrogen chloride gas, he said.
   Struk said the Monsanto spill ``did not leave any adverse health
or environmental effects on the Bloomfield community.''
   Spokeswoman Kathy Meehan said Conrail had no comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
