<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FairnessDoctrine     04-10 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fairness Doctrine,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Opposes Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is recommending that
President Bush veto any legislation that would write into law the
fairness doctrine and require that broadcasters air opposing views
on controversial issues.
   In a letter to Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., Assistant Attorney
General Thomas M. Boyd said the doctrine, which the Federal
Communications Commission repealed in 1987, was outdated, hindered
free expression and unduly discriminated against broadcasters in
favor of the print media.
   Dingell, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee,
introduced a bill this year that would make the doctrine law. The
bill was passed by the Energy and Commerce telecommunications and
finance subcommittee last week and is to be considered by the full
committee Tuesday.
   It is virtually identical to a measure passed by Congress in
1987 but vetoed by then-President Reagan. The present measure is
expected to pass Congress again.
   Although Bush has not indicated his view on the fairness
doctrine since he took office, he said on the campaign trail last
year he was against such a law.
   Boyd said the White House Office of Management and Budget had
advised him that enactment of a bill ``would not be in accord with
the program of the president.''
   A copy of Boyd's letter to Dingell, dated last Wednesday and
obtained Monday, said the Supreme Court turned ``traditional First
Amendment analysis on its head'' in a landmark 1969 ruling on the
fairness doctrine.
   In that ruling, the court held that the fairness doctrine did
not violate the First Amendment rights of broadcasters because the
inherent scarcity of broadcast outlets required the government to
regulate broadcasters for the public good.
   Boyd, as did the FCC in its 1987 repeal, said there no longer is
a scarcity of outlets because of cable television and satellite
broadcasting.
   Boyd also noted that the Supreme Court in 1974 overturned a
Florida law that required newspapers to provide space to political
candidates who had been criticized by the newspaper.
   The court at that time said the law was an unconstitutional
intrusion on editors and rejected the argument ``that the actual
scarcity of the print media justified a content-based regulation,''
Boyd wrote.
   Boyd wrote that ``the purpose of the First Amendment is to help
assure that the people are adequately informed about public issues,
not to assure that they are adequately informed by one particular
medium or group of media.''
   Boyd noted that the FCC also said the doctrine ``inhibits
broadcasters from presenting controversial issues'' and therefore
``the public is deprived of a marketplace of ideas unencumbered by
the hand of government. ...''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
