<FIRST>r a AM-CalifHeat     04-10 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Calif Heat,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fog Chases Away Northern California Heat Wave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fog and an ocean breeze rolled in over the
coast Monday, ending a sizzling streak of record hot days and
ensuring traditional chilly weather for the Giants home opener at
Candlestick Park.
   Inland, however, parts of the San Joaquin Valley were untouched
by the breeze and temperatures were expected to reach near record
levels again with a high of 97 degrees forecast in Bakersfield.
   Unseasonably hot weather over California has been caused by a
high pressure system between California and Hawaii that held the
storm track to the north, the National Weather Service said.
   Southern California got a breath of fresh air during the weekend
when coastal breezes sent temperatures plunging more than 15
degrees in many areas, ending the hottest April week on record.
Sunday's high in downtown Los Angeles was 76 degrees, a sharp drop
from Saturday's 91 and Thursday's 106, a record high for an April
day.
   San Francisco's forecast for Tuesday predicted morning fog
giving way to sunshine and temperatures in the mid 70s to mid 80s.
The baseball team's home opener was scheduled Tuesday night.
   The San Francisco region's heat wave sent temperatures into the
90s for the fourth straight day Sunday and drove sunbathers to
beaches, shoreside boardwalks and reservoirs. Sunday was the fifth
straight day of record temperatess than $50,000 a year.
   Many businesses complain that the law, by weighting them down
with paperwork, could have the opposite effect by encouraging
abandonment of employee health insurance.
