<FIRST>u w AM-League-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru a0647 04-10 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-League-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Rejects US-Endorsed Plan For Palestinian Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs PLO comment after 9th graf pvs, Shamir's plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League rejected on Monday the
U.S.-endorsed Israeli proposal for holding elections among
Palestinians on the West Bank and in Gaza and said it would send a
delegation here next month to meet with Secretary of State James A.
Baker III.
   Clovis Maksoud, the league's representative here, denounced the
proposal by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir as a device ``to buy more
time for Israel and to diffuse the mounting pressure within the
United States and throughout the world as well as to thwart the
Palestinian uprising.''
   Maksoud, at a news conference, said Shamir was seeking to find
through elections ``a boneless or a toothless Palestinian
negotiator who ratifies his conquest.''
   He said the league delegation would include Farouk Kaddoumi, who
the Palestine Liberation Organization calls its foreign minister,
and ministers from Saudi Arabia and Algeria. Such a session would
be Baker's first meeting with a PLO official.
   ``Shamir ignores the obvious assumption that the PLO is the
Palestinian people and that any search outside its framework means
that negotiations is not a serious or consequential pursuit but
rather an exercise in futility,'' Maksoud said.
   Shamir outlined his proposal last week to President Bush at the
White House and gained the president's endorsement. Shamir and Bush
made statements ruling out an independent Palestinian state in the
territories the Arabs lost to Israel in the 1967 Six-Day War.
   ``The plan is totally unacceptable,'' Maksoud said. ``The whole
objective of the Shamir plan is to derail the achievements of the
intefadah (the Arabic word for uprising), to undo what has been
established _ namely the declaration of the Palestinian state _ to
undermine the PLO, to circumvent the international consensus. ...''
   Maksoud met earlier in the day with Paul Hare, the acting deputy
assistant secretary of state for the Near East, and other State
Department officials.
   Shamir's plan has been rejected as well by the PLO.
   In Tunis, Tunisia, the PLO rejected Shamir's proposal. The PLO
news agency, Wafa, said in a dispatch attributed to an unnamed
spokesman:
   ``The idea of elections is totally unacceptable in the shadow of
Israeli occupation and this proposal is nothing but a maneuver
aimed at undermining efforts undertaken by several world powers to
achieve a just settlement in the Middle East.''
   A State Department spokesman, Richard Boucher, said Yasser
Arafat's organization should ``explore practical ways to advance
the peace process.''
   He declined to say whether the United States had asked the PLO
to endorse Shamir's proposal.
   Israel refuses to negotiate with the PLO, which it holds
accountable for terrorism against the Jewish state. After Arafat
publicly renounced terrorism, the United States dropped its ban on
dealing with the PLO and began talks in Tunisia with PLO officials.
   Shamir's propsal is to have Palestinian leaders elected on the
West Bank and in Gaza to negotiate with Israel self-rule for the
territories for five years, to be followed by negotiations among
Israel, the Palestinians, Egypt and Jordan on a final settlement.
   Maksoud praised Bush for insisting last week on an end to what
the president called Israel's ``occupation'' of the West Bank and
Gaza. The Arab League official said the statement was a positive
one.
   Maksoud said the league's delegation would visit Washington in
mid-May. Presumably he meant after Baker's return from Moscow,
where he will hold talks May 10-11. All 21 Arab countries and the
PLO are members of the Arab League.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
