<DOCNO> AP890410-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--NewsroomTampering     04-10 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Newsroom Tampering,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former News Director Charged In Computer-Tampering Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former news editor at WTSP-Channel 10 was
charged Monday with scheming with a colleague to tap into the
confidential computer system of a competing television station.
   Terry Cole, 32, surrendered at the Hillsborough State Attorney's
office on a conspiracy charge and two counts of computer-related
crimes, said Sam Jones, head of the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement in Tampa.
   Cole was fired in March, along with Michael I. Shapiro, 33,
assistant news director at the ABC affiliate.
   Shapiro was charged with 14 counts of computer-related crimes in
an alleged series of raids on the computer news files of Channel
13, the CBS affiliate. He has been released on his own recognizance
and hasn't come to trial yet.
   When Shapiro was arrested Feb. 7, investigators said they had no
information that anyone else was involved, but since have obtained
evidence that ``Terry Cole took part, had full knowledge, gave his
blessings,'' Jones said Monday.
   Shapiro is a former assignment manager at Channel 13 where he
helped set up security for the computer system.
</TEXT>
