<FIRST>u i AM-AuschwitzConvent     04-10 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz Convent,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Leader Says Crosses Erected at Disputed Convent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carmelite nuns living at the site of the Nazi death
camp at Auschwitz in Poland have erected crosses at their disputed
convent, the head of France's Jewish community disclosed Monday.
   In a letter of protest to French Roman Catholic Cardinal Albert
Decourtray, Theo Klein said three crosses have been erected at the
convent of Carmelite nuns, a building used by the Nazis as a
warehouse during World War II to store the deadly Zyklon B gas.
   Klein, president of the Representative Council of French Jewish
Organizations, was, along with Decourtray, among the signatories to
a 1987 agreement for the convent to moved from the site by February
1989.
   The letter, dated April 6, was made public in Washington by the
World Jewish Congress.
   ``A 23-foot cross has gone up on top of the largest Jewish
graveyard in the world,'' Elan Steinberg, Executive Director of the
congress, said in Washington. ``This will further harm already
strained relations with the Vatican.''
   The erection of the crosses marks the latest episode in a bitter
clash between Jewish leaders and the Vatican over the presence of a
dozen nuns on the site that has become a memorial to the 6 million
Jews murdered by the Nazis.
   In Paris, Klein told The Associated Press the letter was the
most recent in a series of exchanges over the crosses.
   ``There's one on the building, another wooden one on a place
called the `Way of the Cross' and a third, smaller one on the gate
next to three stars of David,'' Klein said in a telephone interview.
   He said the erection of crosses contradicted assurances he
received earlier this year from Polish Catholic authorities that
the nuns had agreed to move from the convent, founded in 1984 as a
center for prayer and meditation.
   People returning from recent visits to Auschwitz were ``very
shocked to see that the very nuns who were supposedly getting ready
to move from the convent were, in fact, getting ready to settle in
permanently,'' Klein said.
   Under the 1987 agreement, signed by representatives of the
Vatican and Jewish leaders, the convent was to be moved to another
site by Feb. 22, 1989.
   Decourtray said in February he would urge the nuns be moved to
temporary housing if new quarters were not ready by July 22. Klein
has urged that the nuns be moved before July.
   The nuns have agreed to go once a new convent is ready.
   In Washington, Steinberg said the World Jewish Congress was
informed by a French Jewish delegation that the nuns had undertaken
improvements in the building they occupy and added the cross since
another delegation visited the site last December.
</TEXT>
