<FIRST>r w AM-NorthSubpoena     04-10 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Subpoena,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Asks Denial of North Subpoena for Surveillance Records</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government asked the judge in Oliver
North's trial Monday to deny North's request for surveillance
records on foreigners involved in negotiations to free U.S.
hostages.
   The Justice Department said North's attempt near the end of the
trial to subpoena the records was calculated to ``graymail the
United States'' by threatening disclosure of secrets to force
dismissal of the charges.
   ``This is a last-ditch effort to use classified information as a
weapon rather than as proof,'' said the department, which also
filed under court seal an affidavit by Mary C. Lawton, counsel for
intelligence policy.
   ``The information sought receives the highest protection under
the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act, and the harm to national
security of disclosure of this information would be enormous,'' the
department said in papers filed by Assistant Attorney General
Edward S.G. Dennis Jr., head of the criminal division.
   As an alternative to furnishing records of the surveillances,
the department proposed a stipulation of facts about eavesdropping
by intelligence agencies approved by the secret Foreign
Intelligence Surveillance Court.
   The stipulation document included an indication that Iranian
arms dealer Manucher Ghorbanifar was among those who were the
object of surveillances conducted in Washington by unnamed
intelligence agencies.
   The Justice Department said surveillances were conducted between
Oct. 1985 and September 1986 of several foreigners _ none named _
at the request of then-CIA Director William Casey.
   Included were ``several foreign nationals who purported to be,
or have direct access to, representatives of the government of
Iran,'' according to the proposed stipulation.
   ``The surveillances related to negotiations concerning the
release of American hostages in Lebanon,'' the document said.
   On Oct. 7, 1985, the department, with the authorization of
then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III, sought court approval for
surveillance of two foreigners, the document said.
   The next day, North met in Washington with Ghorbanifar as well
as Israeli arms dealers Al Schwimmer and Yaacov Nimrodi, according
to the report of the presidential commission headed by former Sen.
John Tower.
   Another surveillance of ``one of the same two individuals'' was
approved on April 2, 1986.
   On the next day, North and CIA consultant George Cave met in
Washington with Ghorbanifar, according to the Tower report.
   The meetings, which continued April 4, 1986, involved
discussions about the forthcoming mission to Tehran led by North
and former National Security Adviser Robert McFarlane.
   The Justice Department document also detailed another round of
surveillances approved by Meese in September 1986.
   These surveillances coincided with meetings North and Cave had
in Washington with representatives of an Iranian group that
reportedly included the son of Hashemi Rafsanjani, the speaker of
Iran's parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
