<FIRST>r w AM-Submarines-Cancer 170   04-10 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Submarines-Cancer, 170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cancer Rate Higher On Subs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has performed a medical statistical
study that suggests sailors serving aboard nuclear-missile
submarines are more likely to develop cancer than their civilian
counterparts, a trade publication said Monday.
   Navy News and Undersea Technology, the publication, said the
study had been criticized by one outside researcher as utilizing
procedures that were bound to be biased in the Navy's favor.
   Nonetheless, the study suggests a 37 percent difference between
cancer rates for the general population and sailors aboard nuclear
missile submarines.
   The publication said the statistical tabulation reported an
``observed'' rate of cancer cases among missile submarine personnel
of 54, compared to an ``expected'' rate for the general population
of 39.4.
   The Navy declined immediate comment on Monday, saying it hoped
to release a statement on the matter Tuesday.
   The study was originally requested in 1974 by Rep. Pat
Schroeder, D-Colo.,
</TEXT>
