<DOCNO> AP890410-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WomeninMedia     04-10 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Women in Media,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Media Criticized on Female Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's newspapers and radio and television
stations discriminate against women in pay, promotions and news
coverage, a study released Monday at a conference on ``Women, Men
and Media'' said.
   ``Media coverage of and by women is inexcusably poor,'' Junior
Bridge, a Washington media consultant, told delegates to the
conference sponsored by the Gannett Foundation.
   The study, financed largely by the foundation, showed that 6
percent of news media jobs as publisher, president or vice
president are held by women. The share was 6 percent for
newspapers, 3 percent for television and 8 percent for radio.
   It said women in media earn less than two-thirds as much as men,
64 cents for every dollar paid to a male employe. Comparing women
and men, the study said women average $9,074 less per year in
television, $7,793 less on newspapers and $3,323 less in radio.
   Jean Gaddy Wilson of the University of Missouri, who conducted
the study of hiring and promotion, said the survey covered 1,599
daily newspapers, l,219 television stations and 1,091 radio
stations.
   John Seigenthaler, editor of The Nashville Tennesseean and
president of the American Society of Newspaper Editors, asked to
comment on the report, said, ``It's a cliche to talk about a
comfort level, and that good old boys are more comfortable with
good old boys than they are with anybody else, but I am afraid that
those numbers document that.''
   ``Until a majority of the papers begin to insist that something
be done about the comfort level of good old boys like me, we are
not going to make the sort of progress that justice requires,'' he
said.
   Officials of the Radio and Television News Directors Association
were away from their office and not available to comment, an
employe in the office said.
   The study of television and newspaper coverage was conducted by
Ms. Bridge and Kathy Bonk, co-director of Communications
Consortium, a self-described public interest media center based in
Washington.
   It showed that on the three major nightly television news
programs during February, 15.8 percent of the stories were reported
by women.
   In 10 newspapers, 27 percent of the bylines on the front pages
in March were female, 11 percent of the people quoted were female
and 24 percent of the photographs included women. Unlike the men,
the women usually appeared in group shots with family members.
   By averaging where the papers ranked in the three categories,
the study rated USA TODAY, Gannett's Washington-based national
newspaper, as ``best'' with 41 percent of its front-page bylines
female and with women in 41 percent of its front-page pictures.
There were references to women by name in 21 percent of the paper's
front-page stories.
   The New York Times rated ``worst,'' with women getting 16 per
cent of front-page bylines and appearing in 16 percent of
front-page photographs. Women were referred to by name in 5 percent
of front-page stories.
   The Houston Chronicle and Atlanta Constitution tied for second,
followed in order by the Seattle Times, Washington Post, Los
Angeles Times, Miami Herald, St. Louis Post-Dispatch and Chicago
Tribune.
   The study said 25 percent of newspaper news staffs are women,
while 75 percent of the business office staffs are women. In
television, women account for 32 percent of the news staffs and 77
percent of the business staffs. In radio, the figures are 34
percent for news and 83 percent for television.
   The study of television networks showed that women reported 22.2
percent of the stories on the CBS Evening News in February, 14.4
percent of the stories on the corresponding NBC program and 10.5
percent on ABC.
   It also said that 13.7 percent of the ABC stories, 10.2 percent
of the CBS stories and 8.9 percent of the NBC stories focused on
women as their subject.
   Diana Meehan, director of the Institute for the Study of Men and
Women at the University of Southern California, said she is making
a study of women executives in television and has found that the 30
highest-ranking ones all were the firstborn or only child in their
families.
   In addition, she said, they are all from families that ``had
some wordly success,'' all broke into the business as writers and
all attended universities in the Midwest or in New York, not Ivy
League schools. By comparison, she said, top male executives often
have attended Ivy League schools and broke into television by some
route other than writing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
