<DOCNO> AP890410-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Divorce-Embryos     04-10 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Divorce-Embryos,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman's Right Outweighs Man's In Divorce-Embryo Case, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman's right to become pregnant in a
test-tube baby procedure should outweigh her estranged husband's
decision not to become a father, the woman's attorney said Monday.
   Mary Sue Davis, 28, and Junior Lewis Davis, 30, are getting a
divorce and are at odds over what to do with seven of her eggs that
are fertilized with his sperm and kept in frozen storage.
   Davis, who filed a divorce petition in February, referred to the
embryos as ``property jointly owned'' and said he doesn't want Mrs.
Davis to become pregnant with them.
   Mrs. Davis considers the matter a custody battle and has said
the embryos are life that should be taken to term by being
implanted inside her.
   The Blount County, Tenn., couple have participated in an
in-vitro fertilization program in Knoxville for six years in an
effort to become parents.
   The two were married in 1979. Mrs. Davis said she had had five
tubal pregnancies, resulting in the rupture of one fallopian tube
and surgery to tie the other, by the time she and her husband began
the in-vitro fertilization program.
   Mrs. Davis' attorney, J.G. Christenberry, said in an interview
that because a woman can do more for the eggs _ produce a child _
than a man can, her wants should outweigh his when issues such as
this arise.
   Christenberry said he hoped the Blount County Circuit Court case
could be heard by July. In a two-page court response filed last
week, he said Mrs. Davis maintains ``she is the proper party to be
awarded the custody of her embryos for her exclusive use.''
   The Davises acknowledge that the case is an unusual one
incorporating medical technology, personal rights and ethics, and
that there apparently are no previous court cases like it.
   Many in-vitro fertilization clinics require couples to sign
written agreements regarding the fate of their frozen embryos in
the event of the man and woman's death or divorce. However, medical
officials have conceded it's hard to draft consent forms that
include every possible scenario for embryos.
   The Davises said they were not asked to sign such a paper.
   Dr. I. Ray King, founder of the clinic in Knoxville, has said
that was an oversight. But he added that any such agreement
probably could be contested legally later by a husband or wife who
changed his or her mind.
   King has agreed to continue maintaining the seven frozen, viable
embryos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
