<FIRST>r w AM-OilSpill-Congress     04-10 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Congress,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spill Hampers New Drilling Effort</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The odds that Congress will approve oil
drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge dropped Monday as a
congressman whose subcommittee oversees the Alaska pipeline blasted
the industry's ability to clean up after itself.
   ``It is clear that what happened in Prince William Sound was not
a simple accident,'' said Rep. George Miller, following a three-day
visit to Alaska to see the effects of the Exxon Valdez oil tanker
accident.
   ``Rather, it was the tragic result of a systematic assault by
the oil industry that rendered ineffective the entire system of
regulatory safeguards,'' the California Democrat told a press
conference.
   He said it would irresponsible to allow lease sales in the
refuge after seeing the ineffectiveness of Exxon in dealing with
its 10 million gallon spill into one of the nation's most
environmentally delicate areas.
   Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz., chairman of the Interior Committee,
agreed that legislation to allow oil lease sales in the refuge is
dead this year, but he would not rule out its passage next year.
   Reacting to the nation's largest oil spill, legislators began
expressing doubts about the ANWR legislation last week and, as the
oil continues to spread, are growing increasingly disappointed with
Exxon and others who are connected with clean-up efforts.
   Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., whose Committee on Energy and
Natural Resources approved the ANWR bill last month, said after the
spill that he could not tell right away what the impact would be.
But a few days later, he said he would not push the bill for a full
Senate vote until safety systems were in place.
   Rep. Bill Richards, D-N.M., supported ANWR drilling before the
oil spill but said he has changed his mind.
   The House subcommittee on national parks and public lands
announced a hearing Thursday to find out what the National Park
Service is doing to clean up oil that reached the Kenai Fjords
National Park on Monday and was on its way to the Katmai and Lake
Clark national parks.
   Miller said the spill ``requires us to completely re-evaluate
our the system of delivery.''
   he oil tanker ran aground March 24 and the spill is still not
under control.
   Miller said the industry had promised that it could handle any
problems connected with oil shipping, but over the years stripped
away the safeguards for cost-cutting purposes.
   He said an authority that could command cleanup after an
accident like that last month should be established.
   ``We have to separate those that are looking out for the public
and those looking out for the industry,'' he said. ``I want a
system by which the first thing the industry does is clean up the
oil in the water and not call their lawyers.'''
   At least one congressional subcommittee is planning to look into
the increases in retail gasoline prices that have occurred since
the grounding of the oil tanker.
   The Energy Committee's energy regulation and conservation
subcommittee, chaired by Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, has
planned a hearing for next Monday, said the panel's counsel, Joel
Saltzman. The lawmaker has invited industry and government
officials, along with consumer advocates, to testify.
   Since the accident, oil industry analysts have noted increases
of about a dime per gallon in the prices motorists pay for gasoline.
   They have attributed the higher prices not only to the spill and
the temporary shutdown of the pipeline, but to tight international
supplies, an unusually high proportion of U.S. refineries
undergoing maintenance, the costs of complying with nw federal
restrictions on fuel ingredients, and the usual run-up in prices
with the approach of the summer driving season.
</TEXT>
