<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     04-10 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reformer Elected in Montenegro Presidential Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nenad Bucin, a popular advocate of
economic and political reforms, was declared the winner Monday in
elections for Montenegro's representative on Yugoslavia's
collective presidency, Belgrade radio said.
   Preliminary results indicated Bucin, who ran against a retired
army officer and a career politician, won 171,047 of the 310,000
votes cast in the republic's 20 counties.
   He is scheduled to be formally approved by Montenegro's
Parliament as the republic's representative on the national
presidency next Friday.
   The nine-member federal presidency includes representatives of
Yugoslavia's six republics, its two autonomous provinces and the
head of the Communist Party.
   The balloting Sunday was the first-ever Western-style free
election in Montenegro, the smallest of the republics, and only the
second in communist Yugoslavia.
   In the other republics, representatives are nominated by the
regional leaderships and rubber-stamped by the legislatures.
   Janez Drnovsek, a 39-year-old economist virtually unknown in the
rest of the country, was elected April 2 to represent the liberal
republic of Slovenia on the federal presidency.
   Drnovsek is scheduled to take over as the country's president in
mid-May. Presidency members rotate every year as head of the body.
   Bucin, 54, an outspoken member of the communist leadership, has
frequently stressed the need for fundamental market-oriented
economic reforms and for changes in the political system that would
give ordinary citizens a greater say in the political process.
</TEXT>
