<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0599 04-10 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0599,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian, Druse Gunners Shell Christian Beaches</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 2 grafs after 3rd graf, `Newspapers say...' UPDATING
with French envoy's ``act of war'' remarks. Picks up 4th pvs, `Christian
army...' with minor editing to trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Druse gunners fired rocket
barrages onto Christian beaches Monday in what police called a
rehearsal for shelling French aid ships expected to arrive this
week.
   France is sending two ships loaded with fuel, medical and food
supplies to help ease shortages caused by a month of the worst
sectarian fighting since 1985.
   Newspapers say the ships are due Wednesday, and Moslems say the
former colonial power is biased toward the Christians.
   France says the aid is destined for all Lebanese. A French envoy
to Lebanon was quoted as saying Syrian gunfire against the aid
ships ``would be an act of war against France, against humanity,
against an emergency humanitarian action.''
   ``If they fire, it is clear that they want to destroy Lebanon,''
Jean-Francois Deniau, home from a two-day mission to Lebanon, was
quoted as saying in the French daily newspaper La Nouvelle
Republique du Centre-Ouest, of Tours. He added he did not believe
that would happen.
   Christian army units led by Gen. Michel Aoun responded to
Monday's rocket fire with 155mm howitzers, shelling the Ein
Mreisseh and Wadi Abu Jamil neighborhoods of Moslem west Beirut.
   Police reported two people killed and 15 wounded in west Beirut.
They said the fire was directed at Syrian rocket launchers in the
two districts and at the Murr tower, a unfinished 40-story building
the Syrians use as a sniping and observation post.
   Monday's exchanges violated a cease-fire proclaimed by the Arab
League, which began at midnight Wednesday.
   A police spokesman said a shell hit a Turkish cargo ship
carrying 2,200 tons of flour Sunday night off Jounieh, a Christian
port north of Beirut, killing one of its 12 crew members and
damaging the vessel.
   West Beirut press reports said an army gunboat fired on the
Mololi because it was taking flour to Sidon, a Moslem-controlled
port in the south. The ship left Lebanese waters after the attack
for Famagusta, Cyprus, said the police spokesman, who cannot be
named under standing regulations.
   Artillery duels betweeen Aoun's 20,000 Christian troopers and an
alliance of Syrian soldiers and Druse militiamen began March 8, two
days after Aoun's forces blockaded illegal ports run by militias.
   According to police figures, 180 people have been killed and 619
wounded, nearly all of them civilians.
   Mitri Nammar, head of the Beirut electricity authority, said the
main city power plant at Zouk, a suburb of Christian east Beirut,
was out of fuel and ``unless something is urgently done ... the
one-hour daily supply of electricity to the capital and its
environs will stop.''
   Syrian and Druse gunners regularly fire at the Zouk beach,
preventing fuel tankers from docking there.
   French Ambassador Paul Blanc visited Moslem west Beirut and met
with Salah Staitieh of the Moslem government's Foreign Ministry. A
crisis that began in September has created competing Christian and
Moslem governments _ led by Aoun and Premier Salim Hoss, a Sunni
Moslem _ and divided the army.
   Staitieh said he told Blanc the Moslem cabinet ``is moving
toward rejecting the French relief aid. In this case, let France
give all these supplies to the other party with whom it
sympathizes.''
   Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib's 22,000-man Moslem army suggested in a
statement that the French vessels dock in the northern port of
Tripoli ``to ensure the safety of the two ships and their crew.''
Moslems control Tripoli.
   Police say bombardment of the beaches near the Zouk power plant
and the Christian port of Jounieh north of Beirut has been a
rehearsal for arrival of the ships sent by France, from which
Lebanon became independent in 1943.
   France has supported the Aoun's demand for withdrawal of the
40,000 Syrian soldiers stationed in Lebanon under a peacekeeping
mandate issued by the Arab League in 1976, the year after the
Lebanese civil war began.
</TEXT>
