<FIRST>u w AM-North-Facts     04-10 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North-Facts,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Officials Didn't Agree with North Trial Statement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Strategy Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 107-item government ``admission of facts''
presented at Oliver North's trial last week was viewed by some
administration officials as ``incomplete and therefore distorted,''
one official said Monday.
   A note to that effect was not made public in court, although the
42-page admission was.
   An official who saw the note, commenting on condition he not be
named, said it was at the bottom of a cover letter to U.S. District
Judge Gerhard A. Gesell from independent counsel Lawrence Walsh.
   The statement of facts, agreed to by both the government and
North's lawyers, was introduced to avoid the risks of national
security secrets being disclosed through testimony or documents
that might be put in evidence.
   Among the disclosures in the admission was that George Bush,
then vice president, told the president of Honduras that his nation
would be getting expedited U.S. military and economic aid. Earlier
testimony had indicated then-President Reagan told the Honduran
president such help would be forthcoming in return for his
assisting the Nicaraguan guerrillas.
   Bush has declined to comment on the matter, saying it could
prejudice the North trial. Privately, some State Department and
White House officials have expressed frustration with the document,
saying it does not faithfully represent events as they occurred.
</TEXT>
