<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     04-10 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rights Activist Emigrates To West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslovak human rights activist who
spent 11 years in jail has been given permission to leave
Czechoslovakia and will settle in West Germany, an emigre source
said Monday.
   Walter Kania, 48, arrived in Vienna Friday with wife and two
children, aged 12 and 14. The family will leave for Bavaria on
Tuesday.
   Kania, who worked as a driver before his arrest, is a signatory
of the Charter 77 human rights manifesto.
   He was in prison from 1977 to May 1988, when he was released for
an interruption of his penalty. He suffered two heart attacks in
prison and also developed a liver infection.
   According to the emigre source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, Kania was supposed to have returned to jail after one
year but was exempted under world diplomatic pressure.
   Few Charter 77 signatories have emigrated to the West. One of
the most prominent signatories, playwright Vaclav Havel, has
refused an official offer to leave Czechoslovakia for a Western
country.
</TEXT>
