<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Stroessner     04-10 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Stroessner,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Hospitalized Stroessner In Satisfactory Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Paraguayan President Alfredo
Stroessner, hospitalized for a mild congestive heart failure, is in
satisfactory condition, an official at Sao Paulo's Heart Institute
said Monday.
   Stroessner, 76, was admitted to the hospital Sunday for routine
tests and his condition, ``considering his age, could be accepted
as normal,'' said public relations director Cid Paulo Quaresma
Maida.
   He said Stroessner probably would remain in the hospital for
another day.
   Stroessner came to Brazil Feb. 5, two days after he was ousted
in a coup that ended his nearly 35 years of authoritarian rule. He
bought a home in the coastal resort of Guaratuba 267 miles from Sao
Paulo.
   Heart Institute doctors, speaking on condition they not be
identified, said Stroessner has had heart problems for several
years that he could keep under control with medication.
   Paraguay's foreign minister, Luis Maria Argana, said last week
that Stroessner also suffers from cancer of the prostate and for
``humanitarian reasons'' the new government believes he should go
to a country with advanced medical facilities for treatment.
   He said the United States had refused to grant Stroessner a
temporary visa and Switzerland was being considered.
</TEXT>
