<DOCNO> AP890410-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1926EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ApartmentCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0663 04-10 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apartment Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0663,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Pilots, Passenger Killed When Plane Crashes Into Apartment Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with three deaths confirmed, witness accounts.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine corporate airplane crashed
into an apartment complex and exploded while trying to make an
emergency landing Monday, killing two pilots and their only
passenger.
   Only one minor injury, treated at the scene, was reported on the
ground, although eight apartments were destroyed in the crash and
fire near this Florida Panhandle city, said Escambia County Sheriff
Charlie Johnson.
   ``It weas a miracle that nobody on the ground was killed,''
Johnson said. ``It happened at 1 p.m. If it had happened at 5 p.m.
there's no telling what might have happened.''
   Killed were Jacob Horton of Pensacola, senior vice president of
Gulf Power Co., and the two pilots, John Major and Mike Holmes,
both of Gulfport, Miss., where the plane was based, said Scott
Harrington, a spokesman for the Pensacola-based utility.
   Thomas Powell, 33, said he was showering when he heard a noise
and suddenly could see daylight in his bathroom as the plane tore
away the apartment building's roof.
   The Beechcraft King Air 200 crashed at 1:06 p.m. about four
miles northwest of Pensacola Regional Airport, Johnson said.
   ``The plane was coming in real low over the treetops,'' said
Jerry Johnson, 27, a resident of the Country Walk Estates complex
where the plane crashed. ``It hit the house and flipped.''
   Jerry Johnson, a civilian jet mechanic at the Pensacola Naval
Air Station, said he could tell from the sound of the engines that
the plane was in trouble. He said he also saw smoke coming from one
of the engines before it crashed and exploded, sending a fireball
high in the air.
   ``There were pieces strewn all over the place,'' said Anthony
Baroco, owner of a four-unit apartment building that was destroyed.
The other four damaged apartments were in a neighboring building.
   The plane belonged to Southern Co. Services, a subsidiary of The
Southern Co., an Atlanta-based utility holding company that is also
the parent of Gulf Power, Harrington said. Horton, 57, was Gulf's
second-ranking executive.
   The plane had taken off from the airport minutes earlier en
route to Peachtree-DeKalb Airport in Atlanta, but the pilot radioed
that he had a problem and was turning back, said Arlene Salac, a
spokeswoman for the Federal Aviation Administration in Atlanta.
   She said the pilot declared an emergency but that no report was
immediately available as to what the trouble was, although rain,
thunderstorms and fog were in the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
