<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     04-10 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>72 Guerrillas Killed In Fighting, Army Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked a
civil defense post and a coffee processing plant west of San
Salvador Monday, an army spokesman said.
   Seven civil patrolmen were seriously wounded and the military
post was destroyed in the attacks near Comasagua, 17 miles from the
capital, civilian sources in the area said.
   The army spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
reported casualties but gave no details. He said the El Rosario
coffee processing plant suffered an undetermined amount of damage.
   In fighting last week that ended Thursday, at least 100 people
were killed, the army and guerrillas said.
   An army communique Monday said government troops killed 72
rebels and wounded 103 others. It said the rebels killed 17
civilians, wounded 23 and kidnapped 10 others.
   The rebels, in a broadcast over their clandestine Radio
Venceremos, said they killed or wounded 438 soldiers during the
period, 255 of them in an attack on the 4th Infantry Brigade in the
northern province of Chalatenango on Thursday. At the time, the
army said three soldiers were killed and five others wounded.
   The army said it confiscated mines, other explosives and 30
rifles from the guerrillas. Rebels said they took army rifles and
radios.
   About 70,000 people, the majority of them civilians, have been
killed in the 9-year-old war.
</TEXT>
