<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Korea     04-10 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Dissident Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested the leader of the
nation's largest dissident group Monday because of a secret visit
to communist North Korea by a clergyman who advises the
organization.
   Lee Bu-young, co-chairman of the United National Democratic
Movement, was detained after attending a meeting to arrange a
welcome for the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, who visited North Korea on March
25 and met with its leader, Kim Il Sung, about reunifying the
peninsula.
   A goverment prosecutor, who spoke on condition of not being
identified, said Lee, 46, may be charged with violating a law
banning activity that supports or helps North Korea.
   Moon visited North Korea without the required government
approval and faces arrest when he returns from Tokyo, where he
stopped on the way home. He has said he would arrive in Seoul on
Thursday, the day before his passport expires.
   Prosecutors said Lee was being questioned about whether he knew
of Moon's trip in advance. They said they also suspect Lee of
aiding an illegal strike that has paralyzed South Korea's largest
shipyard for more than three months.
   His arrest may presage a crackdown on the increasingly militant
dissidents, who officials claim want to replace the government of
President Roh Tae-woo with one more friendly to Seoul's communist
rival.
   Several people were arrested last month, including two of Moon's
sons. Officials have indicated many dissident leaders might be
arrested after Moon's return.
   Roh ordered police last week to intensify efforts against
``radical leftists.'' In nationwide raids on publishing houses and
bookstores, police seized 11,000 books they said promoted North
Korea and communism.
   Korea was divided in 1945 and the two nations fought a war in
1950-53 that began with an invasion by North Korea.
   Also Monday, friends and family paid homage to a student who
died after dousing himself with paint thinner and gasoline and
setting himself afire, shouting ``Yankees go home!'' to protest the
U.S. presence in South Korea.
   Nam Tae-hyun, a 24-year-old senior majoring in ethics at Seoul
National Teacher's College, died Saturday hours after setting
himself ablaze.
   Choe Song-ho, 24, said he was on his way to a student rally when
he heard a voice shouting from a classsroom ``Yankee go home!''
``Drive out U.S. imperialists!'' and ``Peaceful unification!'' He
said he found Nam in flames. Students who accompanied Nam to the
hospital said he told them he burned himself ``for independence of
the fatherland. For peace. For unification (with North Korea).''
</TEXT>
