<SECOND>AM-Wright Probe, 1st ld-writethru, a0730,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to CORRECT grammar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee has voted to cite
Speaker Jim Wright, D-Tex., for more than 30 incidents of ethical
wrongdoing and is continuing to review other allegations, CBS News
reported Monday evening.
   The results of the committee's investigation, which began last
June, are expected to be made public next week.
   CS quoted unnamed sources close to the investigation as saying
the charges will involve business activities with Fort Worth, Tex.,
developer George Mallich which were designed to financially benefit
Wright and his wife, Betty, by skirting House ethics rules.
   Mallick told the network that the small company, which was
started in 1980, was perfectly legitimate. `It was a small
corporation between friends...like an investment club. We wanted to
dabble in business together.''
   According to a document obtained by CBS _ a defense of Wright's
activities _ the panel's outside investigator, Chicago attorney
Richard Phelan, ``has concluded that the Wright Mallick company
`Malightoo' was an articifice or a conduit to pass gifts to the
Wrights,'' the network said.
   CBS said the report alleges that the Wrights were furnished a
cut-rate Forth Worth apartment and Mrs. Wright received an annual
salary of $18,000 plus use of a company car which she brought to
Washington and purchased only after learning that the ethics
committee was investigating.
   Mallick told CBS that Mrs. Wright earned the money she was paid.
``She had many duties and performed them well. She was one of the
most liked people in the organization.
   CBS said other charges include questionable oil deals and
attempts to avoid House limits from outside income.
   Wright is expcted to be cited, the network said, for alleged
wrongdoing by himself and his staff for converting honoraria to the
purchase of his book, ``Reflection of a Public Man.''
   The network quoted a spokesman in Wright's office as saying it
would be ``absurd'' to report the committee had voted to cite the
speaker for more than 30 allegations.
