<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SovietAlcoholics     04-10 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Alcoholics,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kitty Dukakis Meets Recovering Alcoholics From Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three recovering alcoholics from the Soviet
Union shared the first day of their visit to the United States with
a fellow sufferer, Kitty Dukakis, on a tour of an alcoholism unit
at a Manhattan hospital Monday.
   ``Alcoholics are the same in Moscow and in New York and in
Boston and all over the world. They share the same disease,'' Mrs.
Dukakis said after the tour at Bellevue Hospital.
   Mrs. Dukakis, the wife of Massachusetts governor Michael
Dukakis, was treated for alcoholism in February following her
husband's unsuccessful campaign as Democratic presidential
candidate.
   The three Soviets, identified only as Sasha, Victor and Volodja,
are visiting the United States for two weeks to learn about the
treatment of alcoholism here. They are the guests of the
Soviet-U.S. Joint Conference on Alcoholism, Drug Addiction and
Peace.
   Alcoholism is ``the most democratic of diseases,'' said the Rev.
J.W. Canty, the chairman of the Joint Conference and an Episcopal
priest from New York City who lives in Moscow.
   ``It happens to auto workers along the Volga River and it
happens to auto workers in Detroit. It happens to first ladies in
the United States and it happens to cleaning ladies in Moscow,'' he
said.
   Canty estimated that there are 10 million alcoholics in the
United States and 10 million to 15 million in the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet visitors overcame their 20-year drinking problems
through Moscow Beginners, the first anti-drinking group for Soviet
citizens that is registered with Alcoholics Anonymous, said Canty,
who helped start the group in 1987.
   The three men, whose last names were withheld, had tried
unsuccessfully for years to dry out in state-run facilities for
alcoholics, he added.
   ``I think the principle of Alcoholics Anonymous is more
effective because it depends on the person himself _ because it
depends on his friends in Alcoholics Anonymous,'' said Victor, a
film producer, through a translator.
   In the Soviet Union, alcoholics undergo compulsory
hospitalization for as long as six months and are forced to spend
up to two years in institutions reserved for those who cannot be
cured by the hospitals.
   ``The fact that it (AA) is one recovering alcoholic helping
another one introduces a whole new experience of trust and honesty
and mutual dependency which the Soviet people are not familiar
with,'' Canty said.
   Mrs. Dukakis was on hand at Kennedy International Airport to
greet the Soviet visitors and their translator Helen Kuzmicheva,
who runs the Soviet-U.S. Alcoholism Center in Moscow, a
Western-style out-patient clinic that opened April 3.
   Mrs. Dukakis then accompanied them for a quick burger and shake
at a fast food restaurant in midtown before going to the hospital.
   Dr. Marc Galanter, the director of the division of alcohol and
drug abuse at Bellevue, said the Soviets ``seemed to be favorably
impressed'' with the hospital.
   ``I think they would have to go a ways in Moscow to equal the
set-up here,'' he added.
   During their two-week visit, the Soviets will also visit the
world headquarters of Alcoholics Anonymous in New York, attend open
AA meetings and visit Chit Chat Farms, an alcoholism rehabilitation
center in Warnersville, Pa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Police     04-10 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Police,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chief of Sweden's Security Police Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Sweden's secret service
resigned Monday, a day before a report was to be submitted to the
government on the counterespionage agency.
   The report by a member of the governing Social Democratic Party
purportedly criticizes the service's effectiveness after the
killing of Prime Minister Olof Palme in 1986.
   Sune Sandstrom said his resignation will take effect as soon as
the government names a replacement. Sandstrom, 49, was appointed in
1987 to head the Sakerhetspolis, or security police, known as SAPO.
   Sandstrom issued a statement saying he was quitting because the
government appeared to want a SAPO chief with ``a broader base of
experience'' and who was more than ``a policeman.''
   Sandstrom has been criticized for allegedly allowing book
publisher Ebbe Carlsson to conduct his own investigation last year
into the Palme killing when the police search failed to determine
the gunman who killed the prime minister as he was walking along a
Stockholm street.
   Sandstrom also allegedly was implicated in connection with an
attempt to smuggle illegal wiretapping equipment into Sweden.
   The scandal over Carlsson's private investigation previously
brought about the resignations of the head of the national police,
Nils Erik Ahmansson, and Justice Minister Anna Greta Leijon.
   Carl Bildt, head of the opposition Conservative party, said he
feared the government may appoint a politician to head SAPO.
   ``I am worried. We must have an efficient security police to
protect ourselves against spies and terrorists,'' he said on
national radio.
   A 42-year-old man suspected in Palme's killing was arrested Dec.
14. Officials have said the trial of Christer Pettersson will start
May 29 and is expected to last at least four weeks. Pettersson has
denied he shot Palme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
