<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli wearing army fatigues opened fire
with an Uzi submachine gun Monday evening, killing a Palestinian
and wounding three as they sat on the grass outside the walled Old
City, police and witnesses reported.
   Israel radio said an anonymous telephone caller speaking Hebrew
with a French accent claimed responsibility in the name of the
Sicarites group, which has made several arson attacks on left-wing
Israeli targets.
   In other developments Monday:
   _Police spokesmen said Chaim Bar-Lev, the police minister,
issued orders that bar some young Palestinians from praying at the
Al Aqsa mosque complex, one of Islam's holiest sites.
   _A military source said Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, the chief of
staff, forced a colonel to resign because of attacks on
Palestinians by soldiers he commanded. The daily Maariv called it
the harshest action in more than a decade against an officer of
such a high rank serving in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   _In the West Bank town of Hebron troops shot and killed an Arab
stonethrower, an army spokesman said. Israel radio identified the
slain man as Jamil Natche and said he was shot when a group of
masked people attacked an army jeep with stones.
   _Arab hospital officials said five Palestainians were wounded by
army gunfire in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. The army confirmed
two people were wounded and said it was investigating.
   Natche's death raised to 423 the number of Arabs killed in the
Palestinian uprising that began in December 1987. Eighteen Israelis
also have been slain in violence related to the uprising.
   According to Israel radio's account of the attack in Jerusalem,
the caller described the shooting as retaliation for stoning
attacks on Jews.
   The assailant escaped by foot after the shooting at about 7:40
p.m. near the Jaffa Gate, a main entrance to the Old City.
   Mahmoud Zahdeh, 20, a hotel waiter interviewed in his hospital
bed, said he and friends were resting after a day of fasting in the
Moslem holy month of Ramadan.
   ``Four of us were sitting on the lawn near the Jaffa Gate eating
pumpkin seeds when a soldier in his late 30s, with slightly gray
hair, approached us and looked at us for a while,'' he said.
   ``He was wearing a military uniform, but with no hat, and was
carrying a short rifle. He left and returned two minutes later. He
did not talk to us. He only started shooting.''
   Zahdeh was shot five times and had wounds in the shoulders, left
leg and scalp.
   Reporters who arrived moments after the shooting said the body
of a man in his 30s was beside the wall and more than a dozen empty
cartridge casings were scattered about. Police identified the dead
man as Khaled Shawish, 26, a blacksmith from the Old City.
   Officials at Bikur Holim Hospital said a 19-year-old factory
worker from Jerusalem was in critical condition with chest and head
wounds, and a cousin of the dead man was being treated for wounds
to the lower stomach, arms and legs.
   Yosef Yehudai of the Jerusalem police said of the attacker: ``He
did not shout. As far as we know, he never said a word and his
movements were sudden. He was standing five meters from his
victims, very close.''
   Bar-Lev's order barring some Arabs from praying at Al Aqsa is
believed to be without precedent. Palestinians rioted outside the
mosque Friday, the first day of Ramadan, and some of the rocks
thrown struck Jews praying at the nearby Western Wall, the holiest
shrine of Judaism.
   About 4,000 Palestinians were involved in the riots, during
which 12 people were reported injured and 37 Arabs were arrested.
   Rafi Levy, the police spokesman, said in explaining Bar-Lev's
order: ``There will be restrictions against those who we fear might
disrupt order, which means youths from the territories. Every
violation of public order will be met with an immediate response.''
   He said Moslem worshipers would be required to give police their
identity cards before entering the mosque complex.
   Since capturing the Old City in 1967, Israel has taken pride in
allowing free access to holy sites of all religions. During the
uprising, however, it sometimes has blocked traffic from the
occupied lands to prevent riots at Al Aqsa after midday prayers on
Friday, the Moslem sabbath.
   Col. Yehuda Meir decided to quit after Shomron said he would
have to stand trial otherwise, the military source said.
   Meir was military governor of Nablus in the West Bank when the
uprising started, and Maariv said the investigation dealt with two
incidents.
   Last year, in Kfar Salem near Nablus, soldiers under Meir's
command used a bulldozer to bury four Palestinians. The victims
survived.
   The other case involved beatings of two Palestinian teen-agers
in Nablus, one of which was filmed by U.S. television cameras.
</TEXT>
