<FIRST>r a AM-People-McClure     04-10 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-McClure,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family of Trapped Girl Watches Recreation of Her Rescue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto LA4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica McClure's parents and the
performers cast to play them in a television movie met Monday, and
watched a recreation of her 1987 rescue from a well shaft, an
operation that enthralled the nation.
   Jessica, who is now 3, and parents Chip and Cissy were flown out
from their Midland, Texas, home to meet the cast of ``Everybody's
Baby: The Rescue of Jessica McClure.''
   At a news conference, a smiling Jessica played with a camera and
microphone, then told the crowd of journalists, ``No more
pictures.''
   ``She's just a little doll,'' said Ellen Gonzalez, a spokeswoman
for the production.
   ``The only scars left are only physical and they are fading
away,'' said her father. He said his daughter can't remember the
ordeal that ended Oct. 16, 1987, as millions watched on television.
   ``She knows what people tell her,'' her mother said. ``She's the
little girl who fell down the well.
   ``What she recalls is that Winnie the Pooh saved her,'' her
mother added. ``I don't know how she got that idea. ... Maybe she
remembers me singing it to her.''
   The film is scheduled for broadcast May 21 on ABC-TV. It stars
Roxana Zal and Will Oldham as the McClures. Miss Zal won Emmy and
Golden Globe awards for her work in the ABC film ``Something About
Amelia.''
   Beau Bridges will play the police chief of Midland, Academy
Award-winner Patty Duke will play a crisis counselor and veteran
character actor Pat Hingle will play the fire chief.
   Jessica and her parents watched filming of part of the rescue
attempt in a tunnel and well built at Culver Studios 10 miles west
of downtown Los Angeles.
   Jessica was 18 months old when she tumbled 22 feet to the bottom
of an abandoned well while playing in her aunt's backyard on Oct.
14, 1987. She remained trapped in a space only eight inches in
diameter for nearly 59 hours while rescuers drilled a side tunnel
through solid rock to reach her.
