<FIRST>r a AM-ChildrenThreatened     04-10 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children Threatened,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Graffiti Renews Fears At Rural School Complex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROOKLYN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worried parents pulled 10 to 20 children
out of classes Monday after a drawing of an assault rifle and the
words ``You're Dead'' were found spray-painted on a school wall, 10
days after telephone threats against pupils.
   State police escorted buses from the school, as they did last
week after the two anonymous phone threats.
   Police said the graffiti, including the phrase ``You're gonzo,''
appeared to be the work of juveniles and not of the person who made
the threats.
   The graffiti was found on an outside wall of the junior high
school. The school is part of the Brooklyn School, which has three
buildings and serves about 850 students in kindergarten through
ninth grade.
   Doors were locked and police were stationed at the school.
   The graffiti was removed, but not until after most of the pupils
saw it, school officials said.
   Some parents picked up their children rather than having them
take the buses, which serve about 98 percent of the students from
the school in the rural area of northeastern Connecticut. Students
were not allowed to walk or bicycle home, and buses were loaded one
at a time.
   ``Maybe it is kids playing a prank. But why take a chance?''
said Barbara Devolve, who decided to drive her son home rather than
having him go by bus. Devolve said she would probably keep her
12-year-old son, Bobby, out of school the rest of the week,
although he had insisted pupils were not worried.
   ``I'm just not going to tempt fate,'' said Chris Crawford, who
came to pick up his son and daughter, both of whom usually ride the
bus.
   ``Most youngsters are taking it in stride. They are probably
less concerned about it than parents, who worry more because they
are not here to see what's going on,'' said Superintendent of
Schools Louise Berry.
   School officials had hoped to restore a sense of normalcy Monday
after six school days of heightened security measures, taken after
a woman warned in a March 30 telephone call to Town Hall that she
planned to shoot children in the schoolyard.
   The next morning a female caller _ police are unsure if it was
the same woman _ telephoned a school bus coordinator and threatened
to kill the children on the bus driven by the coordinator's wife.
   School administrators have told parents they believe there is no
danger, but have left to families the decision on whether to keep
children out of school, Berry said.
   She said the school system would probably have to end its long
practice of allowing parents and others to come and go from the
buildings as they wish.
   ``We now have to face the fact that it's probably not wise to
have such freedoms,'' Berry said. ``It's sad.''
</TEXT>
