<FIRST>r a AM-Shamir 1stLd-Writethru a0649 04-10 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shamir, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0649,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Says Arabs Should Help Solve Refugee Problem; Details Peace
Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT number of Palestinian refugees
in occupied lands. Pick up 5th pvs, `There is...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab states should help Israel pay to ``establish
a human condition'' for the hundreds of thousands of Palestinians
living in refugee camps in occupied territories, Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Monday.
   ``Israel doesn't have the financial means to solve all these
problems'' in the refugee camps, Shamir said at a news conference
during a day-long trip to Chicago to promote a Middle East peace
plan he proposed last week.
   ``It couldn't substitute for a political solution but it could
improve the climate,'' he said.
   According to U.N. relief officials, who manage the refugee camps
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, about 335,000
Palestinians live in the camps. Altogether, about 1.7 million
Palestinians live in the occupied lands, most in towns and cities.
   Shamir estimated it would cost $1 billion to solve problems in
the camps.
   There is a need to ``organize to provide housing and to
establish a human condition for their life there,'' Shamir said.
   Shamir also detailed some of the issues he discussed last week
with President Bush and Secretary of State James Baker III, and
said Israel would listen to any proposal brought to the negotiating
table under a plan proposed Thursday to the Bush administration.
   The plan calls for Palestinian balloting to select
representatives who would negotiate an interim solution of
self-rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Israel seized those
territories from neighboring Arab states in the 1967 Middle East
War, and they have been the site of an uprising Palestinian leaders
say won't end until Israel withdraws.
   Asked whether Israel would consider negotiating land for peace,
Shamir said land is not the issue now, but the country would listen
to any proposal.
   ``We will listen to anything,'' he said. ``Both parties will
listen to all proposals that are brought to the table of
negotiations.''
   ``It will be a full self rule'' for perhaps five years while a
permanent solution to the Arab-Israeli conflict is negotiated,
Shamir said.
   ``It will have all the power of a government except security and
foreign relations,'' he said. ``There will be some problems they
will have to settle with the authorities of Israel.''
   Shamir discounted comments Sunday by the opposition Labor Party
leader, Finance Minister Shimon Peres. Peres said Israel had in
effect abandoned its longstanding refusal to negotiate with the
Palestine Liberation Organization by letting the United States
mediate a proposal that could result in PLO supporters being
elected.
   ``We don't see the PLO as a factor in the peace initiative,'' he
said. ``(But) we will try to negotiate with Palestinian Arabs that
are interested in peace.''
   He also called for a meeting to celebrate the 1979 Camp David
accords, which Shamir labled ``the most successful endeavor to
resolve the Arab-Israeli crisis.''
   Shamir's plan is a modified version of the accords, but it
differs in that it calls for elections, followed by negotiations on
autonomy.
   The anniversary meeting would ``review prospects for enlarging
the peace process,'' Shamir said.
   Shamir was to travel to New York later Monday to discuss the
plan with Jewish groups before returning to Israel on Thursday to
begin working out the details of the peace plan.
</TEXT>
