<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Apartheid     04-10 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Apartheid,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Anti-Apartheid Campaigner in Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-apartheid campaigner from South Africa
said Monday relations with the Soviet Union would not be possible
until apartheid is abolished, the official news agency Tass
reported.
   Frederick Van Zyl Slabbert, heading a delegation from the
Institute for a Democratic Alternative for South Africa, met
members of the Communist Party Central Committee, Foreign Ministry
officials and members of the Academy of Sciences Africa Institute.
   He later told a news conference that for a political settlement
in South Africa to become a reality, all detainees must be
released, the 34-month-old state of emergency must be lifted and
apartheid dismantled, Tass said.
   ``The delegation's conclusion was that as long as apartheid
exists in South Africa, there can be no question of diplomatic
relations between that country and the Soviet Union,'' Tass quoted
Van Zyl Slabbert as saying.
   He said it was obvious the Soviet Union wanted to play a
constructive role and cooperate with other nations in settling the
conflict between the Pretoria government and the outlawed and
exiled African National Congress.
   Tass quoted Van Zyl Slabbert as saying that before he visited
Moscow, he saw the Soviet Union as a country devoted to exporting
revolution and hoping to destroy South Africa by using the ANC as a
proxy.
   ``Delegation members had believed they would be closely watched
and force-fed Soviet views, but none of this actually happened and
he would now advise all his acquaintances to visit the Soviet
Union,'' Tass said.
   Apartheid by law and custom establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
