<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-10 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow In New England, Rain In The South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring snow showers fell Monday from the lower Great Lakes to
New England, and showers and thunderstorms extended from Texas to
the Carolinas. Temperatures fell to record lows in 35 cities in the
Midwest and West.
   An inch of snow fell in Binghamton and Syracuse, N.Y., during
six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT, and snow advisories were in effect
in western New York state.
   Showers and thunderstorms fell from south central Texas to much
of Georgia and the Carolina coast. The thunderstorms were
concentrated over southern Georgia, northern Florida and the
central Gulf Coast.
   Icy roads in the Denver area caused dozens of traffic accidents
during the Monday rush hour, authorities said.
   Sunny skies prevailed across the West and from the northern and
central Plains to the Great Lakes and northern Ohio Valley.
   Temperatures across much of the nation east of the Rockies were
only in the 30s and 40s, with readings in the 20s in sections of
the upper Great Lakes and central High Plains.
   Freeze warnings were posted Monday night for parts of Indiana,
Kentucky, Arkansas, Tennesee, Mississippi, Alabama, Texas, West
Virginia, Maryland, Virginia and North Carolina.
   ``Everything that is in bloom is going to get zapped,'' Marion
County, Ind., extension agent Richard Crum predicted.
   Record lows for the date were set in 33 cities and tied in two.
New records included 14 degrees in Lansing, Mich., where the old
mark of 18 degrees had stood since 1869; 10 degrees in Scottsbluff,
Neb., (12 degrees, 1898); and 5 degrees in Cheyenne, Wyo. (6
degrees, 1959).
   Unseasonably warm weather continued in the Southwest, with
readings in the 80s and 90s across much of Arizona and California
on Monday afternoon.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 24
degrees in Laramie, Wyo., to 95 degrees in Gila Bend, Ariz. The
nation's low Monday morning was 4 degrees below zero in Yellowstone
National Park, Wyo.
   Tuesday's forecast calls for scattered snow showers across the
Great Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley, with snow likely in
upper Michigan; rain showers from Virginia to Georgia, with
scattered showers and thunderstorms across Florida; widely
scattered rain showers across the southern High Plains and fair to
partly sunny skies prevailing across the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 50s and 60s in much of
the country; below 50 degrees from eastern Montana to the Great
Lakes, the northern Ohio Valley, New England and New Jersey; in the
30s from eastern North Dakota to upper Michigan; in the 70s and
lower 80s across the Florida Peninsula; above 70 degrees from
southwestern Oregon to California, much of Nevada, southwest New
Mexico and southwest Texas; and in the 80s and 90s in the
Southwestern deserts.
</TEXT>
