<FIRST>r a AM-Abortion-Fires     04-10 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Fires,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Confirm Arson in Abortion Clinic Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCALA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arson caused fires at two women's clinics
that went up in flames hours before a massive pro-abortion rally
began in Washington, investigators said Monday.
   Accelerants were used in both fires, said Robert Creighton of
the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
   Investigators have not ruled out a link between the fires in
Ocalaand Fort Myers, which both occurred before dawn Sunday. Fort
Myers is on Florida's southwest coast. Ocala is about 150 miles to
the north.
   Meanwhile, about 70 abortion-rights activists riding in two
buses stopped in Ocala on their way home from the Washington rally
to hold a vigil at the gutted All Women's Health Clinic.
   ``We wanted to show the state of Florida that we will continue
to work to continue to have a choice,'' said Candice Slaughter, a
management consultant from the Tampa area.
   ``This does not deter us. It sets us back on our heels, but it
does not deter us,'' said Deborah Struthers, president of the Ocala
clinic and the Fort Myers Women's Health Center. She said both
facilities would reopen in temporary locations.
   The Ocala fire was the second in two weeks and appeared to be
the work of the arsonist who tried to burn the clinic March 31,
causing an estimated $60,000 damage, authorities said.
   Local anti-abortion activists denied responsibility in Sunday's
attacks, but said they hoped the clinics would not be able to
reopen.
   ``I don't condone the destruction of property, but I'm ecstatic
that they will not be able to perform abortions there,'' said Tom
Ranew, an adoption attorney who was arrested at a sit-in in Orlando
last October.
   Ms. Struthers said she had expected picketing at the Ocala
clinic by abortion opponents as a reaction to the march that
brought more than 300,000 demonstrators to Washington.
   ``I just didn't prepare well enough,'' she added. ``It just
never dawned on us that someone would be that disturbed and
unstable and aggressive and vicious.''
</TEXT>
