<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Military     04-10 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Military,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippines Military Announces Revamp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army chief of staff on Monday
announced a major reshaping of the armed forces to bring in younger
officers who are more experienced in fighting communist insurgents.
   Gen. Renato de Villa told a news conference 32 key positions
were involved. Half of the officers to be rotated are generals, he
added.
   The 163-000 strong military has been fighting communist
guerrillas for the last 20 years. It also faces a Moslem separatist
rebellion in the southern Philippines.
   De Villa dismissed speculation that the planned revamping was a
reaction to persistent news media reports of graft and corruption
in the military.
   ``This is to improve the firepower of the armed forces and this
was planned during the first quarter'' of the year, he said. ``It
is unfair to say that these officers were rotated because of graft
and corruption.''
   De Villa said another changeover is scheduled this year to
replace 10 generals who are retiring.
</TEXT>
