<DOCNO> AP890410-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     04-10 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Production of Vaclav Havel's `Temptation' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The devil doesn't get his due in ``Temptation,''
Vaclav Havel's reworking of the Faust legend, but then neither does
the audience.
   That's surprising considering the play by Czechoslovakia's
leading playwright, now in prison for dissident activities, has
been directed by a fellow Czech, Jiri Zizka. The director, with his
wife, Blanka, runs the highly regarded Wilma Theater in
Philadelphia where ``Temptation'' will go after its New York run.
   But you can't find the play because of Zizka's elaborate and
self-conscious staging that suffocates the drama and the actors in
it as well. Much of ``Temptation,'' which opened over the weekend
at the New York Shakespeare Festival Public Theater, is set in a
science laboratory engaged in what seems to be some kind of
sinister work. The setting allows Zizka and set designer Jerry Rojo
to fill the stage with high-tech scenery, accented by slide
projections, smoke screens and weird sound effects.
   They are the same devices Zizka used several seasons ago in his
version of George Orwell's ``1984,'' done at the Joyce Theater. But
Orwell's novel, of a harrowing future, adapted well to Zizka's
stagey devices.
   Here they seem to overwhelm the actors including such fine
performers as David Strathairn who plays the Faust prototype, Dr.
Henry Foustka, and Bill Moor, as the mincing master of the science
institute.
   Foustka dabbles in black magic, and his sorcery conjures up a
mysterious stranger who sounds like Laurence Olivier and dresses
like a Bowery panhandler. Is the man a representative of the devil
or the repressive government that runs the laboratory? Or are they
one and the same?
   Havel's conclusion is surprisingly obvious. It just takes him a
long time _ 10 scenes spread over more than 2{ hours _ to get
there. In between, there are Foustka's dalliances with several
women in the lab including a young secretary who is a counterpart
to Faust's doomed Margaret. She's played here with remarkable
sympathy by Katherine Hiler.
   Havel's polemics get more of a workout in Foustka's verbal
sparring with that shabbily dressed stranger. Some of their
arguments crackle, displaying the passion Havel obviously has for
the free exchange of ideas. But in the end, their conversations are
overshadowed by Zizka's theatrical tricks, making the battle for
Foustka's soul not a very interesting war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugArrests 1stLd-Writethru a0708 04-10 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Arrests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officer Whose Acquittal Sparked Riots Is Arrested On Drug Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``Today we ...,'' with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
men ordered held, additional charges possible, other details; picks up
7th graf, ``Marrero was ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MILT SOSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former police officer whose acquittal in the
beating death of a black man led to race riots in 1980 was arrested
along with a federal agent on drug charges, authorities said Monday.
   The former officer, Alex Marrero, 34, and federal drug agent
Jorge Villar, 44, were charged with conspiring to distribute
cocaine and conspiring to commit bribery after their weekend
arrests, which followed a sting operation.
   Marrero's acquittal in the beating death of businessman Arthur
McDuffie sparked a riot that left 18 people dead and caused $80
million in property damage in May 1980.
   U.S. attorney Dexter Lehtinen said Marrero and Villar had
offered to protect a man who was posing as a smuggler bringing
cocaine from the Bahamas into an area near Miami Beach. The man was
actually working with government agents.
   Marrero and Villar ``provided protection for this load of
cocaine and in return demanded a fee of $300,000,'' he said, and
Marrero got 10 percent of the fee in cash.
   According to an affidavit, Villar had certificates of deposit
worth more than $300,000 in a briefcase when he was arrested.
   ``Today we demonstrate no matter who you are or what you think
you know, if you deal in drugs you can be caught,'' Lehtinen told a
news conference.
   U.S. Magistrate William C. Turnoff ordered Marrero and Villar
back to the federal Metropolitan Correctional Center, where they
have been held without bond since Saturday.
   Prosecutors asked that they be held as dangers to the community
and because of the risk they might flee. Turnoff said he would make
a decision on bonds for the two Tuesday.
   Diane Cossin, executive assistant to Lehtinen, said conviction
on the conspiracy and bribery charges would lead to automatic
10-year federal prison terms for the two men, and possible life
sentences. She said other charges may be filed.
   Marrero was suspended from the Metro-Dade force early in 1980
after an investigation revealed that McDuffie had been beaten to
death by police officers after a highway chase. Marrero, the chief
defendant in the case, was charged with second-degree murder.
   An all-white jury in Tampa later acquitted him and three other
officers of all criminal charges. Within hours, the Miami area,
especially suburban Liberty City, was rocked by riots that lasted
three days.
   Marrero later tried to rejoin the Metro-Dade police force, but
in 1981 a county hearing examiner upheld his firing. He has held
several jobs since, including security guard and personal bodyguard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
