<SECOND>BC-History, Adv22,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Saturday, April 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, April 22, the 112th day of 1989. There are
253 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, on April 22, 1889, the Oklahoma Land Rush
began at noon as thousands of homesteaders staked claims to land
that had not been assigned by the federal government to Indian
tribes. Claimants who jumped the gun were referred to as
``Sooners.''
   On this date:
   In 1451, Queen Isabella I, who sponsored the voyages of
Christopher Columbus, was born in Madrigal, Spain.
   In 1509, Henry VIII ascended the throne of England following the
death of his father, Henry VII.
   In 1864, Congress authorized the use of the phrase ``In God We
Trust'' on U.S. coins.
   In 1898, the first shot of the Spanish-American War rang out
when the U.S.S. Nashville captured a Spanish merchant ship off Key
West, Fla.
   In 1915, the German army used poison gas for the first time in
World War I.
   In 1930, the United States, Britain and Japan signed the London
Naval Treaty, which regulated submarine warfare and limited
shipbuilding.
   In 1937, thousands of college students in New York City staged a
fourth annual ``peace strike,'' vowing to ``refuse to support the
government of the United States in any war it may conduct.''
   In 1952, an atomic test conducted in Nevada became the first
such explosion shown on live network television.
   In 1954, the televised Senate Army-McCarthy hearings began.
   In 1964, President Lyndon B. Johnson opened the New York World's
Fair.
   In 1970, millions of Americans concerned about the environment
observed the first ``Earth Day.''
   In 1983, the West German news magazine ``Stern'' announced the
discovery of 60 volumes of personal diaries supposedly written by
Adolf Hitler. The diaries turned out to be a hoax, and the forger
was eventually sentenced to prison.
   Ten years ago: Israeli ships shelled suspected Palestinian
guerrilla bases in Lebanon after guerrillas attacked an apartment
building in northern Israel.
   Five years ago: Britain severed diplomatic relations with Libya.
The move came after the government of Colonel Moammar Gadhafi
refused to cooperate with an inquiry into a shooting outside the
Libyan embassy in London that left a British police constable dead
and 10 demonstrators wounded.
   One year ago: Hoffman-La Roche Inc. dismissed as ``flawed'' and
``meaningless'' a government estimate that 900 to 1,300 babies were
born with birth defects caused by the popular anti-acne drug
Accutane.
   Today's birthdays: Actor Eddie Albert is 81. Violinist Yehudi
Menuhin is 73. Actor Jack Nicholson is 52. Singer Glen Campbell is
51. Singer Peter Frampton is 39.
   Thought for today:
   ``Nice guys finish last.'' _ Leo Durocher.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for use Saturday, April 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
