<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears ADV11   04-10 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV 11,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues Apr 11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wary Republicans, Embarrassed in Indiana, Eye Wyoming House Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic national chairman said he
couldn't resist, so he didn't. ``Republicans,'' Ron Brown said,
``read my lips: Jill Long.''
   That's hardly a household name, but the Republicans who heard
him certainly recognized it. Jill Long is a very junior member of
Congress from Indiana. She's just won the seat once held by Vice
President Dan Quayle.
   Now the Republicans are battling to defend another House seat in
Wyoming, where they have nothing to gain but a lot to lose.
   One more special election defeat and their national campaign
managers are going to have a hard time convincing anybody that
their new-look strategy for House contests is going to work
anywhere.
   So far they are down two in special House elections in 1989,
losing narrowly in Indiana and overwhelmingly in a Democratic
district in Alabama.
   Now they are on defense again, trying to hold a Republican seat.
   ``Wyoming's next and I think we've got to fight like the devil
to win,'' said Republican National Chairman Lee Atwater.
   This time the laboratory is a whole state, the at-large Wyoming
House seat Richard B. Cheney gave up to become secretary of
defense. The election will be held on April 26.
   Republican Cheney held it by widening margins in six elections.
   But Democrat John Vinich is the better-known contender of the
candidates to succeed Cheney, after narrowly losing a 1988 Senate
race. Vinich, 38, is a state senator. The Republican candidate is
Craig Thomas, 55, a state representative who casts himself as ``the
kind of moderate conservative'' Wyoming voters chose in Cheney and
in their two GOP senators.
   The National Republican Congressional Committee is concentrating
on the Wyoming contest with both money and manpower, its leaders
worrying that their national game plan could be undone before the
game really gets started.
   They are looking to 1990 and beyond, and weren't figuring on
trouble in 1989.
   But that's what they've got.
   Edward J. Rollins, co-chairman of the congressional campaign
committee, took the job this year with a commitment to turn the
trend that has kept Republicans in the House minority since 1954.
Rep. Newt Gingrich of Georgia, the new minority whip, says he'll
make that political offensive part of his daily agenda on the House
floor.
   The premise is that national aid, advice and issues can, in
time, reverse the Republicans' chronic minority status in the House.
   To date, the movement has been in the opposite direction. After
the 1988 elections, the Republicans had 176 House seats, a net loss
of three. Now they have 174, pending the outcome in Wyoming. The
Democrats have 260.
   They're sending funds and campaign help into Wyoming, too. But
they have kept a lower profile, enabling their side to complain
about outside influence in the Republican campaign.
   Not that outside aid necessarily works. The GOP tried it in
Indiana, to no avail. ``We should not have lost that race,'' said
Atwater. ``That's inexcusable.''
   The pattern there is one that should heighten GOP concerns about
Wyoming.
   The Indiana election was for a House seat opened when Dan Coats
resigned to succeed Quayle in the Senate. Rep. Long had challenged
Quayle for the Senate in 1986 and Coats for the House in 1988,
losing by landslide margins both times. She never shut down the
House campaign.
   So she was the better-known candidate. National issues
notwithstanding, she made headway by linking the Republican nominee
to two county tax increases. She won by 1,775 votes.
   While it was a Republican district, that wasn't the case until
Quayle ousted a Democratic congressman to launch his own political
career in 1976.
   Cheney succeeded a Democrat when he first won the Wyoming seat
in 1978.
   Like Rep. Long in Indiana, Democrat Vinich in Wyoming has
renewed a campaign that hardly had ended when he started running
again. His was a 1988 Senate race, and in one-seat Wyoming, the
House race is statewide, too.
   Vinich came within 1,322 votes of upsetting Republican Sen.
Malcolm Wallop last fall. Now he says that in the House, he'll be
able to instruct the Democratic majority on Wyoming concerns. ``The
majority party has some members with senseless ideas and no
understanding of the West,'' he says.
   Atwater has said that Democrats who blur the party issues can be
tough. ``The smartest Democrats are those who create a situation so
you can't differentiate,'' he told a conservative group last week.
``That's what happened in Alabama.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
