<FIRST>s i BC-APN--Oxford-Admissions Adv23   04-10 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Oxford-Admissions, Adv 23,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Oxford</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   OXFORD, England (AP) _ Applicants need not be incredibly clever
to be admitted, Oxford University says, but the old school tie
still helps.
   ``Everyone who is accepted has a reasonable standard of
intelligence; a very small minority is brilliant,'' says the
catalog, which also notes that an IQ of 130 is considered just
average on the campus.
   Oxford admits about 3,000 ``freshers'' every year, selected from
about 10,000 applicants. About half of those who apply, and half of
those admitted, are from expensive ``public schools'' such as Eton,
Rugby or Winchester, says Ted Baskerville, admissions officer at
the university.
   About 7 percent of British schoolchildren attend public schools,
although the figure jumps to nearly 20 percent after age 16 when
many students leave state-funded schools.
   Only in 1981 did the proportion of state schoolers top 50
percent at Oxford.
   Oxbridge, as Oxford and and its sister university Cambridge are
collectively known, has always been the express lane to power. For
instance, 14 of the 22 members of the Cabinet, including Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher, are Oxbridge graduates.
   Students apply for admission to a college, though they will
receive their degrees from the university.
   Many students receive grants from local governments to cover
fees of about $7,400 a year, and ``no one need be kept out by
shortage of funds,'' says Baskerville.
   Americans and other foreign arts students pay an additional
$5,390 a year. In science, the extra charge is $7,368.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
