<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   04-10 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Videos Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Mascara'' (Warner Home Video. VHS-Beta, $79.95. Rated R)
   
   This film version of bizarre sex and murder in the decadent
opera-going upperclass of Paris is pure Eurotrash from beginning to
end.
   Starring Charlotte Rampling, Michael Sarrazin and Derek De Lint
it limps along, exploiting sexual themes that include normal acts
as well as incest, homosexuality, transsexualism, sado-masochism
and bondage.
   The film wanders through dark alleys, tunnels and rain-washed
streets to the hangout of the weird where one is greeted by a
throaty, half-spoken, heavily accented version of ``Help Me Make It
Through the Night.'' It's supposed to remind us of the decadence of
``Blue Angel'' and Marlene Dietrich's smoky presentations.
   The story tumbles along with uninspired scripting and arty
photography until Rampling pushes brother Sarrazin, a burned-out
police detective and murderer, over the edge so-to-speak after he
declares the only man worthy of her is himself.
   In the final scene, Rampling dissolves into a ``Pieta'' pose,
holding the corpse of her lover (De Lint), who Sarrazin had a mob
of transvestites or transsexuals and what-nots beat almost to death
before they tossed him into the ocean.
   It is one of those pretentious films in which the authors,
directors and actors play at being super-sophisticated. It probably
would make for lofty discussions of allegories and metaphors by
pseudo-intellectuals at a cocktail party, but for entertainment
purposes, it's merely exploitative and boring.
   _ By Chris French, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Betrayed'' (MGM-UA Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated R)
   
   ``Betrayed,'' which should be a terrifying view of bigotry and
the ease with which it thrives, instead is an implausible and
unsatisfying movie from Costa-Gavras, one of cinema's most esteemed
architects.
   The movie works best as suspense, but intends so much more.
Cathy Weaver (Debra Winger), a right-thinking undercover FBI agent,
tries to infiltrate a white supremacist network the agency believes
responsible for the slaying of a loud, obnoxious, radio talk show
host. Gary (Tom Berenger) is the sweet, down-home widower farmer
she falls for. He also is a top gun in the racist network.
   Although the actors do their best to provide depth, the
characters are not convincing. It makes no sense that liberal Cathy
would fall for Gary, despite his pot roast-making mom and
sweet-as-pie kids. It makes no sense that Gary, after spending
years developing his secret network, would so easily take Cathy
into his every confidence. It makes no sense that Cathy's FBI
supervisors take so little care with her when she finally realizes
her target is the man she loves.
   Still, there are some powerful scenes. In one, Gary's little
girl, in a comforting bedtime chat with Cathy, suddenly spews an
incredible, frightening string of hateful epithets. In another,
Gary takes Cathy and his kids to a white supremacist camp, a place
of cross burnings, gun trading and preparation to take back the
country.
   By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
