<DOCNO> AP890410-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   04-10 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Truth is Spoken Here'' (RCA-Novus) _ Marcus Roberts
   
   Marcus Roberts, the young pianist who regularly plays in Wynton
Marsalis' band, has released his first album as a leader, and it's
an unabashed tribute to Thelonious Monk.
   Although only one of the eight numbers is a Monk composition,
several of Roberts' own tunes conjure up the quirky style of the
late pianist. Three numbers even feature a longtime Monk sideman,
the late tenor saxophonist Charlie Rouse (he died in December at
age 64, and this was his last recording session).
   Roberts praises Monk's music as ``the reconciliation of
opposites that is so central to the production of great music,''
and added, ``He is certainly one of the role models that I look to
for guidance in my quest for musical understanding.'' Roberts, too,
reconciles opposites _ a maturity that belies his 25 years and the
adolescent whimsy for which Monk was known.
   Marsalis contributed his stylish trumpet to the album. Roberts
let his mentor take off with a breezy muted solo on the opening
number, ``The Arrival,'' heralded by drummer Elvin Jones. The lone
Monk composition, ``Blue Monk,'' was a solo rendering in a stride
piano style that bordered on boogie.
   Roberts' sensitivity came through in a pair of ballads _ the
pianist's own tonally complex ``Maurella'' and the beautiful
``Single Petal of a Rose,'' an Ellington-Strayhorn composition that
conjured up Debussy.
   Ellington's ``In a Mellow Tone,'' the most satisfying tune in
the set, had Rouse playing the straight man while Roberts provided
the humor. A minor blues, ``Country by Choice,'' featured a growing
series of piano choruses with Roberts dodging and weaving around
the pattern like a running back. ``Nothin' But the Blues,'' a basic
12-bar blues pattern with heavy Monkian flavor, was the closer.
   Roberts, blind since he was 4, has made an impressive album
debut. His technical skill, dedication and passion portend
considerable success.
   _ By Barry Hanson, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Spike'' (Warner Bros.) _ Elvis Costello
   
   Elvis Costello's sprawling new ``Spike'' is just the kind of
record critics love. It's got voluminous lyrics with a liberal
bent, touches on a wide array of musical styles and has plenty of
guest stars.
   But don't let that scare you.
   ``Spike'' may be a difficult record to grasp, and Costello
sometimes takes himself Too Seriously, but there's plenty of
treasures here for the people with the patience to sift through
them.
   Most fascinating is Costello's new songwriting collaboration
with Paul McCartney. ``Veronica'' is just what you'd hope from such
a partnership: an intelligently written song about an old woman
reliving her life in dreams, married to a breezy arrangement
reminiscent of ``Baby You're a Rich Man.''
   The other MacManus-McCartney song, ``Pads, Paws and Claws,'' is
a rockabilly number that suffers from a cluttered arrangement.
   ``...This Town...,'' a booming rocker highlighted by Roger
McGuinn's guitar and McCartney's bass, lampoons the ``Wall Street''
syndrome of success at all costs. It's one of Costello's most
infectious songs.
   Costello's vitriol is sharp on ``Tramp the Dirt Down,'' where
his fantasy is to dance on Margaret Thatcher's grave. ``God's
Comic,'' about a former vaudeville comedian meeting his maker, is
funny in a warped sort of way.
   ``Baby Plays Around,'' which Costello co-wrote with his wife,
Cait O'Riordan, is delicately beautiful. Its straightforward,
emotional lyrics also highlight Costello's weakness elsewhere _ his
tendency to run off at the mouth.
   His lyrics are easily among the most intelligent in music today,
but he still has trouble simply telling a story. In the funky
``Chewing Gum,'' he can barely spit out the words fast enough. And
the stately melody of ``Satellite'' is marred by lyrics that don't
quite connect. What exactly is he trying to say about love in the
'80s?
   An artist who challenges his listeners, of course, is always
better than someone who panders to them. There's no pandering on
``Spike.'' Costello takes his listeners on a trip through rock,
jazz, funk, Irish music and ballads.
   The ride's not always smooth, but it's never boring.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
