<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, April 21-23 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: The Zen Conductor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he was younger, conductor Sergiu
Celibidache was known as an eccentric. Now he's known as a legend,
an artist who seeks truth in music and presents it like no other
conductor, a man who infuses his work with Zen.
   At 76 years old, Celibidache is making his first American tour
with the Munich Philharmonic. He will do 14 concerts this month in
11 cities. The two concerts at Carnegie Hall sold out in March.
   For the last five years, Celibidache has conducted only the
Munich Philharmonic. Rehearsals at Gasteig Hall in Munich, which
are free, are always full. He doesn't allow recordings because he
believes that taping changes the speed and brilliance of the
performance.
   He uses the principals of Zen and phenomenology in his work. The
Zen part is Celibidache and the orchestra rehearsing a lot then his
emptying his mind during the concert and having _ often _ a
transcendent experience. Phenomenology is the study of perceptual
experience in its subjective state.
   ``It is eternal no,'' he said. ``All the nos are eliminated and
we are only yes. The musicians would not call it phenomenology.
They say, `Oh, he knows what he does.'
   ``Phenomenology is the sience of why not so? It is not a causal
why. In the Zen discipline you say, `Is this this?' `Is this this
also?' It is not because this is the result of that. Transcendence
is the phase where thinking is over but we still go on living and
experiencing.
   ``I studied Buddhism. When I was 17 I read about this kind of
ego. I met a Zen monk. I had a master. You come to the point where
Zen will take over.
   ``Emptiness means ... the highest form of concentration. You
have the possibility to step in, every second. The prophets of the
Old Testament practiced that kind of consciousness. If it became
part of the conscious will, it didn't work.''
   When the eighth bar of a piece of music is wrong, Celibidache
said, it is because it didn't follow from the first bar and lead to
the last. ``When I was 42, I had an experience in Venice when I
made music. I saw the connection. It is the beginning and the end,
not one after the other but simultaneously.
   He was conducting three masses in a Venice church with two
choirs that didn't cooperate. Choral sound from balconies arrived
at a different rate than orchestral sound. Saturday rehearsal was
chaos, Celibidache recalled, and he wanted to cancel. ``Sunday
morning I prayed just to finish together.''
   On that Sunday, the church was packed, windows were open for
people outside, people were in aisles and the stairs up to his
podium were removed to make room for more bodies. Celibidache said
he could remember nothing after the performance started.
   ``Normal practice is when something happens wrong in the
orchestra you start trying to remake it and sometimes you succeed
and sometimes not. Nothing of that kind happened. I remember the
final amen, and I came to a kind of normal consciousness again,''
he said.
   ``That was the first experience. I went to conduct Brahms after
Venice. Now I have experienced it I want to have it again. I put my
whole weight behind it and pushed.'' Celibidache discovered what
Zen could have told him, that he could not will a transcendent
experience.
   ``I always am animated by the idea to know the composer's
original ideas,'' he said. And he doesn't conduct with
``discoveries'' or ``own ideas.''
   ``I don't have any `own ideas' at all. My object and my strength
is to find out what was the composer's ideas. What did he mean? I
have not discovered anything.
   ``If you think what I do is an interpretation, you're wrong,''
he said. ``This is the authentic way to play according to what we
could inquire about the way a composer used to play.''
   Celibidache said that too much music is mixed with economics.
``Why not more rehearsals? Because rehearsals do not pay,'' he said.
   ``Who conducts nowadays in Europe? The people whom Deutsche
Grammaphon (Records) recommends. Maybe there are good conductors we
do not know in a small village somewhere. In the big cities, that
is not possible.''
   Celibidache was born in Romania, and went to Germany to study
composition, conducting and musicology in 1936 when he was 24. He
was principal conductor of the Berlin Philharmonic from the end of
World War II until 1952 when Herbert von Karajan came in.
Celibidache became a guest conductor in Europe and Latin America.
But American orchestras and some European orchestras didn't engage
him because of his rehearsal requirements: He likes to rehearse
when and as often as he likes.
   The Curtis Institute of Music in Philadelphia invited
Celibidache to train the student orchestra for several months in
1983-84. Celibidache has been in Munich since 1979.
   ``I always avoided the big orchestras, which can follow only one
track, and I avoided living under the pressure of big cities,'' he
said. ``Big symphonies can not afford much rehearsal time and if
they give it they will cry still one year after.
   ``When Munich came to me, I said, `I need very many rehearsals.
I don't accept any pressure. I can not guarantee you a certain
rhythm of production.' They said, `It is all right for us. What
else do you want?' I said, `Nothing.' That is how I land in Munich.
   ``I promised them I'll make the Munich Philharmonic the best
orchestra in the world. I will contend that Munich is nowadays the
best orchestra as far as musical dialectic of the inner parts are
concerned. I don't know any big orchestra which orients itself like
chamber music. This has been not because Celibidache has such great
power. It is because I could find in the musicians an extraordinary
comprehension. The fact that we play Bruckner without facing a
single negative reaction is the confirmation of what I believe in.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 21-23</NOTE>
