<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, April 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ethicist Throws Light On Animal Life And Death Questions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As treatment of animals goes beyond neutering the
family cat and de-worming the dog, veterinarians face ethics
questions like physicians do.
   Should Fido be put to sleep? Does Bossie the cow deserve more
respect? Is the health of a race horse more important than the
owner's bottom line?
   ``The vet serves both the animal and the human community and is
caught in the middle,'' said Jerrold Tannenbaum, who teaches
veterinary law and ethics at the Tufts School of Veterinary
Medicine in Boston and North Grafton.
   Tannenbaum, 43, has offered guidelines for puzzling out
solutions to animal life-and-death questions in his new book,
``Veterinary Ethics.''
   Such questions stem in part from a growing appreciation of the
place pets hold in owners' livess. ``Certainly animals are not
people, but many people now regard pets as members of the family.
Part of what we're involved in here is the definition of these
beings. How high should they be regarded?''
   Animals, like people, can now benefit from expensive treatments.
Dogs can get pacemakers for $800 to $1,000 and hip replacements
costing upwards of $1,000. Cats undergo cancer chemotherapy for
around $1,000.
   Ethical issues arise when a vet is caught between advising the
use of such care and a pet owner who can't afford or doesn't want
to pay what it costs.
   They also extend to other animals: drugging thoroughbreds to
make them go faster, for example, or feeding cows antibiotics and
other drugs that put more meat on the table but could block
symptoms of animal suffering.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Tiny Shrimp May Point Way to Titanium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STATESBORO, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ghost shrimp, seldom-seen crustaceans
that have lived for eons beneath beach sand, may provide fossilized
clues that can help geologists locate valuable titanium deposits in
the Southeast.
   Igneous and metamorphic rocks that form the Piedmont area and
Blue Ridge mountains contain traces of titanium-rich heavy
minerals. As the rocks weather into sand and clay, particles are
carried down rivers and deposited along the coast. Waves and
currents sort the particles by size and density, depositing the
heavy minerals on some parts of the beach.
   ``The ghost shrimp that I'm studying ... appears to be almost
restricted to the beaches, and the heavy minerals are accumulating
on the beaches,'' said geologist Gale Bishop. ``If we can identify
burrows of that species in the past, we should be able to find
heavy mineral deposits.''
   Heavy minerals like rutile and ilmenite contain titanium, a
strong, light metal used by the space industry. Titanium oxide
whitens paints and papers.
   Bishop, of Georgia Southern College, is pumping up ghost shrimp
from beaches along the coast and recording their distribution,
shapes, size and claw types. The shrimp are seldom seen, living out
their lives deep in sandy burrows and feeding on organic debris,
bacteria and nutrients filtered from the water.
   ``What we hope to see is the upper part of the burrow, the
vertical shaft which would indicate we're near the sea-level of the
past. It might indicate heavy mineral deposits nearby,'' Bishop
said. ``The similarity of geological conditions ... in the
Carolinas, Georgia and northern Florida should indicate that heavy
mineral deposits could be found in any of these areas.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>`Not In My Backyard Wall' The Response To Sludge Bricks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Alleman has encountered more
than the ``not-in-my-backyard'' syndrome in trying to deal with
sewage sludge _ people who hear of his ``biobricks'' generally say
not in my wall.
   The environmental engineer worked with a Maryland manufacturer
to make bricks that have been used in two park shelters in
Washington, D.C., and two sewage treatment plants for the
Washington Suburban Sanitary Commission.
   More recently, he's discovered that even sludge laden with
hazardous metals can be put into the clay-sludge mixture that is
fired into bricks. Alleman has been unable to extract the metal
except with the strongest acids.
   ``We soaked them in an acid solution to simulate acid rain and
we couldn't get the metals back out. We had such a hard time we had
to dissolve the bricks. We had to use hydroflouric acid _ the
strongest acid we have,'' he said.
   Of course, if builders have an aversion to bricks made with
normal sludge, they're even less likely to use bricks made with
hazardous metals like nickel, arsenic, cadmium, chrome and lead _
no matter how safe they are.
   ``There's a lot of inorganic sludge with hazardous wastes in it.
You can't put it on farmers' lands, because the crops would be
contaminated with it,'' Alleman said. ``Those kinds of sludge are
ideal candidates for bricks.''
   He estimated that American cities dispose of 6,000 to 10,000
tons of sludge a day. Some bury it, others burn it and a few still
dump it in the ocean.
   The key to Alleman's process is the brick-making kiln, which
operates at 2,000 degrees over two days to bake the 50-50 mixture
of clay and sludge into bricks. In the process, any organic matter
in the sludge is burned away and any hazardous metals are fused
permanently into the brick.
   ``If I were a brick manufacturer, I would find somebody to pay
me to take sludge off their hands. It's easy. You need very hose work is
funded in part
by the National Science Foundation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for April 13</NOTE>
