<DOCNO> AP890410-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 0151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Germany-Cycling     04-10 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Germany-Cycling,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Outdoors: Cycling in Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP LaserPhoto NY700</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the traveler who feels more fear
than freedom during a high-speed hurtle along West Germany's
infamous autobahns, touring the Rhine River valley on two wheels
offers solace as well as scenery.
   From the famous rock of Lorelei, where the legendary siren lured
sailors to their deaths, to the majestic twin towers of Cologne's
14th century cathedral, some of the renowned valley's most splendid
sights are best reached and enjoyed from the seat of a bicycle.
   The 800-mile Rhine River sweeps from the Swiss Alps to the Dutch
North Sea coast. It threads a gentle and inspiring path through the
Black Forest, centuries-old spas where European royalty once
rested, windmill-studded farmland and vineyards ripe with the scent
of next fall's Riesling.
   Dozens of castles, from jagged ruins to restored Medieval
estates that now offer lodging or riverfront dining, dapple the
hillsides flanking the flat winding paths along the river's most
popular and attractive stretch, from Mainz to the capital city of
Bonn.
   The sport of cycling and combined exercise and travel have been
booming over the past decade as West Germans have become more
concerned about their health and the environment.
   Two out of three West Germans own a bicycle, and sales of the
two-wheeled vehicles now run nearly double the volume of cars sold
here, according to ADFC, the national bicycling association that
claims more than 25,000 members.
   Dovetailing the surge in cycling interest among West Germans and
foreign tourists has been a corresponding growth of separate
bicycle paths, touring clubs, guide services and repair shops that
has helped make the endeavor safer and more accessible.
   ``Although there has been a sharp increase in the number of
cyclists over the past few years, the number of accidents and
fatalities involving bicycles has been steadily decreasing,'' said
Karl-Ludwig Kelber, head of Bonn's ADFC chapter.
   The number of bicyclist fatalities dropped from 1,142 in 1980 to
730 in 1987, the last year for which statistics are available,
primarily because of the broader development of bike paths away
from the heavily traveled highways. In comparison, there were more
than 8,000 auto fatalities in West Germany last year.
   Despite the improved safety record and unique protections for
cyclists _ including a federal law requiring cars to pass no closer
than 5 feet _ a bicycling vacation is not for everyone.
   The ADFC and private touring services recommend that
inexperienced cyclists avoid attempting long journeys without being
accompanied by a professional guide.
   Travelers can arrange guided tours or individual itineraries
with guide services that transport bikes to the starting point and
carry baggage by minivan from one overnight stop to the next.
   West German trains also transport bicycles for a nominal fee,
allowing travelers who choose to chart their own course to skip
over some of the most polluted stretches of the river and the most
heavily industrialized areas that scar the landscape.
   Food and lodging abound along the highly developed Rhine, and
travelers can also arrange special-interest bicycle trips such as a
tour of the valley's numerous small wineries.
   The ADFC has collected and published a detailed two-volume
guidebook to the Rhine River bike paths, covering the entire
waterway from its headwaters near St. Gotthard, Switzerland, to its
delta outflow at Hoek van Holland.
   The books, which are published in German but contain notes and
glossaries in English and Dutch, describe path conditions,
sightseeing opportunities, hotel and restaurant facilities and the
location of shops that rent bikes or repair them.
   There are also recommendations on when to cross from one side of
the north-flowing river to the other, making use of the more than
100 bridges and ferries crossing the waterway to take the more
scenic route or avoid ``anti-bicycle'' strongholds where cyclists
are expected to dismount and walk.
   General information about cycling in West Germany and bike path
maps of specific regions are available by mail from the ADFC's
national headquarters: ADFC, Postfach 107744, 2800 Bremen, West
Germany.
   But for detailed planning of a trip and information about group
or guided tours, the organization recommends cyclists contact a
travel agent or the ADFC's commercial tour operator, Velomobil, at
the Bremen address.
</TEXT>
