<DOCNO> AP890410-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Keeping'EmAlive     04-10 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Keeping 'Em Alive,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Outdoors: Keeping `Em Alive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Keep fish alive in your boat with clean, cool
water, oxygen, and chemical treatment to calm the fish and help
them recover from injuries, including the touch of your hands.
   ``About the most important thing is the way you handle the fish
in the first place,'' said Tony Gergley, vice president of Jungle
Laboratories Corp., which has been studying ways to keep fish alive
in aquariums and livewells.
   ``Use heavy enough tackle in the first place to bring the fish
in without exhausting it, and then be careful handling it when you
take the hook out,'' he said in an interview from his Cibolo,
Texas, office. ``We don't recommend the use of nets, although I
know a lot of people use them. But they can tear up a fish too bad,
can hurt them too much.''
   Gergley and the Bass Anglers Sportsman Society ran an experiment
at major BASSmaster tournaments last year ``and we did not lose a
fish,'' he said.
   Livewells in boats were treated with Catch and Release, made by
Jungle Laboratories, and water inside was cooled with ice.
   Catch and Release is a tranquilizer and water conditioner. It
also adds electrolytes to water to restore them to the fish.
   The water treatment also stimulates slime protection by fish.
When a fish is stressed by being caught and handled, the cells
which produce slime ``clamp up,'' Gergley said. ``Taking off the
slime is like taking the skin off a human. You are going to get
infection.''
   Lower the water temperature in the livewell about 15 degrees
from lake water temperature.
   ``In a good-sized livewell, five to eight pounds of ice at one
time will not hurt your fish,'' Gergley said. ``I think they will
love you for it.''
   The best way to monitor water temperature is to put an aquarium
thermometer in the livewell, he said. The experiments with BASS, he
added, ``disproved the old wives' tale that you can't drop
temperature on bass or it will kill them.''
   Finally, make sure the water in the livewell is clean. If you
get your boat in very shallow water and the pump sucks mud into the
livewell, change the water, even if it means you have to dip it out.
   ``It's less harmful to the fish to change the water and leave
them out of water for a minute or two than to leave them in dirty
water,'' he said.
   New boats, he said, have aeration and recirculating systems in
livewells, making the livewells in-boat aquariums. Older livewells
circulate water from below the boat into the livewell.
   By keeping your fish alive, you can return to the water those
you don't need for a tournament or don't want for dinner. They can
grow and be caught another time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Hiking     04-10 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Hiking,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Outdoors: Hiking</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to hiking in the Southeast, North Carolina wants
you to think of North Carolina.
   Hiking trails in the Tar Heel State are used more than any other
trails in the nation, according to the U.S. Forest Service. More
than 500,000 recreation visitor days are recorded each year.
   ``Hiking is one of our key trail activities,'' says Melinda
Waldrep, trail specialist and landscape architect for the U.S.
Forest Service in Asheville, N.C. ``Our area is unique because of
our waterfalls, rock features and because the Southern Appalachians
have the largest number of plant species in the world.''
   National park land in the state includes the Great Smoky
Mountains National Park, with 900 miles of maintained hiking
trails, the Nantahala National Forest and the Pisgah National
Forest.
   Travelers who are unfamiliar with the area can take day or
half-day hiking trips with the Sierra Club or the Carolina Mountain
Club. Or they can try unguided but well-marked trails inside local
private parks such as Chimney Rock in Lake Lure, 25 miles southeast
of Asheville, or Grandfather Mountain, the highest peak in the Blue
Ridge range, at 5,964 feet.
   The Carolina Mountain Club publishes a guide, ``100 Favorite
Trails of the Great Smokies and Carolina Blue Ridge,'' written by
club member Bernard Elias. The club has conducted more than 6,000
hiking trips around Asheville since it was established in 1931.
   ``There is an interesting companionship that develops on a hike
with a group from this area,'' says Elias. ``It's a good way to get
to talk to each other away from the distractions of city life. You
get a feeling of closeness with the wonders of nature and a real
appreciation of life.''
   Some of the trails recommended by Elias include:
   _ The Mountains to the Sea Trail, part of a 750-mile path that
will eventually stretch between the Smoky Mountains and the eastern
coast of North Carolina. The trail, surrounded by thick green
forests, is open for the first time this year.
   _ The Shut-in Trail, a 16-mile trail running parallel to the
Blue Ridge Parkway, offers stunning overlooks into the valleys
below. It's a full-day hike one way.
   _ Blue Ridge Pinnacle, near Mount Mitchell off the Blue Ridge
Parkway, is a three-mile round-trip hike.
   _ Horsepasture River trail has waterfalls and many hikers take
along bathing suits for a dip in the falls or river along the way,
says Elias.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 0200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:WithHiking-Tips     04-10 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Outdoors: With Hiking-Tips,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Outdoors: With Hiking-Tips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every year, thousands of tourists roam
through North Carolina's mountains on trails that range from short
``leg-stretchers'' along the Blue Ridge Parkway to long-distance
treks through the remote wilderness.
   Some end up lost, others with injuries that run from sprains to
broken legs. A few die from falls, exposure or over-exertion.
   Here are some tips from experts on hiking in the mountains:
   _ Pick the right clothes. Wear hiking boots or a good pair of
sneakers with deep tread, heavy socks and loose-fitting,
long-legged pants. A T-shirt is fine in moderate weather, but carry
a sweater or wind breaker that can be tied around the waist. And
take a hat, even if it's just a baseball cap. Add more clothing as
the weather becomes more extreme.
   ``Wearing a pair of thin, nylon socks with hiking boots is about
like going barefoot,'' said Jeff Wahoo Stanley, owner of Wahoo's
Outdoor Adventures in Boone. ``We've found that some of the best
pants for hiking are just ordinary sweatpants _ the kind with a
drawstring waist. They protect your legs, but they're comfortable
and warm.''
   _ Carry a minimum amount of equipment. Anyone going into the
woods, even on a short hike, should carry a pocket knife, a
cigarette lighter, water and a few first-aid supplies. A small
day-pack can hold lunches and enough supplies for several people.
   _ Choose the right trail. Steep, rugged trails might be fine for
an experienced 30-year-old hiker. But a 6-year-old or novice hiker
doesn't need that much of a challenge. Check with outfitters or
other local experts about available trails, their degree of
difficulty and hazards.
   _ Make sure someone knows where you are. Always tell someone
what trail you intend to take and your estimated return time.
   _ Never hike alone. ``The worst thing you can do is go out by
yourself because you never know what can happen,'' said Tom Collins
of the Watauga County Emergency Management Office. ``You get bitten
by a snake, turn an ankle or take a fall and you're just out there
on your own until somebody happens to come across you.''
   _ Do not leave the trail. Heavy foliage in the mountains
sometimes hides sheer drops. And taking a short-cut on a trail that
winds back and forth on a mountainside can lead to erosion and
other ecological damage.
   _ Don't panic. If you lose your way, stop and think before
taking action. Following a stream downstream will eventually lead
to a road or a place where you can get help. If darkness is
falling, stay where you are for the night. Wandering around in the
darkness can lead to a fall. Wait for daylight and make your way
back to the trail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890410-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 0201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Turkeyhunting     04-10 0929</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Turkey hunting,0959</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION ^Outdoors: Turkey Hunting ^AP LaserPhoto NY703</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUSKEGEE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The turkey is too magnificent a bird to be
shot at 100 yards with a rifle, declared James Earl Kennamer.
   ``He's got to be called within shotgun range,'' said Kennamer,
director of research and management for the National Wild Turkey
Federation, a moving force behind the recovery of the wild turkey
in North America.
   He then proceeded to demonstrate, calling two toms and at least
two hens within 55 yards using a box call, slate call and mouth
call. The birds, however, stayed about 15 yards outside the range
of shotguns, loaded with No. 6 shot, and lived to thrill other
hunters with their ear-rattling gobbles.
   A turkey gobbles to tell hens where he is and to call them to
him.
   A turkey hunter calls like a hen, trying to seduce the gobbler
to abandon his waiting and come to her.
   ``Any hunter can learn to use calls,'' Kennamer said. ``The box
call is the easiest to learn and you start with that.''
   ``But calling is overrated. It's important, but you don't have
to be a world class caller to hunt turkeys,'' he said. ``Good
woodsmanship is vital to kill turkeys.''
   The woodsmanship starts with quiet and ends with invisibility.
   ``You've got to be quiet enough to get close enough to birds to
call them without them hearing you, and a turkey's hearing is
acute,'' Kennamer said.
   Camouflage yourself from head to toe, making sure there are no
gaps allowing some white skin on a wrist, a ring or the flash of a
belt buckle to betray you to a turkey.
   ``A turkey can see you blink while he is outside gun range,''
Kennamer said. ``You must not only be camouflaged, you must not
move a muscle while that turkey is in a position where he can see
you.''
   A turkey's head is red, white and blue. As a safety precaution,
Kennamer stressed, don't wear any of those colors when in the woods
during turkey season, because you may become the target for a
careless hunter.
   A hunter's calls are similar to musical instruments, and in the
hands of an expert caller become exactly that.
   The first call is the box call, a rectangular box with a top
which slides across the sides, imitating the yelp, gobble and other
calls.
   ``The box call carries further in the woods than any other
call,'' Kennamer said.
   He has had his current box call 17 years. He occasionally
smooths the underside of the top with very fine sandpaper and
frequently chalks it with soft builders' chalk. When the top slides
across the side of the box, the box resonates, like a violin.
   Next is the slate call, a slab of rock or other hard material
also in box form. The shell of a box turtle makes an excellent
slate call, he said. It is played by rubbing a strike across the
surface. Many strikers today are made of plastic or acrylic.
   Kennamer sands the surface of his slate with ultrafine sandpaper
and draws the striker across the sanded area to imitate the
turkey's putts and purrs.
   Both have a major drawback. They must be worked in the hunter's
hands, and the movement can give away his position to a gobbler.
The bird's vision is many times better than a human's.
   The answer is the mouth call. It's the most difficult to master,
but it can be used without any giveaway movement.
   About the size of a half-dollar with part cut away, the mouth
call is a reed instrument, like a clarinet or saxophone. Pressed
against the roof of the mouth, it is played by forcing air across
its reeds.
   ``Some people have trouble with a gagging reaction'' in keeping
the call in their mouths, Kennamer said. ``But it can be overcome
with a little practice.''
   To carry his gear, Kennamer wears a vest with zipped pouches.
   ``I lost one of my favorite calls when it fell out of a pocket
when I was crossing a stream,'' he said.
   He also has room for a snack, two compasses, snakebite kit, crow
call, owl call, small first-aid kit and some tissues. A cushion
attaches to the bottom of the vest.
   The cushion can be vital to the hunter who has to sit motionless
at the base of a tree for several hours, seducing a turkey.
   Picking the right tree is important, Kennamer stressed.
   ``It's got to be wide enough to cover your silhouette
completely,'' he said. ``Make sure there are no branches or brush
that will move if you bump them with your gun as you line up your
shot. A turkey will see that branch move even if you have stopped.''
   The ideal hunt starts the previous night, tracking a gobbler to
his roost at sunset. Use an owl call to get him to gobble, then
follow the sound.
   Set up within 100 to 150 yards of that tree before dawn. Once
the turkey gobbles and flies down, start making alluring sounds
with your calls.
   If you have to reach for your gun, do it when his head is behind
a tree or other object and he can't see you. Point it at where you
think he will reappear and freeze.
   With No. 6 shot, don't even think of a shot outside 40 yards.
Aim for the head and neck for a clean kill. Aiming for the body
probably will mean a wounded bird that dies later.
</TEXT>
