<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Trailers     04-10 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Trailers,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Outdoors: Trailers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Safer travel may be ensured by equipping travel trailers and
other vehicles properly, especially with efficient hitches and
electrical hook-ups.
   ``A quality hitch properly suited for the trailer tongue, weight
and your particular automobile is a necessity,'' says Steve
Cochran, agricultural engineer with the Texas Agricultural
Extension Service.
   ``Universal-type hitches cannot always be adapted to all
automobiles,'' Cochran says. ``Heavy duty shock absorbers or
springs may have to be installed on the car if the trailer tongue
weight exceeds towing specifications. Transmission coolers and
external electric fan cooling devices can be used to supplement
standard engine cooling fans.''
   To compensate for the extra electrical load a trailer adds, he
says, add a heavy duty flasher to the turn signal and emergency
flashers.
   ``Extra wiring presents a need for a quality trailer plug to
make the added electrical load compatible with your car,'' Cochran
says. ``A 6-connector plug allows for tail lignts, left and right
turn signals, stop lights, back-up lights and a ground. If the
trailer has brakes, a 7 or 8 plug is needed.''
   A trailer's added weight and length calls for extra equipment
and safety precautions to ensure a safe trip.
   ``Extra length side mirrors may have to be added to the towing
vehicle for good rear vision,'' Cochran says. ``Wide angle mirrors
used in conjunction with standard mirrors are best for covering
blind spots.''
   In loading a trailer, Cochran suggests placing 60 percent of the
total weight in front of the trailer axle to provide maximum
stability, and adding extra air in the tires to reduce side sway
and overheating.
   The added weight and length of a trailer alters driving
conditions, he says. Passing calls for at least doubling the space
and time normally needed. He cautioned against over-steer when
making lane changes or the trailer will sway or ``whip.''
   Lightly pumping the brakes when stopping can prevent them from
over-heating due to the extra load, Cochran says, adding:
   ``By following these suggestions, your pace will be more
leisurely, the drive smoother and safer, and your family will have
a better chance to enjoy the scenery.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
