<FIRST>r f PM-ConsolidatedGold     04-10 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consolidated Gold,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minorco Raises Offer for Consolidated Gold Fields</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African-backed Minorco SA today sweetened to
$6.02 billion its takeover bid for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC in
a final attempt to win control of Britain's largest mining company.
   Minorco increased its offer by raising the cash portion of the
bid for a total of $26.35 a share, up from the previous offer of
$23.80 per share, or a total of $5.4 billion. Minorco first offered
$5.1 billion last fall.
   Minorco, which owns 29.6 percent of Consolidated Gold Fields, is
hoping to meet an April 26 deadline set by British regulators for
gaining more than 50 percent control.
   The company received British regulatory clearance in February
allowing it to proceed with the takeover battle it originally
launched in September.
   The offer, however, still depends on Minorco winning its appeal
against a U.S. court injunction blocking Minorco from acquiring
more than 30 percent of Consolidated Gold Fields' shares.
   The Minorco bid is the largest for a British company, topping
Nestle SA's $4.6 billion purchase of British confectioner Rowntree
PLC last year.
   Based in Luxembourg, Minorco is 60 percent-owned by the
Oppenheimers' Anglo American Corp. gold mining giant and the
diamond mining group De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd. of South
Africa.
</TEXT>
