<FIRST>u f PM-Gulf&amp;Western     04-10 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf &amp; Western,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communications Giant To Sell Financial Services Unit, Change Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New 3rd graf, Wall Street ... Stock Exchange, to UPDATE
with morning stock price. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``The sale ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf &amp; Western Inc. says it will sell its
financial-services operations and change its name as it completes
its transformation from a diverse conglomerate to an entertainment
and publishing company.
   The company, the parent of Paramount Pictures, said Sunday it
would change its name to Paramount Communications Inc. after
selling The Associates, its consumer and commercial financial unit.
   Wall Street applauded the move today. Gulf &amp; Western jumped
$3.25 to $52.75 a share in active mid-morning trading on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   ``The sale of The Associates represents another phase in our
strategic development,'' said Martin S. Davis, Gulf &amp; Western's
chairman and chief executive.
   ``We have concluded that the current market dynamics and the
financial and regulatory restraints inherent in our
consumer-commercial finance business are incompatible with those of
our entertainment and publishing operations,'' he said in a
statement.
   Proceeds from the sale would be used to expand the entertainment
and publishing operations through product development and through
acquisitions, the company said.
   In addition, the company said it would continue a program to buy
back Gulf &amp; Western stock on the open market or through tender
offers.
   Gulf &amp; Western spokesman Jerry Sherman declined to state what
acquisitions may be of interest to the New York-based company. He
also would not say what price the company expected to fetch for the
financial services division.
   Company directors approved the restructuring Friday, he said.
   Financial analyst Mark Manson of Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette
Inc. said he believed the restructuring was a good move and that it
would boost the company's stock price.
   ``Paramount has been the leading film company for most of the
last decade,'' he said. ``They're a leader in the educational
publishing area as well. So I think they can expand their already
very strong positions in those areas.''
   He said the stock market has been unwilling to recognize what he
believes is the true worth of The Associates as reflected in Gulf &amp;
Western's share prices.
   But, Manson said, the company is taking a risk in running what
essentially is a public auction for the division. ``They are
assuming there will be a buyer or buyers out there that will
recognize the value they are seeking,'' he said.
   Manson placed the value of The Associates as in excess of $3.2
billion.
   The company has retained the New York investment banking firm
Lazard Freres &amp; Co. to find a buyer for the division, formally
called the Associates First Capital Corp., Sherman said.
   The Associates has 520 retail branch offices in 42 states and
Puerto Rico, through which it offers mortgages, retail loans and
other personal financing. It also has 95 offices in Japan and 45 in
the United Kingdom.
   The commercial division of The Associates, with 75 offices in
the United States and Canada, is a leading source of financing for
the trucking industry, Sherman said.
   The Associates also operates a bank in California, Associates
National Bank, whose sole business is issuing credit cards, he said.
   The financial division had operating income of $372.4 million on
revenue of $2.05 billion in the fiscal year ended Oct. 31, 1988,
Sherman said.
   The net receivable base of The Associates has grown from $4.5
billion in 1982 to $11.2 billion, the company said. Its assets
exceed $13 billion. It has had a record profit the past 12 years.
   Gulf &amp; Western's publishing and entertainment operations had an
operating profit of $431.8 million on revenue of $3.06 billion in
the fiscal year, the company said.
   Combined, the company reported a net profit of $384.7 million on
revenue of $5.11 billion in the fiscal year.
   In addition to Paramount's movie, television and home-video
interests, the company's operations include book publishers
Prentice Hall, Pocket Books, and Simon and Schuster; the Canadian
theater chain Famous Players; Madison Square Garden and its cable
TV network; the New York Knicks basketball team and the New York
Rangers hockey team.
   The divestment of the financial services arm would cap a
restructuring begun six years ago that has seen the sale of
divisions with combined revenue of more than $4 billion.
   The units were involved in areas as diverse as manufacturing,
building products, natural resources, cigars, sugar growing,
automotive parts, apparel, bedding and home furnishings.
</TEXT>
