<FIRST>u f PM-Ford-Gilmour     04-10 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford-Gilmour,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Names Gilmour To New Position</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allan Gilmour, Ford Motor Co.'s executive
vice president for international operations, Monday was named
executive vice president in charge of corporate staffs and a member
of the company's office of the chief executive.
   Gilmour, seen as likely to eventually step into the driver's
seat of the nation's No. 2 automaker, will be succeeded by Louis R.
Ross as executive vice president for international automotive
operations, Ford said.
   Alexander J. Trotman, former chairman of Ford of Europe, will
move into Ross's post as executive vice president for North
American automotive operations.
   The appointments are effective May 1, Ford Chairman Donald E.
Petersen said.
   Gilmour, 54, joined Ford in 1960 as a financial analyst. From
1968-72 he was a special assistant to J. Edward Lundy, Ford's
executive vice president for finance.
   In 1975, Gilmour was named president of Ford Motor Credit Co.,
the company's consumer financing arm, and four years later, he was
elected vice president and controller.
   Gilmour became vice president for external and personnel affairs
in 1984, and executive vice president and chief financial officer
in 1986. He took over the company's international operations in
October 1987.
</TEXT>
