<HEAD>Grain, Soybeans Mostly Lower on Chicago Board of Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower in early activity today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   With demand weak and enough moisture in both the western
cornbelt and the southwestern wheat growing areas, traders expected
prices to settle in slightly lower ranges and stay there most of
the day.
   But some support came from talk of possible buys by the Soviet
Union and a strong cash market also underpinned prices.
   Soybeans, meanwhile, got some backing from reports that the
harvest in Brazil was being delayed by too much rain.
   Wheat was 1 cent lower to 2 cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in May at $3.93{ cents a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1\
cents higher, with May at $2.66; oats were } cents to 1\ cents
higher, with May at $1.86}; and soybeans were 2{ cents to 6 cents
higher, with May at $7.17.
