<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-CBS     04-10 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-CBS,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Net Income Down From Year Ago, But Operating Net Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. said Monday its first-quarter profit
skidded from a year earlier, when results were swelled by a huge
gain on the sale of its records division, but said improvement at
its television network helped boost income from continuing
operations by 26 percent.
   The broadcasting giant said its net income fell to $56.1
million, or $2.18 a share, in the three months ended March 31 from
$911.3 million, or $35.34 a share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 5 percent to $731.2 million from
$696.6 million a year earlier.
   The 1988 results were fattened by an after-tax gain of $866.6
million on the sale of CBS Records to Sony Corp.
   CBS said its income from continuing operations rose to a record
$56.3 million from $44.8 million a year earlier.
   Laurence A. Tisch, president and chief executive, said the
operating reuslts reflected a profit of undisclosed size at the CBS
Television Network in contrast with a ``minor loss'' a year earlier.
   He said the network had improved results in several key time
periods including primetime, sports and news.
   The miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' was broadcast during the
quarter and achieved the highest ratings for that type of program
in five years.
   The company said its interest income fell to $39.4 million from
$51.5 million in the same period a year earlier, which included a
pre-tax gain of $14 million on the sale of Treasury securities.
   The decline was also attributed to lower balances of cash and
securities due to tax payments on the CBS Records sale and
acquisitions of a television station in Miami and two radio
stations in Detroit.
</TEXT>
