<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Minorco-ConsolidatedGold     04-10 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minorco-Consolidated Gold,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minorco Increases Offer for Consolidated Gold Fields</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minorco SA, the investment arm of a South African
gold and diamond empire, on Monday made a last-ditch $6.02 billion
offer for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   Minorco increased its offer by raising the cash portion of the
bid for a total of $26.35 a share, up from the previous offer of
$23.80 per share, or a total of $5.4 billion. Minorco first offered
$5.1 billion last fall.
   Minorco said the offer was a final attempt to gain control of
Britain's largest mining company. If successful, the takeover would
be the largest ever of a British company.
   ``Our offer ... is our final word and represents a full premium
for control,'' Minorco Chief Executive Michael Edwardes said.
``Nobody will pay more.''
   British regulators have set an April 26 deadline for Minorco's
attempt to capture more than 50 percent of Consolidated Gold
Fields. Minorco, a mining investment concern, currently owns 29.6
percent of Gold Fields.
   The offer still depends on Minorco winning its appeal of an
injunction issued in U.S. District Court in Manhattan blocking
Minorco from acquiring more than 30 percent of Consolidated Gold
Fields' shares.
   The shares, which closed at $23.71 Friday, jumped to $25.07
early Monday before Minorco announced its revised offer, then fell
back to $24.02.
   Based in Luxembourg, Minorco is 60 percent-owned by the
Oppenheimer family's Anglo American Corp. gold mining giant and the
diamond mining group De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd.
   Minorco's original $5.1 billion hostile bid last September
automatically lapsed when it was referred to Britain's Monopolies
and Mergers Commission. The commission cleared the proposed
acquisition in February, prompting the renewed bids.
   In a novel defense against Minorco, Consolidated Gold Fields has
promised to pay its shareholders $2.2 billion in dividends if it
does not meet its own profit forecast. The company has guaranteed
shareholders more than 20 percent average annual compound growth in
earnings per share over the next three years.
   If its target of $6.80 in cumulative earnings per share is not
reached by the end of the 1992 fiscal year, then shareholders will
get a special cash dividend of $10.20 a share, it said.
</TEXT>
