<FIRST>r f BC-SiliconBuyout     04-10 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Silicon Buyout,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Tape-Maker TDK to Buy Silicon Systems Inc. for $200 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Silicon Systems Inc. has agreed to be
bought by Japanese recording tape company TDK Corp. in a deal that
values the computer chip maker at $200 million.
   The Orange County company makes integrated circuits for use in
computer hard-disk memory systems and in modems, the devices that
allow computers to communicate with each other over phone lines.
   TDK has agreed to pay $20 a share, or a total of about $200
million, for Silicon Systems stock, the companies announced Monday.
Once the Japanese company has acquired a majority of the stock
through a tender offer to shareholders, the companies will be
merged.
   Silicon Systems management and workforce will be retained, said
Ken Aoshima, a vice president of TDK USA, the company's U.S.
marketing arm.
   The California company, with 950 employees in the United States
and 450 in Singapore, reported a profit of $12.7 million on sales
of $120.8 million in 1988.
   The deal should not be portrayed as a Japanese acquisition of
American technology, the company's president, Carmelo Santoro, has
said.
   Santoro told the Wall Street Journal in an interview published
Monday that his company doesn't develop technology, but rather
makes and markets components based on existing knowledge.
   TDK is best known to consumers as a maker of audio and video
tapes and computer disks, though 65 percent of its business is in
manufacture of components for electronic gear.
   TDK, publicly traded in Japan, had sales of $3.4 billion in its
latest fiscal year.
</TEXT>
