<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Waterford     04-10 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Waterford,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crystal Company Reports Worse-Than-Expected Financial Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Waterford Glass Group PLC, Ireland's
well-know but financially troubled crystal company, reported Monday
that it made a small profit in 1988 compared to a loss in the
previous year.
   However, the company called last year's earnings of $430,000,
vs. a $85.37 million loss in 1987, ``significantly worse than
expected.''
   Sales rose to $435.29 million from $403.97 million.
   Waterford had been optimistic about its 1988 figures until it
hired accountants Peat Marwick McLintock in January to conduct an
independent review of its financial performance.
   The accounting firm discovered serious accounting errors, and
shortly after Waterford Chairman Paddy Hayes resigned. He is being
replaced by Paddy Byrne, chairman and chief executive of
Waterford's Wedgwood division.
   The accountants found that Waterford's internal review had
overstated last year's profits by $21.45 million largely through
overvaluation of inventories.
   In recent years, Waterford, one of Ireland's best known
manufacturers and one of the country's largest employers, has
suffered huge losses and laid off one-third of the 3,000 employees
in its crystal division.
   Half of Waterford's crystal is exported directly to the United
States and another 35 percent is bought by Americans traveling
abroad.
</TEXT>
