<DOCNO> AP890410-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Boeing-Asiana     04-10 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-Asiana,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Korean Airline Orders $1 Billion In Boeing Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new South Korean airline with plans for
service to Europe and North America on Monday announced a deal
worth about $1 billion to buy nine Boeing Co. jetliners and take
options on seven more.
   Including the new agreement with fledgling Asiana Airlines,
Seattle-based Boeing has announced orders for 110 jetliners worth
$8.7 billion so far this year.
   Asiana, based in Seoul, South Korea, began operations within
that country on Dec. 23. It said it will use its new jets to expand
to other Asian markets and eventually to North America and Europe.
   Asiana ordered five 737-400s and took options for another five.
It also signed letters of intent to order two 747-400 jumbo jets
and take options for two more, and to convert two previous options
for widebody 767-300s to firm orders.
   A 747-400, the world's largest passenger jet, sells for $116
million to $136 million a copy, depending on configuration and
equipment, Boeing said. The smaller 737-400 twin-jet sells for $31
million to $36 million, while a widebody 767-300 goes for $66
million to $73 million.
   ``In the short term, we could have saved a few dollars by buying
or leasing older planes,'' S.Y. Park, chairman of Kumho Business
Group, Asiana's parent company, said at a news conference.
   ``However, a new airline has enough problems establishing its
market base without the burden of heavy maintenance
responsibilities and the uncertainty of whether older planes will
perform reliably,'' he said.
   Park said other aircraft manufacturers had talked about selling
planes to Asiana, ``but at first, others didn't take us seriously.
Boeing did take us seriously.''
   J.F. Chorlton, a Boeing vice president, said Asiana had
indicated an interest in Boeing aircraft as early as a year ago. He
said Boeing had made room on its production line for the planes
before the order was announced.
   Asiana began its Korean service with six 737-400s leased from
GPA Group Ltd.
   Deliveries of Asiana's new planes will begin in July 1992 and
continue through June 1993. Asiana will get the two 767-300s
ordered earlier in 1990, Boeing said.
   Boeing normally doesn't announce letters of intent, said Boeing
Commercial Airplanes spokesman Randy Harrison, but Asiana had made
it clear it intended to buy the planes.
   Harrison said a letter of intent is just short of an order, but
no money is paid to begin construction.
</TEXT>
