<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-10 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0196</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices closed mixed, but soybeans
were mostly higher Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Both markets opened under slight pressure as a result of weak
demand and weekend rain or snowfall in both the western cornbelt
and the southwest wheat growing areas.
   Following last week's losses, soybeans skidded to an 11-month
low, only to make a quick runup on ideas the market may have been
oversold.
   Although commission houses and local traders continued buying,
the large commercial houses blunted the rally by staying on the
selling side of the equation and soybeans closed off the high for
the day.
   Both old-crop wheat and corn were higher on short-covering, but
contracts for the deferred months remained lower.
   On the close, wheat was 4{ cents lower to 3 cents higher, with
the contract for May delivery at $3.94{; corn was 1 cent lower to 1
cent higher, with May at $2.66}; oats were { cent to 1{ cents
higher, with May at $1.87; and soybeans were 6} cents to 8} cents
higher, with May at $7.18{.
