<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1719EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-FrenchBank     04-10 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-French Bank,0238</SECOND>
<UNK>U.S. To Use French Bank To Push Sales to Africa</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal Export-Import Bank on Monday
announced an agreement with a French bank to push loans for the
sale of American products in 18 African countries, 12 of them
former French colonies.
   The Export-Import Bank said in a statement that the deal with
Banque Internationale pour l'Afrique Occidentale (BIAO-Afribank)
would help U.S. exporters penetrate markets traditionally dominated
by European exporters.
   BIAO-Afribank began more than 130 years ago as the bank of issue
in Senegal, said Mario Varela, general manager of the bank's New
York office. Now private, the bank has headquarters in Paris and
offices in former British colonies, including Nigeria and Zimbabwe.
   The Export-Import bank makes loans to encourage purchases of
U.S. exports, especially in Third World countries.
   Varela said the agreement has been in effect since December and
a loan to Burkina Faso, formerly Upper Volta, is being negotiated.
   The statement did not mention France as a specific target of
competition.
   It said if there is evidence of foreign competition,
BIAO-Afribank can lend U.S. dollars from the Export-Import Bank at
internationally agreed rates of interest. It also can use a U.S.
guarantee program to cover loans in French francs as well as those
in dollars.
   Loans must be for U.S. exports of $200,001 or more. No upper
limit was named.
</TEXT>
