<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLdWritethru   04-10 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld Writethru,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell sharply on the London Stock
Exchange Monday, depressed by continued fears that British interest
rates might have to rise to contain inflationary pressures.
   At the close the Financial Times 100 index was down 20.7 points,
or 1.01 percent, at 2025.0. The index plunged as much as 30.8
points shortly after the producer price index numbers were
released. At its best, the index was up 1.2 points at the opening.
   The Financial Times 500 index closed down 10.97 at 1151.34.
   Equities opened on shaky ground, following bearish forecasts for
the economy issued late last week by two leading stock brokerages.
   Prices then headed sharply lower following the release of the
producer price index for March. The data, on a seasonally adjusted
basis, suggested British manufacturers faced continued cost
pressures.
   Also depressing share prices was nervousness before a series of
additional economic figures later this week, including British
average earnings and employment data on Thursday, and British
inflation and U.S. trade numbers on Friday.
</TEXT>
