<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-10 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened slightly against most
major currencies in moderate trading Monday despite central bank
intervention.
   Gold prices moved ahead at home after a mixed performance
abroad. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of $385.20
for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, $1.95 higher than
Friday's late bid.
   John McCarthy, chief dealer at Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank, said
the dollar was bid higher amid market rumors and continuing
reaction to the U.S. employment report issued Friday.
   According to one unconfirmed report that triggered dollar
purchases, U.S. Treasury officials have decided that the dollar is
trading at acceptable levels and that a lower dollar could be
inflationary and stem the flow of much-needed foreign capital into
the United States, McCarthy said.
   The Labor Department's report of a decline in the unemployment
rate to 5 percent last month from 5.1 percent in February was taken
as slightly supportive of the dollar.
   McCarthy said the U.S. currency rose in spite of dollar sales by
the Federal Reserve. He said the U.S. central bank sold dollars
when the currency was trading at around 1.88 West German marks.
   Currency dealers expect the dollar to trade in a narrow range
during the next few days as the market awaits a series of economic
statistics, including the Commerce Department report on retail
sales Thursday and the Labor Department's Producer Price Index on
Friday.
   The dollar began its trading day in Tokyo by rising 0.45
Japanese yen to a closing of 132.53 yen. Later, in London, it edged
up further to 132.65 yen and in New York it finished at 132.90, up
from Friday's 132.725.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6995, more expensive for
buyers than $1.6975 late Friday.
   After European dealing ended, U.K. Chancellor of the Exchequer
Nigel Lawson renewed the government's determination to fight
inflation, vowing to raise interest rates if necessary. The comment
spurred sterling purchases in U.S. trading and late in New York a
pound was quoted at $1.6955 compared to $1.6945 on Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday's late
rates, included: 1.88325 West German marks, up from 1.8765; 1.66075
Swiss francs, up from 1.6499; 6.35675 French francs, up from 6.336;
1,379.45 Italian lire, up from 1,376.00; and, 1.18945 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.19305.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday:
1.8785 West German marks, up from 1.8745; 1.6565 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6500; 6.3425 French francs, up from 6.3340; 2.1200 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1110; 1,378.50 Italian lire, up from 1,373.50;
1.1890 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1928.
   In New York, a troy ounce of gold for current delivery closed at
$386 on the Commodity Exchange, up from Friday's settlement of
$383.40.
   Gold bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $382.45 a
troy ounce, up from $381.75 bid late Friday.
   In Zurich, the metal fell to a late bid of $381.50 from $382 bid
late Friday.
   Earlier, gold fell $1.28 in Hong Kong to close at a bid $383.50.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.77 a troy
ounce from $5.76 bid late Friday.
   Silver for current delivery also increased in New York, rising
to $5.821 a troy ounce from $5.769 Friday.
</TEXT>
