<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-10 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures rose in volatile trading
Monday, led by strength in the gasoline market as the start of the
summer driving season continued to increase demand.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for
unleaded gasoline rose 2.34 cents to 67.29 cents a gallon.
Contracts for delivery between June and September also showed
strong gains, up more than a penny.
   The May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, closed 57 cents higher at $20.59 a barrel. And
heating oil for May delivery ended the day at 53.45 cents a gallon,
up 1.85 cents from last Friday's session.
   Analysts attributed the market's strength largely to technical
trading in advance of the American Petroleum Institute's weekly
report on oil and gas inventories. The report is scheduled for
release after the close of trading on Tuesday.
   ``People are anticipating bullish (numbers),'' said James R.
Fiedler, vice president of energy brokering for E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc. ``They're anticipating draw-downs in
gasoline and crude oil as the ramifications continue of the Valdez
disaster.''
   Two weeks ago, the oil tanker Exxon Valdez went aground off the
Alaskan coast spilling thousands of barrels of its cargo into
Prince William Sound. The spill temporarily halted oil shipments
from Alaska.
   Nauman Barakat, vice president of energy investments at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.,said strong seasonal demand for
gasoline and new summer octane regulations likely to strain
refinery capacity gave the market its initial strength.
   The regulations scheduled to take effect next month mandate
higher octane levels in an effort to reduce vapor emissions.
   Reports of a continued slowdown in British crude oil production
stemming from problems in the North Sea also lifted the market,
analysts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
