<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1819EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Returning 1stLd-Writethru f0129 04-10 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Returning, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0129,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Once It Returns, Eastern Must Rebuild Gradually</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf pvs with status of ticketholders;
PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `Eastern was...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines isn't ready to soar back
immediately to major-carrier status, even once striking employees
agree to return to work at the crippled airline.
   Once Eastern's unions agree to return, it could take 10 days for
the airline to restore 80 percent of its pre-strike schedule of
1,040 flights daily, said Karen Ceremsak, an Eastern spokeswoman.
   Airliners idled for weeks must be ``de-pickled'' and moved from
Miami hangars to other airports; crew members must be ferried back
to their bases; laid-off non-union workers must be called back, if
they're even available; and myriad operations from food to fares to
computerized scheduling must be addressed before Eastern can fly
the bulk of its pre-strike schedule.
   ``You can't just go the same day you get the signal,'' Ms.
Ceremsak said. ``We have to make scheduling decisions and there are
a lot of details and all those little, behind-the-scenes things.''
   Last week, in announcing an agreement for a group led by Peter
V. Ueberroth to buy Eastern, Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo
said the airline could return to ``significant'' amounts of service
within 24 hours after its unions reached new work agreements with
the prospective new management.
   The group has offered the unions a 30 percent stake in Eastern
in return for cost-saving contract concessions.
   Sources said the Ueberroth group reached tentative agreements
with union representatives during weekend negotiations and on
Monday the parties met with U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland,
who must approve the sale.
   Lifland also would have to approve any plan governing would-be
passengers whose tickets became useless when Eastern was struck.
The value of the unused tickets is estimated at about $200 million
and the holders are considered unsecured creditors.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said he didn't know what effect
the completed sale of the airline would have on ticketholders,
adding it was probably premature to make any predictions about
ticketing.
   Eastern was virtually grounded after its pilots and flight
attendants unions began honoring a March 4 strike by its Machinists
and sought bankruptcy court protection from creditors on March 9.
   With a few thousand non-union employees and some 200 pilots, the
airline rebuilt its schedule to about 110 flights daily, focusing
on its Northeastern shuttle and Latin American routes.
   To return Eastern to full service will require preparation on
numerous fronts:
   _Less than 15 percent of Eastern's 250-plane fleet has been
flying and at least 50 planes have been ``pickled,'' or taken out
of service. Their engines, vents and intakes have been sealed to
prevent damage and Ms. Ceremsak estimated it requires 100 man-hours
per plane to return them to service. The other idled planes have
been undergoing maintenance checks.
   _Eastern's parked planes are all in Miami, Atlanta or New York.
Eastern served 118 cities before its strike and its planes and crew
members, most of them scattered to their homes, must be ferried to
the appropriate airports.
   _Catering contracts have to be resumed or obtained, fuel made
available and computers re-loaded with new scheduling information.
   _Some of the 3,400 pilots who haven't flown since March 4 may
have to undergo refresher training required by the Federal Aviation
Administration if they haven't made at least three takeoffs and
landings within 90 days. Ms. Ceremsak had no estimate of how many
pilots would need that training.
   The company also will have to replace non-striking workers who
went on to other jobs after being laid off when Eastern slashed its
flight schedule.
   ``We don't have any estimate on how many would choose to come
back to work,'' Ms. Ceremsak said of the nearly 12,000 non-union
employees, who include skycaps, clerical workers and reservations
agents.
   There also will be emotional issues.
   ``I think there's definitely going to be some bad feelings''
between union employees returning to work and management holdovers
and any others who worked said Rick Iacino, a Machinists union
general chairman. ``There's no way in hell you can stop people's
feelings.''
   Even once it is capable of flying its pre-strike schedule,
Eastern still must rebound from virtually no advance sales, weeks
of negative publicity and passenger defections to other airlines
that aggressively have been moving into Eastern's turf.
   Ms. Ceremsak said the airline likely would offer incentives such
as sharply discounted fares or buy-one, get-one-free ``companion''
ticket offers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
