<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1821EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-NCNB-C&amp;S     04-10 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NCNB-C&amp;S,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulator Says Review Of C&amp;S Takeover Bid Could Take Up To 18 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state banking commissioner said Monday it
could take up to 18 months _ three times the normal period _ to
review NCNB Inc.'s bid to acquire Citizens &amp; Southern Corp.
   C&amp;S officials said the long wait may kill the takeover attempt,
but NCNB said it feels there are no legal or regulatory impediments
to the merger.
   The C&amp;S board last week rejected a $2.4 billion stock exchange
offer that NCNB said would create the nation's sixth largest
banking company. NCNB reportedly has been preparing a new offer,
and the North Carolina banking company Monday dismissed the notion
that the proposed merger would require a lengthy review process.
   Georgia Banking Commissioner Jack Dunn released a statement
outlining the regulatory matters that could be involved in the
consideration of a NCNB-C&amp;S deal. Dunn said such a review would not
begin until the Department of Banking and Finance received a merger
application.
   ``Although a final decision would normally be reached within six
months, applications involving complex legal and technical issues
have required 12 to 18 months state-federal regulatory time,'' Dunn
said.
   C&amp;S officials seized upon Dunn's statement, saying it confirmed
their position that NCNB's bid has serious regulatory problems.
   ``Given the length of time for the state to resolve these
issues, and the uncertainty of a successful resolution, we think
NCNB's bid is dead,'' said C&amp;S Chairman Bennett A. Brown. ``It is
time for both of our institutions to get back to the business of
banking.''
   Ben Johnson, an attorney with Alston &amp; Bird, C&amp;S' corporate
counsel, said, ``Twelve to 18 months is a pretty long period of
time for a deal like this to be in limbo.''
   Johnson said the value of NCNB stock, during the period, ``can
be all over the place.''
   NCNB spokeswoman Lynn Easley said from her company's
headquarters in Charlotte, N.C., that Dunn broke no ground in his
statement and that he simply recited the law.
   ``NCNB is quite confident there are no legal or regulatory
impediments to the merger it has proposed to the Citizens &amp;
Southern Corp.,'' Ms. Easley said.
   Many of the items referred to in Dunn's statement are legal
matters that regulators would be required to consider in any bank
acquisition proposal. Some appeared to have particular relevance to
the NCNB-C&amp;S proposal and would require consultation with the
Georgia Department of Law, Dunn said.
   One such issue is whether NCNB's interests in Texas would
jeopardize its eligibility to acquire the Atlanta-based C&amp;S. NCNB
last year paid more than $200 million for a 20 percent stake in
First RepublicBank Corp. after the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
chose NCNB to manage and operate the financially ailing Texas
facility.
   Dunn said an acquisition may be rejected if it involves a
holding company that has its largest aggregate state deposit base
outside the 11-state Southern Region (which does not include Texas)
or has more than 20 percent of its aggregate deposit base outside
the region.
   There are exceptions to that provision, however, including the
presence of insolvent banks, Dunn said. The Texas bank's insolvency
at the time of NCNB's involvement could affect the interpretation
of the regulations.
   ``The statement released by (Dunn) simply restates the law and
regulations governing approval for interstate banking
acquisitions,'' Ms. Easley said. ``It raises no new legal or
regulatory issues.''
</TEXT>
