<FIRST>r f AM-US-TaiwanTrade     04-10 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Taiwan Trade,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Offers Credit to U.S. Exporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Taiwan's Export-Import Bank announced plans Monday
to provide loans to American companies to help encourage American
exports and reduce the huge U.S. trade deficit with the island.
   The loans are part of the Taiwan government's continuing
campaign to persuade Taiwanese firms to ``buy American,'' said K.W.
Kung, executive vice president of the Export-Import Bank of the
Republic of China on Taiwan.
   Kung said the bank has $200 million to lend to American
companies to help them export machinery and other goods and
services to Taiwan against deferred payment from purchasers.
   Kung plans to take his loan message to eight U.S. cities
stretching from Boston and New York to Seattle and Los Angeles.
   The unique effort to promote another country's exports stemmed
from concern in Taiwan that it would be targeted under new U.S.
trade laws directed against countries who persistently sell more to
the United States than they buy.
   Sheu Ke-Sheng, economic director of Taiwan's Washington mission,
said that within four years the surplus should be ``largely
eliminated, but to reduce it to zero is very difficult.''
   The U.S. trade deficit with Taiwan dropped from $18 to $14.1
billion from 1987 to 1988 and is expected to narrow by at least 10
percent a year, he said. Sheu said his government's own statistics
showed the Taiwan surplus dropped from $16 billion to $10.4 billion
the past year.
   U.S. trade with Taiwan started registering deficits in the early
1970s and since then the island has sent 15 ``Buy American''
purchasing missions to the United States, reduced import tariffs 16
times and, more recently, appreciated its currency 49 percent
against the U.S. dollar, Sheu said.
   Another round of tariff reductions will be announcd in a few
weeks and plans call for reducing Taiwan's average tariff, at 5.5
percent now comparable to that of the United States, to 3.5 percent
within four years, he added.
   Kung said U.S. exporters hoping to use Taiwan Export-Import Bank
credit may contact any of about 40 U.S. major and regional banks
authorized to borrow from his bank at 6.55 percent annual interest,
making for a relending rate to the exporter of approximately 8.3
percent.
</TEXT>
