<HEAD>Gulf Air To Buy Six Boeing, 12 Airbus Planes For $1 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 2nd graf pvs to CORRECT plane type to 767s
sted 727s, ADD Boeing comment; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Gulf Ai...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf Air said Monday it will spend $1
billion over the next five years to buy 18 aircraft from the
European consortium Airbus Industrie and the U.S. manuacturer
Boeing Co.
   Gulf Air spokesman Abdullah Abdel-Karim said the airliners will
include 12 Airbus A-320s and six Boeing 767s. Abdel-Karim said the
deal was being made on an optional basis, allowing the airline to
drop an order without ann liability to compensate the manufacturer.
   A spokesman for Seattle-based Boeing said it has held talks with
Gulf Air about purchasing 767s, but declined to confirm the deal.
   Gulf Air is owned by the governments of Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and
Abu Dhabi. The announcement came one day after Gulf Air's board met
in the Qatari capital of Doha.
   Abdel-Karim said that the 18 new jets will be delivered between
1990 and 1994. Gulf Air is currently spending $260 million as part
of a modernization program involving the lease of four Boeing
767-300s.
   The airline last week secured a $208 million loan from 22
international and regional banks to cover part of the modenization.
It expects to cover the balance of $52 million with a similar
credit from Japanese institutions.
   Abdel-Karim said that by June the airline will have nine
Tri-Stars, eight Boeing 737s and six Boeing 767-300s. The fleet
will increase to 40 to 42 aircraft by 1994, he added.
