<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FrontierReorganization     04-10 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frontier Reorganization,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Frontier Chapter 11 Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge has approved a
reorganization plan for defunct Frontier Airlines, which sought
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in August 1986 when it shut down
for good.
   The reorganization plan, approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Charles Matheson on Friday, allows about 500 of Frontier's former
employees and others to be paid 100 percent of court-approved
claims.
   Continental Airlines bought Denver-based Frontier's assets for
$119 million after negotiations to sell Frontier to United Airlines
fell through.
   Under the reorganization plan, Continental, a unit of Texas Air
Corp., would receive $20 million to $70 million after all other
creditors are paid. The total of the individual payments was not
released.
   ``There's no question this is a great deal for Continental,''
said Bill Waller, a Denver lawyer representing the claims of 57
former Frontier employees.
   Waller said his clients will receive ``substantial payments''
from Frontier and Continental. ``We're generally satisfied,'' he
said.
   Frontier's creditors gave nearly 95 percent approval to the plan
in a vote taken March 31. The plan calls for former employees and
others to receive either cash or a combination of cash and notes
for their allowed claims.
   Most of Frontier's former employees dropped their claims against
the airline two years ago in exchange for limited cash settlements
and jobs at Continental. Lawyers estimate that only about 500
employees are still owed money.
   The claims range from a few hundred dollars to ``a few hundred
thousand dollars for some former officers of Frontier,'' said Carl
Eklund, the lawyer who shepherded the reorganization plan through
the courts for Frontier and Continental.
   Matheson's approval of the reorganization plan does not settle
all claims against Frontier. The defunct airline still faces more
than $268 million in outstanding claims, although that amount is
expected to be trimmed substantially, said Eklund.
   Waller speculated that when all the claims are paid under the
reorganization plan, Continental's take could reach $100 million.
He said that does not count the route structure, the planes and the
employees Continental also received when it purchased Frontier's
assets.
   Others involved in the case, however, estimated Continental
would receive $20 million to $70 million.
</TEXT>
