<FIRST>u f AM-Drexel     04-10 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deadline Apparently Passes for Drexel-SEC Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecuror indicated Monday that a
deadline that could jeopardize Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s
landmark criminal plea deal with the government passed without an
extension.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Bruce Baird said there was no written
agreement extending the Monday deadline for the Wall Street
investment firm to settle separate civil securities fraud charges
filed by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Baird, who heads the office's securities and commodities fraud
unit, had said the government did not plan a lengthy extension of
the deadline. Apparently none was made Monday.
   ``The only letter that there is the letter that extends the
deadline until April 10,'' Baird said. ``There isn't any other
writing or agreement.''
   Baird declined to say whether that meant the deadline indeed had
passed, but he said, ``Nothing formal has changed at all.''
   He also refused to say what action the Manhattan U.S. attorney's
office might take if no pact was reached by the deadline.
   Failure to reach agreement could nullify the U.S. attorney's
office's plea deal with Drexel and raise the possibility of a far
more serious indictment on fraud and racketeering charges.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said he did not know whether a
deadline had been extended, but added: ``We're still conversing,
we're still negotiating.''
   SEC officials and Drexel attorneys were reported to have left
their offices for the day and could not be reached for comment
Monday evening.
   Settling civil charges including insider trading brought by the
SEC last September was a precondition for Drexel's criminal plea
bargain three months later. The firm agreed to plead guilty to six
felonies and pay a record $650 million in fines and restitution.
   Officials familiar with the talks indicated earlier Monday that
an agreement between the SEC and Drexel was imminent, possibly by
the end of the day. But no announcement came from any quarter.
   Drexel and the SEC initially agreed to complete their
negotiations Jan. 30. That deadline was extended several times by
mutual consent of prosecutors and Drexel as talks deadlocked.
   The U.S. attorney's office governs the terms of the SEC-Drexel
talks.
   One of the major snags in the talks reportedly had been an SEC
demand that Drexel fire Michael Milken, who took a leave of absence
after he and two others were charged with 98 counts of racketeering
and securities fraud. Drexel has a policy that all indicted
employees must be placed on leave.
   Milken pleaded innocent Friday to the charges and was released
pending negotiations on setting bond. On Monday, U.S. District
Judge Kimba Wood rescheduled from Tuesday to Wednesday a hearing on
an expected agreement between prosecutors and Milken's lawyers on
posting a bond.
   The government reportedly sought under racketeering laws to have
Milken post a $1 billion bond to avoid pretrial restraints on
assets that may be seized upon conviction.
   But a bond arrangement could allow Milken to place a substantial
amount of money in an account to be monitored by the government
rather than posting the bond. Baird and lawyers for Milken declined
to comment Monday on the bond talks.
</TEXT>
